\n\n#[[Zhang Desheng]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u5fb7\u751f}}): 1949\u20131954\n#[[Zhang Zhongliang]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u4ef2\u826f}}): 1954\u20131961\n#[[Wang Feng (politician)|Wang Feng]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6c6a\u950b}}): 1961\u20131966\n#[[Hu Jizong]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u80e1\u7ee7\u5b97}}): 1966\u20131967\n#[[Xian Henghan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51bc\u6052\u6c49}}): 1970\u20131977\n#[[Song Ping]] ({{lang|zh|\u5b8b\u5e73}}): 1977\u20131981\n#[[Feng Jixin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51af\u7eaa\u65b0}}): 1981\u20131983\n#[[Li Ziqi (politician)|Li Ziqi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u674e\u5b50\u5947}}): 1983\u20131990\n#[[Gu Jinchi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u987e\u91d1\u6c60}}): 1990\u20131993\n#[[Yan Haiwang]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u960e\u6d77\u65fa}}): 1993\u20131998\n#[[Sun Ying]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b59\u82f1}}): 1998\u20132001\n#[[Song Zhaosu]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b8b\u7167\u8083}}): 2001\u20132003\n#[[Su Rong]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u82cf\u8363}}): 2003\u20132007\n#[[Lu Hao (born 1947)|Lu Hao]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9646\u6d69}}): April 2007 \u2212 December 2011\n#[[Wang Sanyun]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u738b\u4e09\u8fd0}}): December 2011 \u2212 March 2017\n#[[Lin Duo]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6797\u94ce}}): March 2017 \u2212 incumbent\n\n'''Governors of Gansu''': The Governorship of Gansu is the second highest-ranking official within Gansu, behind the Secretary of the CPC Gansu Committee.<ref name=xinhua/> The governor is responsible for all issues related to [[economics]], [[personnel]], political initiatives, the [[Environmental policy|environment]] and the [[Foreign policy|foreign affairs]] of the province.<ref name=xinhua/> The Governor is appointed by the [[Gansu Provincial People's Congress]], which is the province's [[legislative]] body.<ref name=xinhua/>\n\n#[[Wang Shitai]] ({{lang|zh|\u738b\u4e16\u6cf0}}): 1949\u20131950\n#[[Deng Baoshan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9093\u5b9d\u59d7}}): 1950\u20131967\n#[[Xian Henghan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51bc\u6052\u6c49}}): 1967\u20131977\n#[[Song Ping]] ({{lang|zh|\u5b8b\u5e73}}): 1977\u20131979\n#[[Feng Jixin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51af\u7eaa\u65b0}}): 1979\u20131981\n#[[Li Dengying]] ({{lang|zh|\u674e\u767b\u701b}}): 1981\u20131983\n#[[Chen Guangyi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9648\u5149\u6bc5}}): 1983\u20131986\n#[[Jia Zhijie]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8d3e\u5fd7\u6770}}): 1986\u20131993\n#[[Yan Haiwang]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u960e\u6d77\u65fa}}): 1993\n#[[Zhang Wule]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u543e\u4e50}}): 1993\u20131996\n#[[Sun Ying]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b59\u82f1}}): 1996\u20131998\n#[[Song Zhaosu]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b8b\u7167\u8083}}): 1998\u20132001\n#[[Lu Hao (born 1947)|Lu Hao]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9646\u6d69}}): 2001\u20132006\n#[[Xu Shousheng]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f90\u5b88\u76db}}): January 2007 \u2013 July 2010<ref name=xinhua>{{cite news |title=Xu Shousheng re-elected governor of northwest China's Gansu Province |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-01/27/content_7502167.htm |work= [[Xinhua]] |date=27 January 2008 |accessdate=23 February 2008}}</ref>\n#[[Liu Weiping]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5218\u4f1f\u5e73}}): July 2010 \u2013 April 2016\n#[[Lin Duo]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6797\u94ce}}): April 2016 \u2013 April 2017\n#[[Tang Renjian]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5510\u4ec1\u5065}}): April 2017\u2212incumbent\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Lanzhou-rio-amarillo-baita-shan-d03.jpg|thumbnail|right|The Yellow River in Lanzhou seen from the park of the White Pagoda.]]\nAgricultural production includes [[cotton]], [[linseed oil]], [[maize]], [[melons]] (such as the [[honeydew melon]], known locally as the [[Bailan melon]] or \"Wallace\" due to its introduction by US [[Vice president of the United States|vice president]] [[Henry A. Wallace]]),<ref>[http://www.baike.com/wiki/%E7%99%BD%E5%85%B0%E7%93%9C Hudong.com] This simplified Chinese page discusses how the seeds were brought to China, the connection to Wallace, dates, etc.</ref> [[millet]], and [[wheat]].  Gansu is known as a source for wild medicinal herbs which are used in [[Chinese medicine]]. However, pollution by heavy metals, such as [[cadmium poisoning|cadmium]] in irrigation water, has resulted in the poisoning of many acres of agricultural land. The extent and nature of the heavy metal pollution is considered a state secret.<ref name=Caixin030113>{{cite news|title=The Poison Eaters of Gansu Province: Pollution is not a problem some western farmers can choose to ignore, as many say they have suffered from chronic bone pains for decades|url=http://english.caixin.com/2013-03-01/100496199.html|accessdate=1 March 2013|newspaper=Caixin|date=1 March 2013|author=Liu Hongqiao}}</ref>\n\nHowever, most of Gansu's economy is based on [[mining]] and the extraction of [[minerals]], especially [[rare earth elements]].  The province has significant deposits of [[antimony]], [[chromium]], [[coal]], [[cobalt]], [[copper]], [[fluorite]], [[gypsum]], [[iridium]], [[iron]], [[lead]], [[limestone]], [[Mercury (element)|mercury]], [[mirabilite]], [[nickel]], [[crude oil]], [[platinum]], [[troilite]], [[tungsten]], and [[zinc]] among others.  The oil fields at Yumen and Changqing are considered significant.\n\nGansu has China's largest nickel deposits accounting for over 90% of China's total nickel reserves.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nIndustries other than mining include [[electricity generation]], [[petrochemicals]], oil exploration machinery, and building materials.\n\nAccording to some sources, the province is also a center of China's nuclear industry.\n\nDespite recent growth in Gansu and the booming economy in the rest of China, Gansu is still considered to be one of the poorest provinces in China. Its nominal GDP for 2017 was about 767.7 billion yuan (US$113.70 billion) and per capita of 29,326&nbsp;RMB (US$4,343). Tourism has been a bright spot in contributing to Gansu's overall economy. As mentioned below, Gansu offers a wide variety of choices for national and international tourists.\n\nAs stipulated in the country's 12th Five Year Plan, the local government of Gansu hopes to grow the provinces GDP by 10% annually by focusing investments on five pillar industries: renewable energy, coal, chemicals, nonferrous metals, pharmaceuticals and services.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n===Economic and technological development zones===\nThe following economic and technological zones are situated in Gansu:\n*Lanzhou National Economic and Technological Development Zone was established in 1993, located in the center of Lanzhou Anning District. The zone has a planned area of {{convert|9.53|km2|abbr=on}}. 17 colleges, 11 scientific research institutions, 21 large and medium-size companies and other 1735 enterprises have been set up in the zone. Main industries include textile mills, rubber, fertilizer plants, oil refinery, petrochemical, machinery, and metallurgical industry.<ref>[http://rightsite.asia/en/industrial-zone/lanzhou-economic-technology-development-zone/ RightSite.asia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611124453/http://rightsite.asia/en/industrial-zone/lanzhou-economic-technology-development-zone |date=11 June 2010 }}, Lanzhou Economic and Technological Development Zone</ref>\n*Lanzhou New & Hi-Tech Industrial Development Zone, Lanzhou Hi-Tech Industrial Development Zone, one of the first 27 national hi-tech industrial development zones, was established in 1998 covering more than {{convert|10|km2|abbr=on}}. It is expected to expand another {{convert|19|km2|abbr=on}}. The zone mainly focuses on Biotechnology, chemical industry, building decoration materials and information technology.<ref>[http://rightsite.asia/en/industrial-zone/lanzhou-hi-tech-industrial-development-zone/ RightSite.asia] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120717180648/http://rightsite.asia/en/industrial-zone/lanzhou-hi-tech-industrial-development-zone/ |date=17 July 2012 }}, Lanzhou Hi-Tech Industrial Development Zone</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:Lanzhou-037.JPG|thumb|[[Lanzhou]] city]]\n{{Historical populations\n|title       = Historical population\n|footnote    = Ningxia Province/AR was part of Gansu Province until 1929 and 1954\u20131958.\n|1912<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:1912\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3|url=http://www.ier.hit-u.ac.jp/COE/Japanese/discussionpapers/DP97.9/fhyo2.html|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref>  |4,990,000\n|1928<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:1928\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3|url=http://www.ier.hit-u.ac.jp/COE/Japanese/discussionpapers/DP97.9/fhyo3.htm|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref> |6,281,000\n|1936\u201337<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:1936\u201337\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3|url=http://www.ier.hit-u.ac.jp/COE/Japanese/discussionpapers/DP97.9/fhyo4.htm|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref> |6,716,000\n|1947<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:1947\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3|url=http://www.ier.hit-u.ac.jp/COE/Japanese/discussionpapers/DP97.9/fhyo5.htm|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref> |7,091,000\n|1954<ref name=\"census1954\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16767.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\u5173\u4e8e\u7b2c\u4e00\u6b21\u5168\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3\u8c03\u67e5\u767b\u8bb0\u7ed3\u679c\u7684\u516c\u62a5 |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805174810/http://www.stats.gov.cn/TJGB/RKPCGB/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16767.htm |archivedate=5 August 2009  }}</ref> |12,928,102\n|1964<ref name=\"census1964\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16768.htm |script-title=zh:\u7b2c\u4e8c\u6b21\u5168\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u7ed3\u679c\u7684\u51e0\u9879\u4e3b\u8981\u7edf\u8ba1\u6570\u5b57 |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914173158/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16768.htm |archivedate=14 September 2012  }}</ref> |12,630,569\n|1982<ref name=\"census1982\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16769.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\u5173\u4e8e\u4e00\u4e5d\u516b\u4e8c\u5e74\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u4e3b\u8981\u6570\u5b57\u7684\u516c\u62a5 |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510075429/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16769.htm |archivedate=10 May 2012  }}</ref> |19,569,261\n|1990<ref name=\"census1990\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16772.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\u5173\u4e8e\u4e00\u4e5d\u4e5d\u3007\u5e74\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u4e3b\u8981\u6570\u636e\u7684\u516c\u62a5 |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619002216/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020404_16772.htm |archivedate=19 June 2012  }}</ref> |22,371,141\n|2000<ref name=\"census2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020331_15435.htm |script-title=zh:\u73b0\u5c062000\u5e74\u7b2c\u4e94\u6b21\u5168\u56fd\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u5feb\u901f\u6c47\u603b\u7684\u4eba\u53e3\u5730\u533a\u5206\u5e03\u6570\u636e\u516c\u5e03\u5982\u4e0b |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829052024/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjgb/rkpcgb/qgrkpcgb/t20020331_15435.htm |archivedate=29 August 2012  }}</ref> |25,124,282\n|2010<ref name=\"census2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20110429_402722516.htm |title=Communiqu\u00e9 of the National Bureau of Statistics of People's Republic of China on Major Figures of the 2010 Population Census |publisher=[[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727021210/http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20110429_402722516.htm |archivedate=27 July 2013  }}</ref> |25,575,254\n}}\nGansu province is home to 30,711,287 people. 73% of the population is rural. Gansu is 92% [[Han Chinese|Han]] and also has [[Hui people|Hui]], [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]], [[Dongxiang people|Dongxiang]], [[Tu (ethnic group)|Tu]], [[Yugur]], [[Bonans|Bonan]], [[Mongols|Mongolian]], [[Salar people|Salar]], and [[kazakhs|Kazakh]] minorities. Gansu province's community of Chinese [[Hui people|Hui]] Muslims was bolstered by Hui Muslims resettled from [[Shaanxi]] province during the [[Dungan Revolt (1862\u201377)|Dungan Revolt]]. Gansu is also a historical home, along with [[Shaanxi]], of the [[Dungan language|dialect]] of the [[Dungan people|Dungans]], who migrated to [[Central Asia]]. The southwestern corner of Gansu is home to a large [[Tibetan people|ethnic Tibetan]] population.\n\n== Languages ==\nMost of the inhabitants of Gansu speak dialects of Northern [[Mandarin Chinese]]. On the border areas of Gansu one might encounter [[Tu language|Tu]], [[Amdo|Amdo Tibetan]], [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], and the [[Kazakh language]]. Most of the minorities also speak Chinese.\n\n== Culture ==\n{{see also|Music of Gansu}}\nThe cuisine of Gansu is based on the staple crops grown there: [[wheat]], [[barley]], [[millet]], [[beans]], and [[sweet potatoes]].  Within China, Gansu is known for its [[lamian]] (pulled noodles), and [[Chinese Islamic cuisine|Muslim restaurants]] which feature authentic Gansu cuisine.\n\n===Religion===\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Gansu (2012)<ref name=\"CFPS2012\">{{cite web |publisher=[[Chinese Academy of Social Sciences]] |trans-title=China Family Panel Studies 2012 |url=http://iwr.cass.cn/zjwh/201403/W020140303370398758556.pdf |script-title=zh:\u5f53\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd\u5b97\u6559\u72b6\u51b5\u62a5\u544a\u2014\u2014\u57fa\u4e8eCFPS\uff082012\uff09\u8c03\u67e5\u6570\u636e |language=zh |access-date=7 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809051625/http://iwr.cass.cn/zjwh/201403/W020140303370398758556.pdf |archive-date=9 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}. p. 013</ref>\n|label1 = Non religious and [[Chinese folk religion|traditional faiths]]\n|value1 = 88\n|color1 = Honeydew\n|label2 = [[Buddhism in China|Buddhism]]\n|value2 = 8.2\n|color2 = Yellow\n|label3 = [[Islam in China|Islam]]\n|value3 = 3.4\n|color3 = Green\n|label4 = [[Protestantism in China|Protestantism]]\n|value4 = 0.4\n|color4 = DodgerBlue\n|label5 = [[Catholicism]]\n|value5 = 0.1\n|color5 = DarkOrchid\n}}\nAccording to a 2012 survey<ref name=\"CFPS2012\"/> only around 12% of the population of Gansu belongs to organised religions, the largest groups being [[Buddhism in China|Buddhists]] with 8.2%, followed by [[Islam in China|Muslims]] with 3.4%, [[Protestantism in China|Protestants]] with 0.4% and [[Catholicism in China|Catholic]] with 0.1% (in total, as of 2012 Christians comprise 0.5% of the population, decreasing from 1.02% in 2004<ref>China General Social Survey 2009, Chinese Spiritual Life Survey (CSLS) 2007. Report by: [https://baylor-ir.tdl.org/baylor-ir/bitstream/handle/2104/9326/WANG-THESIS-2015.pdf?sequence=1 Xiuhua Wang (2015, p. 15)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925123928/https://baylor-ir.tdl.org/baylor-ir/bitstream/handle/2104/9326/WANG-THESIS-2015.pdf?sequence=1 |date=25 September 2015 }}</ref>) Around 88% of the population may be either irreligious or involved in [[Chinese folk religion|worship of nature deities]], Buddhism, [[Confucianism]], Taoism, and [[Chinese salvationist religions|folk religious sects]].\n\nMuslim restaurants are known as \"qingzhen restaurants\" (\"pure truth restaurants\"), and feature typical Chinese dishes, but without any pork products, and instead an emphasis on [[lamb and mutton]]. Gansu has many works of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] art, including the [[Maijishan Grottoes]]. Dunhuang was a major centre of Buddhism in the [[Middle Ages]].\n{|\n|-\n|<gallery mode=\"packed\" style=\"font-size:88%; line-height:130%\">\nFile:Lanzhou Chanyuan 2013.12.29 11-47-46.jpg|Main hall of a [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] temple of [[Lanzhou]].\nFile:Lanzhou Fu Chenghuang Miao 2013.12.29 11-19-25.jpg|Temple of the [[Chenghuangshen]] (City God) of Lanzhou.\nFile:5855-Linxia-Yu-Baba-Gongbei-and-Nanhua-Amituo-Fo-Temple.jpg|Nanhua Amituo Fo Temple of Chinese Buddhism seen on a hill above the roofs of the Yu Baba Gongbei, a [[Sufism|Sufi]] shrine.\nFile:\u62c9\u535c\u695e\u5bfa\u50e7\u820d\u4fef\u77b0.jpg|Labrang Monastery of [[Tibetan Buddhism]] in [[Gannan Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture|Gannan]].\nFile:5913-Linxia-County-Xihe-township-village-temple.jpg|Village temple in [[Linxia County]].\nFile:\u4f0f\u7fb2\u5e99\u724c\u574a.jpg|Arch of the Temple of [[Fuxi]] in [[Tianshui]].\n</gallery>\n|}\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Yulin Cave 3 w wall Manjusri (Western Xia).jpg|thumb|A painting of the Buddhist [[Manjushri]], from the [[Yulin Caves]] of Gansu, [[Tangut people|Tangut]]-led [[Western Xia]] dynasty (1038\u20131227 AD)]]\n[[File:Han Dynasty Granary west of Dunhuang.jpg|thumb|These [[rammed earth]] ruins of a [[granary]] in Hecang Fortress ({{zh|s=\u6cb3\u4ed3\u57ce\uff1b |p=H\u00e9c\u0101ngch\u00e9ng}}), located ~11 km (7 miles) northeast of the Western-Han-era [[Yumen Pass]], were built during the [[Western Han]] (202 BC \u2013 9 AD) and significantly rebuilt during the [[Western Jin]] (280\u2013316 AD).<ref>Wang Xudang, [[Li Zuixiong]], and Zhang Lu (2010). \"Condition, Conservation, and Reinforcement of the Yumen Pass and Hecang Earthen Ruins Near Dunhuang\", in Neville Agnew (ed), ''Conservation of Ancient Sites on the Silk Road: Proceedings of the Second International Conference on the Conservation of Grotto Sites, Mogao Grottoes, Dunhuang, People's Republic of China, 28 June \u2013 3 July 2004'', 351\u2013357. Los Angeles: The Getty Conservation Institute, J. Paul Getty Trust. {{ISBN|978-1-60606-013-1}}, pp 351\u2013352.</ref>]]\n\n===Jiayuguan Pass of the Great Wall===\n{{main|Jiayuguan Pass}}\nJiayuguan Pass, in Jiayuguan city, is the largest and most intact pass, or entrance, of the [[Great Wall of China|Great Wall]]. Jiayuguan Pass was built in the early [[Ming dynasty]], somewhere around the year 1372. It was built near an oasis that was then on the extreme western edge of China. Jiayuguan Pass was the first pass on the west end of the great wall so it earned the name \"The First And Greatest Pass Under Heaven\".\n\nAn extra brick is said to rest on a ledge over one of the gates.  One legend holds that the official in charge asked the designer to calculate how many bricks would be used. The designer gave him the number and when the project was finished, only one brick was left. It was put on the top of the pass as a symbol of commemoration.  Another account holds that the building project was assigned to a military manager and an architect.  The architect presented the manager with a requisition for the total number of bricks that he would need.  When the manager found out that the architect had not asked for any extra bricks, he demanded that the architect make some provision for unforeseen circumstances.  The architect, taking this as an insult to his planning ability, added a single extra brick to the request.  When the gate was finished, the single extra brick was, in fact, extra and was left on the ledge over the gate.<ref name=\"CNTOLEGEND\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnto.org/iconic/the-great-wall-in-gansu/|title=The Great Wall in Gansu|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Mogao Grottoes===\n{{main|Mogao Caves}}\nThe Mogao Grottoes near [[Dunhuang]] have a collection of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] art. Originally there were a thousand grottoes, but now only 492 cave temples remain. Each temple has a large statue of a [[Buddha (general)|buddha]] or [[bodhisattva]] and paintings of religious scenes. In 336&nbsp;AD, a monk named Le Zun (Lo-tsun) came near Echoing Sand Mountain, when he had a [[Vision (spirituality)|vision]]. He started to carve the first grotto. During the [[Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period|Five Dynasties period]] they ran out of room on the cliff and could not build any more grottoes.\n\n===Silk Road and Dunhuang City===\n[[File:Cernuschi Museum 20060812 156.jpg|thumb|200px|A terracotta warrior from Gansu, with traces of polychrome and gold, from the [[Tang dynasty]] (618\u2013907)]]\nThe historic [[Silk Road]] starts in [[Chang'an]] and goes to [[Constantinople]]. On the way merchants would go to Dunhuang in Gansu. In Dunhuang they would get fresh camels, food and guards for the journey around the dangerous [[Taklamakan Desert]]. Before departing Dunhuang they would pray to the Mogao Grottoes for a safe journey, if they came back alive they would thank the gods at the grottoes. Across the desert they would form a train of camels to protect themselves from thieving bandits. The next stop, [[Kashgar|Kashi (Kashgar)]], was a welcome sight to the merchants. At Kashi most would trade and go back and the ones who stayed would eat fruit and trade their [[Bactrian camel]]s for [[Dromedary|single humped]] ones. After Kashi they would keep going until they reached their next destination.\n\nLocated about {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} southwest of the city, the [[Crescent Lake (Dunhuang)|Crescent Lake]] or Yueyaquan is an oasis and popular spot for tourists seeking respite from the heat of the desert. Activities includes camel and 4x4 rides.\n\n===Silk Route Museum===\n{{main|Silk Route Museum}}\nThe Silk Route Museum is located in [[Jiuquan]] along the [[Silk Road]], a trading route connecting [[Rome]] to China, used by [[Marco Polo]]. It is also built over the tomb of the [[Western Liang (Sixteen Kingdoms)|Western Liang]] King.<ref name=\"touristlink\">[http://www.touristlink.com/china/silk-route-museum/overview.html Silk Route Museum China Tourist Information] Tourist Link.</ref>\n\n===Bingling Temple===\n{{main|Bingling Temple}}\nBingling Temple, or Bingling Grottoes, is a [[Buddhist]] cave complex in a canyon along the [[Yellow River]]. Begun in 420&nbsp;AD during the [[Jin dynasty (265\u2013420)|Jin dynasty]], the site contains dozens of caves and caverns filled with outstanding examples of carvings, sculpture, and frescoes. The great Maitreya Buddha is more than 27 meters tall and is similar in style to the great Buddhas that once lined the cliffs of [[Buddhas of Bamiyan|Bamiyan]], Afghanistan. Access to the site is by boat from [[Yongjing County|Yongjing]] in the summer or fall. There is no other access point.\n\n===Labrang Monastery===\n{{main|Labrang Monastery}}\nLabrang Tashikyil Monastery is located in [[Xiahe|Xiahe County]], [[Gannan Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture]], located in the southern part of Gansu, and part of the traditional Tibetan province of [[Amdo]]. It is one of the six major monasteries of the [[Gelukpa]] tradition of [[Tibetan Buddhism]] in [[Tibet]], and the most important one in Amdo. Built in 1710, it is headed by the Jamyang-zhaypa. It has 6 ''dratsang'' (colleges), and houses over sixty thousand religious texts and other works of literature as well as other cultural artifacts.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Colleges and universities===\n{{see also|List of universities and colleges in Gansu}}\n*[[Lanzhou University]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u5170\u5dde\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Northwest Normal University]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u897f\u5317\u5e08\u8303\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Lanzhou University of Technology]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u5170\u5dde\u7406\u5de5\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Lanzhou Jiaotong University]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u5170\u5dde\u4ea4\u901a\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Northwest University of Nationalities]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u897f\u5317\u6c11\u65cf\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Gansu Agricultural University]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u7518\u8083\u519c\u4e1a\u5927\u5b66}})\n*[[Lanzhou City University]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u5170\u5dde\u57ce\u5e02\u5b66\u9662}})\n*[[Gansu Political Science and Law Institute]], Lanzhou ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u7518\u8083\u653f\u6cd5\u5b66\u9662}})\n*[[Gansu University of Technology]]\n*[[Lanzhou Commercial College]]\n*[[Lanzhou Polytechnic College]]\n*[[Northwest Minority University]]\n*[[Tianshui Normal College]] (Tianshui)\n*[[Longdong College]] (Qingyang)\n\n==Natural resources==\n[[File:\u7518\u8083 \u8352\u5c71\u4e0e\u6c83\u571f - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Fertile fields near [[Wuwei, Gansu|Wuwei]]]]\n\n===Land===\n*{{convert|166400|km2}} grassland\n*{{convert|46700|km2}} mountain slopes suitable for livestock breeding\n*{{convert|46200|km2}} forests (standing timber reserves of {{convert|0.2|km3}})\n*{{convert|35300|km2}} cultivated land ({{convert|1400|m2}} per capita)\n*{{convert|66600|km2}} wasteland suitable for forestation\n*{{convert|10000|km2}} wasteland suitable for farming\n\n===Minerals===\nThree thousand deposits of 145 different minerals. Ninety-four minerals have been found and ascertained, including nickel, cobalt, platinum, [[selenium]], casting clay, finishing serpentine, whose reserves are the largest in China.{{citation needed|date=May 2009}} Gansu has advantages in getting{{clarify|date=January 2020}} nickel, zinc, cobalt, platinum, iridium, copper, [[barite]], and [[magnesite|baudisserite]].\n\n===Energy===\nAmong Gansu's most important sources of energy are its water resources: the Yellow River and other inland river drainage basins. Gansu is placed ninth among China's provinces in annual hydropower potential and water discharge. Gansu produces 17.24 gigawatts of hydropower a year. Twenty-nine hydropower stations have been constructed in Gansu, altogether(?) capable of generating 30 gigawatts. Gansu has an estimated coal reserve of 8.92 billion tons and petroleum reserve of 700 million tons.\n\nThere is also good potential for wind and solar power development. The [[Gansu Wind Farm]] project \u2013 already producing 7.965GW in 2015<ref name=\"busitza\">{{cite web|title=South Africa's biggest wind farms vs the world|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/energy/93743/south-africas-biggest-wind-farms-vs-the-world/|publisher=BusinessTech|accessdate=22 November 2016|date=22 July 2015}}</ref> \u2013 is expected to achieve 20GW by 2020, at which time it will likely become the world's biggest collective windfarm.\n\nIn November 2017 an agreement between the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] and Gansu government was announced, to site and begin operations of a [[molten salt reactor]] pilot project in the province by 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cas.cn/yw/201711/t20171110_4621454.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u79d1\u9662\u4e0e\u7518\u8083\u7701\u7b7e\u7f72\u948d\u57fa\u7194\u76d0\u5806\u6838\u80fd\u7cfb\u7edf\u9879\u76ee\u6218\u7565\u5408\u4f5c\u6846\u67b6\u534f\u8bae----\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662 |publisher=[[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] |date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Flora and fauna===\nGansu has 659 species of wild animals.<ref>[http://www.gansu.gov.cn/en/BasicDetail.asp?CID=50 Gansu.gov.cn] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091115095308/http://www.gansu.gov.cn/en/BasicDetail.asp?CID=50 |date=15 November 2009 }}</ref> It has twenty-four rare animals which are under a state protection.\n\nGansu's mammals include some of the world's most charismatic: the [[giant panda]], [[golden monkey]]s, [[lynx]], [[snow leopard]]s, [[sika deer]], [[musk deer]], and the [[Bactrian camel]].\n\nAmong zoologists who study [[Mole (animal)|mole]]s, the [[Gansu mole]] is of great interest.  For a reason that can only be speculated, it is taxologically a [[Scalopini|New World mole]] living among [[Talpinae|Old Word moles]]; that is to say an American mole living in a sea of Euro-Asians.\n\nGansu is home to 441 [[species]] of [[bird]]s; it is a center of [[endemism]] and home to many species and [[subspecies]] which occur nowhere else in the world.\n\nGansu is China's second-largest producer of medicinal plants and herbs, including some produced nowhere else, such as the [[hairy asiabell]] root, [[fritillary]] bulb, and [[Chinese caterpillar fungus]].\n\n{{wide image|Daxia-River-Valley-panorama-5902+5903+5904+5905+5906.jpg|900px|Panorama of the lower [[Daxia River]] valley in the northeast of the [[Linxia County]], and the [[loess plateau]] flanking in, cut by a [[canyon]]||none}}\n\n==Environment==\n\n=== Natural disasters ===\n{{see also|1920 Haiyuan earthquake}}\nOn 16 December 1920, Gansu witnessed the deadliest landslide ever recorded. A series of landslides, triggered by a single earthquake, accounted for most of the 180,000 people killed in the event.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Guinness world records 2014|last=Glenday|first=Craig|publisher=The Jim Pattison Group|year=2013|isbn=978-1-908843-15-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_r3e7/page/015 015]|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_r3e7/page/015}}</ref>\n\n=== Anti-desertification project ===\n\nThe [[Asian Development Bank]] is working with the [[State Forestry Administration of China]] on the [[Silk Road Ecosystem Restoration project]], designed to prevent degradation and desertification in Gansu. It is estimated to cost up to US$150 million.\n\n== Space launch center ==\nThe [[Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center]], located in the Gobi desert, is named after the city of [[Jiuquan]], Gansu, the nearest city, although the center itself is in the [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Huangyangchuan]]\n* [[List of prisons in Gansu]]\n* [[Major national historical and cultural sites (Gansu)|Major national historical and cultural sites in Gansu]]\n* [[Silk Road transmission of Buddhism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Gansu}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.gansu.gov.cn Gansu Government Website]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Kan-suh |short=x}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Gansu\n|North     = {{flag|Govi-Altai}}, {{flag|Mongolia}}\n|Northeast = [[Inner Mongolia]]\n|East      = [[Ningxia]]\n|Southeast = [[Shaanxi]]\n|South     = [[Sichuan]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Qinghai]]\n|Northwest = [[Xinjiang]]\n}}\n{{Gansu topics}}\n{{Gansu}}\n{{Province-level divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Gansu| ]]\n[[Category:Provinces of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Inner Asia]]\n[[Category:Mongolia]]\n[[Category:Western China]]\n[[Category:1666 establishments in China]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gansu"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Venezuela}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Venezuela.svg\n| legend1         = States with confirmed (red) cases (as of 18 April 2020) {{legend|#C9C9C9|No confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#FDD6C4|1-5 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FCA486|6-10 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FB7050|11-30 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#EA372A|31-50 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BA1419|51-100 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#67000D|\u2265101 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Venezuela]]\n| first_case      = [[Miranda (state)|Miranda State]]\n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[China]]<br>[[Spain]]<br>[[United States]]<br>[[Italy]]<br>[[Colombia]]\n| confirmed_cases = 285<ref name=efectococuyo20a/> <small>(as of 20 April 2020)</small>\n| recovery_cases  = 117<ref name=efectococuyo19a/> <small>(as of 19 April 2020)</small> \n| deaths          = 10<ref name=efectococuyo20a/> <small>(as of 20 April 2020)</small>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\n{{Crisis in Bolivarian Venezuela short}}\n\nAs part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing worldwide pandemic]],  the first two patients with [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[Venezuela]] were confirmed on 13 March 2020;<ref name=\"FirstCases\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/regimen-de-maduro-confirma-dos-primeros-casos-de-coronavirus-120128|title=R\u00e9gimen de Maduro confirma dos primeros casos de coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|website=NTN24.com|language=es|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PH\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-confirms-coronavirus-cases-amid-public-health-concerns-idUSKBN2102DR|title=Venezuela confirms coronavirus cases amid public health concerns|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> the first death was reported on 26 March.<ref name=Reutersfirstdeath>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-death-idUSKBN21D3Q3|title=Venezuela confirms first coronavirus death: official|date=26 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the first record of a patient claiming to have symptoms of coronavirus disease dates back to 29 February 2020,<ref name=efectococuyo29m>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/tercer-fallecido-por-coronavirus-en-el-pais-era-un-taxista-de-antimano/|title=Tercer fallecido por coronavirus en el pa\u00eds era un taxista de Ant\u00edmano|work=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|author=Mar\u00eda Victoria Ferm\u00edn|date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> with government officials suspecting that the first person carrying the virus could have entered the country as early as 25 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/de-marzo-a-febrero-versiones-sobre-la-llegada-del-coronavirus-a-venezuela/|title=De marzo a febrero: versiones sobre la llegada del coronavirus a Venezuela|last=Souquett Gil|first=Mariana|date=1 April 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nVenezuela is particularly vulnerable to the wider effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] because of its [[Crisis in Venezuela|ongoing socioeconomic and political crisis]] causing [[Shortages in Venezuela|massive shortages]] of food staples and basic necessities, including medical supplies. The [[Venezuelan refugee crisis|mass emigration]] of Venezuelan doctors has also caused chronic staff shortages in hospitals.<ref name=\"Healthcare\" />\n\nTo prevent the spread of the disease into Venezuela, the governments of [[Brazil]] and [[Colombia]] temporarily closed [[Borders of Venezuela|their borders with Venezuela]].<ref name=\":ET\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"RBR\" />\n\n==Background==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Venezuela medical cases chart}}In January, Venezuela's [[Ministry of Communication and Information (Venezuela)|Ministry of Popular Power for Health]] announced that the Rafael Rangel National Institute of Hygiene ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]: Instituto Nacional de Higiene Rafael Rangel) in [[Caracas]] would act as the observatory for non-influenza respiratory viruses, including coronaviruses in humans. It is the only health institution in the country with the ability to diagnose respiratory viruses and to operate logistically across the [[States of Venezuela|23 states, the Capital District and the Federal Dependencies]] of Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/salud/venezuela-sin-kits-de-diagnostico-ni-condiciones-optimas-para-enfrentar-el-nuevo-coronavirus/|title=Venezuela sin kits de diagn\u00f3stico ni condiciones para enfrentar el nuevo coronavirus|last=Souquett Gil|first=Mariana|date=31 January 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Venezuelan government announced that the country had imposed epidemiological surveillance, restrictions and a plan to detect individuals with COVID-19 at the [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport (Venezuela)|Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport]] in [[Maiquet\u00eda]], Venezuela's main international airport. They said Venezuela would receive diagnostic kits for the virus strain from the [[Pan American Health Organization]] (PAHO).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=51767&SEO=venezuela-imposes-entry-restrictions-over-coronavirus|title=Venezuela imposes entry restrictions over coronavirus|date=3 February 2020|work=[[Prensa Latina]]|access-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== March ===\nVenezuela reported its first official cases of coronavirus disease on 13 March 2020.<ref name=\"PH\" /> However, several days earlier a suspected case became controversial due to the state treatment of a [[whistleblower]].<ref name=\":13\" /> On 7 March, ''[[Fe y Alegr\u00eda]]'' reported that a suspicious medical case was registered in [[Zulia]]: a 31-year-old who was not from Venezuela was examined at the Dr. Pedro Iturbe Hospital and later transferred to the University Hospital of [[Maracaibo]]. The patient had apparent symptoms and was discharged days later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiofeyalegrianoticias.com/detectan-un-caso-sospechoso-de-coronavirus-en-maracaibo/|title=Detectan un caso sospechoso de Coronavirus en Maracaibo|date=7 March 2020|work=[[Fe y Alegr\u00eda]]|access-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> The state governor, {{ill|Omar Prieto|es}}, asked the Public Ministry to investigate a [[University of Zulia]] professor, Freddy Pachano, for bringing attention to the suspected case in the state, and the NGO Espacio P\u00fablico condemned Prieto for ordering such an investigation.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/omar-prieto-pide-investigar-a-profesor-por-denunciar-casos-sospechosos-de-coronavirus/|title=Omar Prieto pide investigar a profesor por denunciar casos sospechosos de coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] declared a ban on protests on 12 March before to prevent cases in Venezuela, as well as a ban on flights from Europe and Colombia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.periodistadigital.com/pd-america/20200312/dictador-nicolas-maduro-prohibe-manifestaciones-evitar-coronavirus-noticia-689404278621/|title=El s\u00e1trapa Nicol\u00e1s Maduro proh\u00edbe las manifestaciones en su contra \"para evitar el coronavirus\"|last=Digital|first=Periodista|date=2020-03-12|website=Periodista Digital|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nThe first cases, two on 13 March, were registered in the state of [[Miranda (state)|Miranda]].<ref name=\"FirstCases\" /><ref name=\"PH\" /> Colombian president [[Iv\u00e1n Duque M\u00e1rquez|Iv\u00e1n Duque]] closed the border with Venezuela effective from the next day.<ref name=\":ET\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/politica/gobierno/duque-ordena-cerrar-los-pasos-fronterizos-con-venezuela-472746|title=Duque ordena cerrar los pasos fronterizos con Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|work=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)]]|language=ES|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/07a1e78f17fdc39144b14e95292b93a6|title=Venezuela, already in crisis, reports 1st coronavirus cases|last=Smith|first=Scott|date=13 March 2020|website=Associated Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, the official number of cases rose by eight (to ten), and had spread across four states (Miranda, [[Apure]], [[Aragua]] and [[Cojedes (state)|Cojedes]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-ocho-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez confirma ocho nuevos casos de coronavirus en Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|publisher=El Carabore\u00f1o|language=Spanish|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Communication Minister [[Jorge Rodr\u00edguez (politician)|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]] announced that flights from [[Panama]] and the [[Dominican Republic]] to the country would be suspended for 30 days, beginning on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-ocho-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=Suben a 10 los casos por coronavirus en Venezuela|last=Torrealba|first=Diego|date=14 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Stay-at-home order|Stay-at-home orders]] were announced on 15 March, when the country registered another seven cases, and introduced the next day across six states and the [[Caracas]] area.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-orders-collective-quarantive-in-response-to-coronavirus-idUKKBN2121B8|title=Venezuela orders 'collective quarantine' in response to coronavirus|date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020|work=Reuters}}</ref> The orders were dubbed \"collective quarantine\"; there are exceptions for transportation, health, and delivery of food.<ref name=\"reuters\" /> It was on the first day of the quarantine across six states, 16 March, that Argentina's ambassador in Venezuela, Eduardo Porretti, tested positive for the virus,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=454175|title=Embajador de Argentina en Venezuela contrajo coronavirus|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> and [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] announced that sixteen new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 33. Based on this, Maduro extended the quarantine to the entire country.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/401253/maduro-anuncia-que-hay-33-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela-16mar/|title=Maduro confirma 33 casos de coronavirus en Venezuela y ordena \"cuarentena total\" #16Mar|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Runrunes]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Venezuela went into lockdown on 17 March, authorities in Brazil partially [[Brazil\u2013Venezuela border|closed their border]] with Venezuela. Brazilian Health Minister [[Luiz Henrique Mandetta]] had urged closure of the border due to Venezuela's collapsing health system.<ref name=\"RBR\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-venezuela-idUSKBN2143ZS|title=Brazil partially closing Venezuela border, allowing trucks|date=18 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Venezuelan Vice-President [[Delcy Rodr\u00edguez]] announced three more cases the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2143QY|title=Quarantine threatens to deepen Venezuelan crisis as roadblocks snarl food supplies|date=17 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the afternoon, a patient that would later test positive for coronavirus fled from a hospital in Propatria, in west Caracas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/paciente-portador-de-covid-19-huyo-de-cdi-en-propatria-donde-permanecia-aislado/|title=Paciente portador de COVID-19 huy\u00f3 de CDI en Propatria donde permanec\u00eda aislado|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Carabobe\u00f1o]]|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/paciente-coronavirus-huye-del-hospital-caracas-n4195206|title=Paciente con coronavirus huye del hospital en Caracas|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=[[Diario Las Am\u00e9ricas]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Delcy Rodr\u00edguez reported that the numbers of cases had not changed since the previous day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=456588|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez: No se confirmaron nuevos casos de coronavirus en las \u00faltimas 24 horas|date=18 March 2020|website=El Nacional|language=es|url-status=live|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> By 21 March, the government reported 70 confirmed cases in the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-aislados-idLTAKBN21810Y-OUSLT|title=Venezuela usar\u00e1 cuartos de hotel para aislar casos suaves de coronavirus: ministro - Reuters|date=21 March 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> two of which were in critical condition, and with 15 labeled as recovered (showing no symptoms after five days).<ref name=\"mpps-latest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vtv.gob.ve/venezuela-70-casos-confirmados-covid-19-15-recuperados/|title=Venezuela registra 70 casos confirmados de Covid-19 y 15 de ellos se han recuperado satisfactoriamente|work=Venezolana de Televisi\u00f3n|language=es|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Rodr\u00edguez{{Who|date=April 2020}} said the two critical cases were hospitalized in private clinics in Miranda state and that their treatment was being provided for free through the Ministry of Health.<ref name=\"mpps-latest\" />\n\nEconomic measures to deal with the consequences of the pandemic were announced on 22 March, along with seven more cases.<ref name=\"reuters22march\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN21A02V|title=Venezuela prohibits company layoffs and suspends credit collections over coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the plans, rent and credit payments will be suspended for six months, accompanied by compensation in [[Currency of Venezuela|local currency]] for property owners and medium-sized businesses.<ref name=\"reuters22march\" /> The measures also extende a 2015 policy that prevents companies from firing employees through December 2020.<ref name=\"reuters22march\" />\n\nThe first confirmed death from the disease was announced on 26 March.<ref name=\"Reutersfirstdeath\" /> Another death was reported the next day.<ref name=\"2death\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/segunda-muerte-por-covid-19-y-suben-a-113-los-contagiados/|title=Segunda muerte por COVID-19 y suben a 113 los contagiados\n|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=27 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"27MarchReuters\">{{cite news|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-idLTAKBN21E3KX-OUSLT|title=Venezuela reporta segunda muerte por COVID-19, casos ascienden a 113 en el pa\u00eds|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=Reuters|language=es}}</ref> Also on 27 March, Delcy Rodr\u00edguez met with [[Prime Minister of Trinidad and Tobago]] [[Keith Rowley]], with the meeting focused on the strategy being deployed in both countries to combat the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gov.tt/content/prime-minister-meets-venezuelan-vice-president#.XoJKjogzaUn|title=Prime Minister Meets with Venezuelan Vice President|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=gov.tt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> There was also controversy on this day, when NGO [[PROVEA|Provea]] revealed that around ninety people coming from [[C\u00facuta]], [[Colombia]], were forcefully isolated on 25 March by the [[Venezuelan National Guard|National Guard]] in [[Barquisimeto|Barqusimeto]], [[Lara (state)|Lara]], without food or proper sanitary conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cronica.uno/en-lara-la-gnb-somete-a-cuarentena-forzosa-a-mas-de-60-personas-que-regresaron-de-cucuta/|title=En Lara la GNB somete a cuarentena forzosa a m\u00e1s de 60 personas que regresaron de C\u00facuta|last=Sarmiento|first=Mabel|date=27 March 2020|website=Cr\u00f3nica Uno|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/provea-aislan-a-90-personas-de-manera-forzosa-en-barquisimeto/|title=Provea: Aislan a 90 personas de manera forzosa en Barquisimeto|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=[[El Carabobe\u00f1o]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/ong-denuncia-confinamiento-forzado-90-venezolanos-covid-19-n4195775|title=ONG denuncia \"confinamiento forzado\" de 90 venezolanos por COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Diario las Am\u00e9ricas]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>  \n\n===April===\n[[Ministry of Communication and Information (Venezuela)|Information Minister]] [[Jorge Rodr\u00edguez (politician)|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]] first reported that there were more recoveries than new infections in Venezuela on 11 April.<ref name=\"EP11A\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/jorge-rodriguez-asegura-que-venezuela-no-reporta-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19-este-11abril/|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez: Venezuela no reporta nuevos casos de COVID-19 este #11abril|last=Leonett|first=Vanessa|date=11 April 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\"efectococuyo11a\">{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/rodriguez-asegura-que-en-venezuela-se-hacen-25-000-pruebas-diarias-para-covid-19/|title=Rodr\u00edguez asegura que en Venezuela se hacen \"25.000 pruebas diarias\" para COVID-19|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Ibis Le\u00f3n|language=es|date=11 April 2020|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> Delcy Rodr\u00edguez and Nicol\u00e1s Maduro announced an extension of the national quarantine and state of alarm for 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-alarma-idLTAKCN21U02U-OUSLT|title=Venezuela extiende 30 d\u00edas m\u00e1s el estado de alarma y cuarentena por coronavirus - Reuters|date=12 April 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter a sudden rise of the number of cases in [[Margarita Island]], Nicol\u00e1s Maduro announced a [[curfew]] the entire state of [[Nueva Esparta]] on 19 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-casos-idLTAKBN222031-OUSLT|title=Venezuela impone nuevo toque de queda en una isla por salto de casos de coronavirus - Reuters|date=19 April 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> 41 of the cases at the time, were related to ''Roberto Vahlis Baseball Academy''. Some of its member had just arrived from [[Dominican Republic]] by plane.<ref name=efectococuyo19a/>\n\n== Measures ==\n\n=== Executive response ===\nOn 12 March, [[President of Venezuela|President]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] declared a public health emergency in the country and suspended all inbound flights from [[Europe]] and [[Colombia]] for 30 days. He also announced that public gatherings were to be suspended and that the government would be evaluating whether or not to suspend flights from other regions in the coming weeks. According to Maduro, there had been 30 suspected cases in Venezuela, but these had all tested negative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-pol/venezuelas-maduro-suspends-all-flights-from-europe-and-colombia-for-a-month-over-coronavirus-concerns-idUSKBN20Z2W9|title=Venezuela's Maduro suspends flights from Europe, Colombia over coronavirus concerns|date=12 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=13 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter the first cases in the country were confirmed, Vice-President Delcy Rodr\u00edguez instructed all the passengers of the 5 and 8 March [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] 6673 flight{{Clarify|reason=Is it 5 or 8 March; the rest of the sentence indicates only one flight, which can't have been on two days|date=April 2020}} to immediately enter into a mandatory preventive quarantine, since the two cases were from this flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/gran-caracas/gobierno-convoca-a-viajeros-del-vuelo-6673-presentarse-para-cumplir-la-cuarentena/|title=Gobierno convoca a viajeros del vuelo 6673 presentarse para cumplir la cuarentena|date=13 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRodr\u00edguez announced that all classes would be suspended at public and private schools from Monday 16 March until further notice,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caraotadigital.net/nacionales/delcy-rodriguez-anuncio-suspension-de-clases-tras-llegada-del-coronavirus-a-venezuela|title=Anuncian suspensi\u00f3n de clases tras llegada del Coronavirus a Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|website=Noticias de Venezuela y el Mundo - Caraota Digital|language=es|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> while [[N\u00e9stor Reverol]] announced that the government would provide border control authorities with face masks, gloves and thermometers, without mentioning supplies for citizens and hospitals.<ref name=\"PH\" /> Reverol also announced that the operational control of all the police forces would be transferred to the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|Armed Forces]] in order to coordinate the action and contingency plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.panorama.com.ve/ciudad/Reverol-No-puede-entrar-ninguna-persona-al-territorio-nacional-sin-tapabocas-20200313-0044.html|title=Reverol: \"No puede entrar ninguna persona al territorio nacional sin tapabocas\"|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=Panorama|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, authorities arrested two people for spreading false information about the virus, recording a video about fake cases in [[Los Teques]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/sucesos/64379/dos-detenidos-por-difundir-informacion-falsa-sobre-el-covid-19|title=Dos detenidos por difundir informaci\u00f3n falsa sobre el Covid 19|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> SUDEBAN, the government's department related to banks and financial institutions, announced the suspension of banking activities, effective from 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eltiempo.com.ve/2020/03/15/sudeban-informo-que-actividades-bancarias-estaran-suspendidas-desde-el-lunes-comunicado/|title=Sudeban inform\u00f3 que actividades bancarias estar\u00e1n suspendidas desde el lunes (+Comunicado)|date=15 March 2020|website=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDefense Minister [[Vladimir Padrino L\u00f3pez]] announced that, effective from 16 March, the Armed Forces would control access to the six states and the [[Capital District (Venezuela)|Capital District]] declared by Nicol\u00e1s Maduro to be in quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/padrino-lopez-a-partir-del-16mar-la-fan-controlara-el-acceso-a-los-estados-en-cuarentena/|title=Padrino L\u00f3pez: Fuerza Armada controlar\u00e1 acceso a los estados en cuarentena|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Maduro reversed the country's official position against the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF), asking the institution for US$5&nbsp;billion to combat the pandemic,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/economia/Maduro-FMI-millones-dolares-COVID-19_0_1006850528.html|title=Maduro le pide al FMI 5 mil millones de d\u00f3lares para actuar contra el COVID-19|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[EFE]]|publisher=eldiario.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a first during Maduro's presidency; he has been a critic of the institution.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berwick|first=Angus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2143QY|title=Quarantine threatens to deepen Venezuelan crisis as roadblocks snarl food supplies|date=17 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/420afb1fa856dedcc4cb3eddcd8ac0a2|title=Venezuela seeks emergency $5 billion IMF loan to fight virus|date=17 March 2020|website=AP NEWS|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The IMF also has had conflicts with the Venezuelan government in the past, as Maduro's predecessor [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] had pledged to cut ties with the fund in 2007, and the IMF suspended US$400&nbsp;million in [[special drawing rights]] during the [[Venezuelan presidential crisis]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-17/venezuela-requests-5-billion-from-imf-to-fight-coronavirus|title=Venezuela Requests $5 Billion from IMF to Fight Coronavirus|date=17 March 2020|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=17 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> The IMF rejected the deal as it was not clear, among its member states, on who it recognizes as Venezuela's president, Nicol\u00e1s Maduro or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/420afb1fa856dedcc4cb3eddcd8ac0a2|title=IMF rejects Maduro's bid for emergency loan to fight virus|date=17 March 2020|website=AP NEWS|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> According to a report by [[Bloomberg News|''Bloomberg'']], the Maduro administration also tried to request aid of $1 billion from the IMF after the first request was denied.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Vasquez|first=Alex|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-21/rejected-venezuela-returns-to-the-imf-seeking-1-billion-in-aid|title=Rejected Venezuela Returns to IMF Seeking $1 Billion in Aid|date=21 March 2020|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Rodr\u00edguez announced that 4,000 diagnosis kits were delivered from [[China]] to test for coronavirus disease. The government said that the Chinese diagnosis kits would benefit 300,000 Venezuelans and thanked the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] and its [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] for its generosity. In a separate measure, Venezuela's INEA maritime authority has prohibited crews aboard ships docking in the country's ports from disembarking.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-lifts-coronavirus-cases-to-42-thanks-china-for-aid-idUSKBN2163I9|title=Venezuela lifts coronavirus cases to 42, thanks China for aid|date=19 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Maduro announced that he had received a letter from the [[United Nations]] (UN) Resident Coordinator and [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) Resident Representative Peter Grohmann, confirming that the organization \"is ready to support the Venezuelan government in its fight against COVID-19.\" Maduro stressed that the UN has taken concrete actions, particularly in the areas of health and water, sanitation and hygiene, and \"will support the Ministry of Health in the care and containment of the coronavirus.\" Likewise, they will offer support in the disclosure of reliable and updated information.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://actualidad.rt.com/actualidad/346828-maduro-confirma-venezuela-recibira-ayuda|title=Maduro confirma que Venezuela recibir\u00e1 ayuda de la ONU para combatir el coronavirus|date=19 March 2020|work=[[RT en Espa\u00f1ol]]|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Maduro said that [[Russia]] was considering \"a significant donation of special humanitarian aid\" to the country, such as medical equipment and kits for the diagnosis of COVID-19, which was expected to arrive by the following week.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferm\u00edn Kancev|first=Mar\u00eda Victoria|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/maduro-rusia-enviara-ayuda-humanitaria-a-venezuela-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Maduro: Rusia enviar\u00e1 ayuda humanitaria a Venezuela por el coronavirus|date=20 March 2020|work=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|access-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> On 23 March, Foreign Minister [[Jorge Arreaza]] and Russian ambassador Sergei Melik-Bagdasarov announced that 10,000 diagnosis kits had been delivered from Russia, with more to be supplied in future shipments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ariza|first=Joselyn|url=http://mppre.gob.ve/2020/03/23/rusia-envia-insumos-medicos-venezuela-detectar-covid19/|title=Rusia env\u00eda insumos m\u00e9dicos a Venezuela para detectar Covid-19|date=23 March 2020|publisher=Venezuelan Ministry of Foreign Affairs|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> In a [[Twitter|tweet]], President Maduro thanked the [[Government of Russia|Russian government]] and President [[Vladimir Putin]] for their generosity and for standing in solidarity with the Venezuelan people.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NicolasMaduro |number=1242281781740670980|title=Llegaron a Venezuela 10 mil kits de pruebas diagn\u00f0sticas procedentes de la Federaci\u00f0n de Rusia para el despistaje del COVID-19. En nombre de nuestro pueblo, agradezco la solidaridad y la cooperaci\u00f0n del hermano Presidente Vlad\u00edmir Putin y del pueblo ruso. \u00a1Un Abrazo! |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMaduro announced several economic measures on 23 March to deal with unemployment, the assumption of wage payment by the state, the suspension of rent and credit interests payments, the assignment of new bonds, the flexibility of new loans and credit, the prohibition of the telecommunication services and the guarantee of CLAP ([[Local Committees for Supply and Production]]) supplies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/economia/medidas-economicas-populistas-anunciadas-por-maduro-podrian-enterrar-al-sector-privado/|title=Medidas econ\u00f3micas populistas anunciadas por Maduro podr\u00edan enterrar al sector privado|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Erika|date=23 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== National Assembly response ===\nDisputed [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] leader and disputed [[Venezuelan presidential crisis|acting president]] [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] said that the country is experiencing one of the most serious health crises in its history, caused by the inaction of the Maduro government, and announced a series of measures in order to take \"responsible measures against the pandemic.\"<ref name=\"infobae\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/03/13/guaido-anuncio-una-redefinicion-de-la-agenda-de-protestas-por-el-coronavirus-es-momento-de-que-el-regimen-deje-entrar-la-ayuda-humanitaria/|title=Guaid\u00f3 anunci\u00f3 una redefinici\u00f3n de la agenda de protestas por el coronavirus: \"Es momento de que el r\u00e9gimen deje entrar la ayuda humanitaria\"|date=13 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"guaidocorona\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/guaido-anuncia-redefinicion-de-las-convocatorias-de-calle-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Guaid\u00f3 anuncia redefinici\u00f3n de las convocatorias de calle por el coronavirus|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=13 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> These include the postponement of opposition protests and the creation of the Special Health Commission.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"infobae\" /> In addition, Guaid\u00f3 also called for the entry of humanitarian aid from the [[United Nations]], while explaining that health services are not impacted by [[International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis|international sanctions]].<ref name=\"guaidocorona\" />\n\nThe Committee of Electoral Candidacies, in charge of appointing a new [[National Electoral Council (Venezuela)|National Electoral Council]] (CNE), announced that it would suspend its meetings because of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/politica/64502/comite-para-designar-nuevo-cne-suspendera-reuniones|title=Comit\u00e9 para designar nuevo CNE suspender\u00e1 reuniones|last=Murillo|first=Yuskerli|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Julio Castro M\u00e9ndez|Julio Castro]], head of the Special Health Commission appointed by Juan Guaid\u00f3, reported on 16 March that face masks are a prevention measure useful only for one day,  and that once used the mask loses its effectiveness and can become a source of infection; he also declared that Venezuelans have to take additional measures to deal with the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elimpulso.com/2020/03/16/julio-castro-la-mascarilla-solo-sirve-para-un-dia-puede-ser-un-foco-de-infeccion-si-se-usa-varias-veces-16mar/|title=Julio Castro: La mascarilla solo sirve para un d\u00eda, puede ser un foco de infecci\u00f3n si se usa varias veces #16Mar|last=Escalona|first=Jos\u00e9|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Impulso]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] deputy Jes\u00fas Y\u00e1nez announced that the government of [[Taiwan]] donated 1,000 surgical masks as a measure to prevent the coronavirus pandemic. The masks were distributed in five stations of the [[Caracas Metro]] ([[Plaza Sucre station|Plaza Sucre]], [[P\u00e9rez Bonalde station|P\u00e9rez Bonalde]], [[Plaza Venezuela station|Plaza Venezuela]], [[Chacao station|Chacao]] and [[Petare station|Petare]]). Y\u00e1nez highlighted that the metro is a means of transportation used by a large part of the population and is a breeding ground for the pandemic due to the crowding of people in closed spaces, should any one of them be carrying the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/13/mil-venezolanos-recibieron-donacion-de-taiwan-para-prevenir-el-coronavirus/|title=Mil venezolanos recibieron donaci\u00f3n de Taiw\u00e1n para prevenir el coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nGuaid\u00f3's Special Health Commission collected 3,500 protection kits for caregivers at five hospitals on 16 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berwick|first=Angus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2132FD|title=Venezuela expands quarantine as number of coronavirus cases climbs to 33|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Guaid\u00f3 announced that he delivered medical kits to protect the health sector from the coronavirus pandemic. On his official [[Twitter]] account, he shared a video expressing that \"We are protecting a sector that today is giving everything: the health sector, our doctors and nurses. To support them is to support us all. We must bring this help to hundreds who need it\", and concluded \"We can contain this emergency. Venezuela is in our hands.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/21/en-video-guaido-entrega-kits-para-proteger-al-sector-salud-del-brote-de-coronavirus/|title=EN VIDEO: Guaid\u00f3 entrega kits para proteger al sector salud del brote de coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=jguaido|number=1241389880137125892|date=21 March 2020|title=Estamos protegiendo a un sector que hoy est\u00e1 d\u00e1ndolo todo: el sector salud, nuestros m\u00e9dicos y enfermeras. Apoyarlos es apoyarnos todos. Esta ayuda debemos llevarla a cientos que la necesitan. Podemos contener esta emergencia. Venezuela est\u00e1 en nuestras manos. #AuxilioParaVzla|author=Juan Guaid\u00f3}}</ref> Guaid\u00f3 also announced the creation of the Human Rights Observatory as a response to the increase of human rights violations in the country during the social isolation orders.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.europapress.es/internacional/noticia-guaido-denuncia-aumento-violaciones-ddhh-venezuela-estallido-pandemia-20200323130355.html|title=Guaid\u00f3 denuncia un aumento de las violaciones de los DDHH en Venezuela desde el estallido de la pandemia|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=[[Europa Press]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGuaid\u00f3 called for the creation of a \"national emergency government\", not lead by Maduro, on 28 March. According to Guaid\u00f3, a loan of US$1.2 billion was ready to be given in support of a power-sharing coalition between pro-Maduro officials, the military and the opposition in order to fight the pandemic in Venezuela. If accepted, the money would go to assist families affected by the disease and its economic consequences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/645b00c744ded5db872e02b933609deb|title=Guaido urges unity government backed by loans to fight virus|last=Goodman|first=Joshua|date=29 March 2020|website=Associated Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Other responses ===\n[[Baltazar Enrique Porras Cardozo|Baltazar Porras]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caracas|Apostolic Administrator of Caracas]], announced the suspension of ecclesiastic activities on 15 March, while assuring that temples would remain open, asking Venezuelans to avoid crowded places and to remain calm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vpitv.com/ultimas_noticias_sobre_venezuela/actividades-eclesiasticas/|title=Suspendieron actividades eclesi\u00e1sticas en Venezuela tras brote de coronavirus|last=|first=|date=15 March 2020|website=[[VPItv]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Health Ministry certified the microbiology laboratory of the [[University of the Andes (Venezuela)|University of the Andes]], in [[M\u00e9rida (state)|M\u00e9rida state]], to start carrying out tests to detect the presence of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]], the coronavirus responsible for the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] disease, on 18 March. Once the necessary supplies are received, the laboratory will be able to perform up to 20 tests per day and would be the second laboratory in the country to perform detection tests after the National Hygiene Institute in Caracas; it would be expected to carry out tests for the states of M\u00e9rida, [[T\u00e1chira]], [[Trujillo (state)|Trujillo]] and [[Barinas (state)|Barinas]], and possibly other states in the west, as it is closer than the Hygiene Institute in Caracas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/los-andes/laboratorio-de-microbiologia-de-la-ula-hara-pruebas-para-detectar-coronavirus/|title=Laboratorio de microbiolog\u00eda de la ULA har\u00e1 pruebas para detectar coronavirus|last=Fern Rodr\u00edguez|first=Mar\u00eda|date=18 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThree men that were playing [[dominoes]] during the quarantine were murdered on 21 March in the [[23 de Enero|23 de Enero parish]], in Caracas, and two more were injured.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/sucesos/colectivos-imponen-toque-de-queda-en-el-23-de-enero-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Colectivos imponen toque de queda en el 23 de Enero por el coronavirus|last=Galaviz|first=Daisy|date=23 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> According to neighbors and relatives, a dozen members of the ''[[Colectivo (Venezuela)|colectivo]]'' Tres Ra\u00edces arrived while they were playing and were responsible for their deaths; the witnesses accused the ''colectivo'' members of being linked with [[Iris Varela]], Minister of Popular Power for the Prison Service, being linked to a [[Cuerpo de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas, Penales y Criminal\u00edsticas|CICPC]] officer, and of wearing FAES and [[Venezuelan National Police|National Police]] uniforms, announcing that they would protest as a response to the killings, in defiance of the quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/sucesos/familiares-senalan-a-colectivos-por-asesinato-de-tres-vecinos-del-23-de-enero/|title=Familiares se\u00f1alan colectivos por asesinato tres vecinos del 23 de Enero|date=22 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ''colectivo'' denied the accusations of being related to the government or police, saying that the murders were instead motivated by revenge.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn late March, the ''[[Colectivo (Venezuela)|colectivos]]'' Tres Ra\u00edces and [[La Piedrita]] started imposing a paramilitary-enforced [[curfew]] in the 23 de Enero parish, increasing repression and imposing closure times to businesses.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\n\n=== Government reactions ===\nMaduro asked people to not politicize the pandemic,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.entornointeligente.com/maduro-pide-no-politizar-el-tema-del-coronavirus-mientras-apunta-el-dedo-a-los-eeuu-y-la-oposicin-videos/|title=Maduro pide no politizar el tema del coronavirus mientras apunta el dedo a los EEUU y la oposici\u00f3n (VIDEOS)|date=13 March 2020|work=Entorno Inteligente|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> while also expressing concern as to how the country could control the pandemic with the [[International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis|United States-imposed sanctions]].<ref name=\"FirstCases\" /> Maduro called on [[US President]] [[Donald Trump]] to lift the sanctions so the country could acquire necessary medical supplies.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Laya|first=Patricia|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/venezuela-doctors-fear-pandemic-will-overwhelm-wrecked-hospitals|title=Venezuela Conducts 'Tens' of Virus Tests and Bans Europe Flights|date=12 March 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJuan Guaid\u00f3 denounced that since the start of the pandemic, human rights violations by Maduro's administration had increased, citing the murders in the 23 de Enero parish, the arrest of [[Darvinson Rojas]], and human rights abuses against political prisoners, who are held in prisons with a high infection risk. Guaid\u00f3 announced the creation of a Human Rights Observatory as a response.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n=== Other reactions ===\nThe Venezuelan Medical Federation expressed condemnation at how a medic in Zulia was forced to leave for Colombia after denouncing the inability of Venezuela to cope if the disease arrived;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/fmv-denuncio-amedrentamiento-a-medicos-tras-estado-de-alarma-por-coronavirus/|title=FMV denunci\u00f3 amedrentamiento a m\u00e9dicos tras estado de alarma por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> it also asked for the release of the political prisoners in the country, who are vulnerable to the virus, specifically [[Roberto Marrero]], [[Juan Requesens]], and other lawmakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/presidente-de-la-fmv-exhorta-a-que-se-liberen-a-presos-politicos-por-coronavirus/|title=Presidente de la FMV exhorta a que se liberen a presos pol\u00edticos por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Anzo\u00e1tegui|Anzo\u00e1tegui state]], nurses denounced the lack of face masks, gloves and disposable gowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/oriente/enfermeras-denuncian-falta-de-mascarillas-guantes-y-bata-desechable-en-anzoategui/|title=Enfermeras denuncian falta de mascarillas, guantes y bata desechable en Anzo\u00e1tegui|last=Pellicani|first=Giovanna|date=16 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the Chinese Embassy in [[Caracas]] rejected the accusations made by [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] deputies against China in calling the pandemic the \"China or Wuhan virus.\" In a statement, the embassy said it \"strongly rejects the attacks and unfounded and arbitrary accusations of some Venezuelan deputies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.eluniversal.com/politica/64829/embajada-china-rechaza-acusaciones-de-parlamentarios-venezolanos|title=Embajada china rechaza acusaciones de parlamentarios venezolanos|date=19 March 2020|work=[[[[El Universal (Caracas)]] (Venezuela)]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nTransparencia Venezuela asked for transparency and access to public information regarding the handling of the emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/403571/transparencia-venezuela-exige-informacion-veraz/|title=Transparencia Venezuela exige informaci\u00f3n veraz|last=|first=|date=2020-04-07|website=Runrun.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nMedia outlets, such as [[El Nacional (Venezuela)|''El Nacional'']], denounced the price increase of face masks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/economia/coronavirus-en-venezuela-denuncian-encarecimiento-de-las-mascarillas/|title=Coronavirus en Venezuela: encarecimiento de las mascarillas|last=Villarreal|first=Karina|date=13 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/venezuela/como-es-la-situacion-en-venezuela-frente-al-coronavirus-472324|title=Coronavirus en Venezuela: $ 140 mil por caja de tapabocas|date=13 March 2020|website=El Tiempo|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://versionfinal.com.ve/ciudad/tapabocas-desechables-se-elevan-de-7-000-a-80-000-bolivares-tras-confirmacion-de-coronavirus/|title=Tapabocas desechables se elevan de 7.000 a 80.000 bol\u00edvares tras confirmaci\u00f3n de coronavirus|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=Diario Versi\u00f3n Final|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Outlets have also reported on the violation of the quarantine for reasons such as buying food, medicines, and both cleaning and hygiene products, as well as the public services crisis, including the lack of drinking water, electric power, cooking gas, telephone signal and [[waste collection]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/venezuela/la-necesidad-obliga-el-pueblo-en-la-calle-a-pesar-de-la-cuarentena/|title=La necesidad obliga: el pueblo en la calle a pesar de la cuarentena|last=Brito|first=Estefani|date=26 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== International sanctions ====\n{{see also|International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis}}\nThe [[Embassy of the United States, Caracas|United States Embassy in Venezuela]] rejected claims from [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] and [[Jorge Arreaza]] that sanctions are preventing the government from purchasing medical supplies, saying that \u201cmedicines, medical supplies, spare parts and components for medical devices in Venezuela, or to people from third countries who buy specifically for resale from Venezuela are excluded from the sanctions.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/embajada-virtual-de-eeuu-en-venezuela-se-las-canto-clarito-a-maduro-tras-llorantina-por-sanciones/|title=Embajada virtual de EEUU en Venezuela se las cant\u00f3 clarito a Maduro tras llorantina por sanciones|date=14 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=usembassyve|number=1238476780731850757|date=13 March 2020|title=Medicinas, insumos m\u00e9dicos, piezas de repuesto y componentes para productos sanitarios en Venezuela, o a personas de terceros pa\u00edses que compran espec\u00edficamente para reventa a Venezuela quedan excluidos de las sanciones estadounidenses. Para que sepan @NicolasMaduro @jaarreaza|author=Embajada Virtual de los EE.UU., Venezuela}}</ref> Days later, Foreign Minister [[Jorge Arreaza]] called the statements \"the height of impudence and falsehood.\" He declared that Venezuelan government assets worth more than US$5&nbsp;billion were blocked overseas, in addition to \"Venezuela's ban on access to the international [[Bank|banking system]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.2001.com.ve/en-la-agenda/224732/jorge-arreaza--bloqueo-economico-contra-venezuela-afecta-adquisicion-de-insumos.html|title=Jorge Arreaza: bloqueo econ\u00f3mico contra Venezuela afecta adquisici\u00f3n de insumos|date=21 March 2020|work=[[Diario 2001]]|access-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agencia Venezolana de Noticias]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nFormer Attorney General [[Luisa Ortega D\u00edaz]] declared that Maduro \"lied\" when saying that there were no medicines in the country because of the sanctions, saying that the reasons were incompetence and [[Corruption in Venezuela|corruption]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/ortega-diaz-maduro-miente-al-decir-que-no-hay-medicinas-por-las-sanciones/|title=Ortega D\u00edaz: Maduro miente al decir que no hay medicinas por las sanciones|last=Pitazo|first=Redacci\u00f3n El|date=16 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs|US Acting Assistant Secretary for Western Hemisphere Affairs]] [[Michael Kozak]] also accused Maduro of lying, saying that [[United States sanctions|U.S. sanctions]] never block food or medicine purchases. He emphasized that [[shortages in Venezuela]] resulted from \"the regime\u2019s theft of the nation\u2019s wealth.\"<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WHAAsstSecty|number=1240784224988381184|date=19 March 2020|title=More lies from #Maduro, author of the #MaduroCrisis, about #Venezuela\u2019s tragedy. U.S. sanctions NEVER block food or medicine. Shortages in Venezuela result from the regime\u2019s theft of the nation\u2019s wealth. #EstamosUnidosVE|author=Michael G. Kozak}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://albertonews.com/coronavirus/kozak-reitero-que-las-sanciones-de-eeuu-al-regimen-de-maduro-no-bloquean-comida-o-medicinas/|title=Kozak reiter\u00f3 que las sanciones de EEUU al r\u00e9gimen de Maduro 'no bloquean comida o medicinas'|date=20 March 2020|website=AlbertoNews|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nEconomist [[Francisco Rodr\u00edguez (economist)|Francisco Rodr\u00edguez]] declared that the sanctions \"severely harm the capacity of affected countries\" to respond to the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://cepr.net/press-release/us-government-should-immediately-lift-economic-sanctions-to-avoid-causing-more-deaths-from-pandemic-economists-say/|title=US Government Should Immediately Lift Economic Sanctions to Avoid Causing More Deaths From Pandemic, Economists Say|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=Center for Economic and Policy Research|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|sure=y|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 24 March, [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|UN High Commissioner for Human Rights]] [[Michelle Bachelet]] called for any sanctions imposed on Venezuela and other countries facing the pandemic such as [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cuba|Cuba]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe|Zimbabwe]] to be \"urgently reevaluated\" in order to avoid pushing strained medical systems into collapse. In a statement, Bachelet said: \"At this crucial time, both for global public health reasons, and to support the rights and lives of millions of people in these countries, sectoral sanctions should be eased or suspended.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1060092|title=Ease sanctions against countries fighting COVID-19: UN human rights chief|date=24 March 2020|website=UN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/world/bachelet-calls-easing-sanctions-enable-medical-systems-fight-covid-19-and-limit-global|title=Bachelet calls for easing of sanctions to enable medical systems to fight COVID-19 and limit global contagion|date=24 March 2020|work=[[ReliefWeb]]|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]]}}</ref> Bachelet also accentuated the need to protect health workers in these countries as authorities should not punish professionals that point out the deficiencies in the state response to the crisis.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n===International concern===\n{{See also|Health care in Venezuela|Shortages in Venezuela}}\nInternational concern was raised before the first cases were reported, as Venezuela's [[Health care in Venezuela|health care system]] has completely collapsed due to the [[Crisis in Venezuela|ongoing crisis]], meaning its already suffering population is especially vulnerable to the spread of a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"Healthcare\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/venezuela-doctors-fear-pandemic-will-overwhelm-wrecked-hospitals|title=Venezuela Conducts 'Tens' of Virus Tests and Bans Europe Flights|date=12 March 2020|work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|access-date=13 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPer the ''[[Global Health Security Index]]'', Venezuela's health system is ranked among the worst in the world in its ability to detect, quickly respond, and mitigate a pandemic.<ref name=\"ghsindex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ghsindex.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/2019-Global-Health-Security-Index.pdf|title=2019 Global Health Security Index|date=22 October 2019|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> Hospitals are plagued by chronic shortages of supplies, including eye protectors, gloves, masks, and soap.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN20X2F1|title=Buckets for toilets, recycled gloves: Venezuelan hospitals await coronavirus unprepared|date=10 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=11 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> Due to [[Shortages in Venezuela|ongoing shortages of resources]], hospitals must also constantly deal with chronic lack of staff, thus making the response to treating a large number of infected patients significantly more challenging.<ref name=\":0\" /> Patients are also often turned away at hospitals due to overcrowding, or asked to bring in their own gauze, IV solution, or syringes, while there are often no hygiene facilities like toilets, and power outages are a regular occurrence.<ref name=\"Healthcare\" />\n\nThe [[Pan American Health Organization]] (PAHO) said that it would be prioritizing Venezuela alongside Haiti and other Central and South American countries because of \u201cchallenges to their health systems.\u201d<ref name=\"PH\" />\n\n''[[Associated Press]]'' reported that experts are worried that the [[Venezuelan refugee crisis]] could worsen the spread of the virus.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Prison system ====\n''[[Reuters]]'' reported that Venezuela's notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary prisons could spread the coronavirus \"like a fast-moving fire.\" Venezuelan prisons frequently lack bathrooms, people sleep on floors, and many inmates spend their days without shirts or shoes on, in part to combat the infernal heat of windowless facilities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellsworth|first=Brian|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-prisons/overcrowded-and-unsanitary-venezuelas-prisons-brace-for-coronavirus-idUSKBN215323|title=Overcrowded and unsanitary, Venezuela's prisons brace for coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sequera|first2=Vivian}}</ref> This has caused [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]] [[Mike Pompeo]] to demand the Maduro government release six [[Citgo]] executives, held in prison since 2017, on humanitarian grounds.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SecPompeo|number=1240617609441280002|date=19 March 2020|title=It is past time for the Maduro regime to release the #Citgo6 who are currently languishing in the notorious Helicoide prison in #Venezuela. 2+ years in prison with no evidence brought against them; 18 hearings cancelled. Unacceptable.|author=Secretary Pompeo}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Pompeo said that all six men have weakened [[immune system]]s and \"face a grave health risk if they become infected\" with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200319-us-demands-venezuela-free-citgo-executives-as-virus-hits|title=US demands Venezuela free Citgo executives as virus hits|date=19 March 2020|work=[[France 24]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 84 out of 518 inmates escaped from a prison in San Carlos, [[Zulia]], after restrictions against the pandemic were announced, including jail visits. Mayor Bladimir Labrador declared that ten prisoners were killed during the prison break and that two policemen were detained for complicity. According to Carlos Nieto Palma from the NGO Ventana a la Libertad, the suspension of visits directly affects the prisoner's nutrition, given that there was no state-sponsored program to feed them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2020/03/19/5e72c06f21efa09a6a8b462a.html|title=Las restricciones por el coronavirus provocan una fuga de presos que deja 10 muertos en Venezuela|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|publisher=AFP|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The NGO Provea denounced \"grave human rights violations\" after a military spokesperson announced the \"neutralization\" of 35 escapees.  State authorities later declared that the there were eight deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talcualdigital.com/provea-denuncia-asesinato-de-35-presos-fugados-de-reten-en-zulia/|title=Provea denuncia asesinato de 35 presos fugados de ret\u00e9n en Zulia|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=[[Tal Cual]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n\nAs a result of the pandemic's economic impact some business have sought to supplement lost business with deliveries, though exact figures remain obscure and the services are prohibitively costly for average Venezuelans. Some have started to make deliveries to support their families using bicycles instead of motorcycles due to [[gasoline]] shortages.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-transpor/for-struggling-venezuelans-in-quarantine-an-opportunity-in-delivery-services-idUSKCN21Y1VN |title=For struggling Venezuelans in quarantine, an opportunity in delivery services |date=April 16, 2020 |work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Non-government estimates ==\nOn 18 March, four cases were extraofficially reported in [[El Helicoide]], three women and a male officer of the motorized brigade of the [[Venezuelan National Police|National Police]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=456613|title=Detectaron cuatro casos de coronavirus en El Helicoide|date=18 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/03/19/los-presos-politicos-de-venezuela-estan-riesgo-por-el-coronavirus-se-detectaron-cuatro-casos-de-funcionarios-contagiados-en-la-carcel-de-el-helicoide/|title=Los presos pol\u00edticos de Venezuela est\u00e1n en riesgo por el coronavirus: se detectaron cuatro casos en la c\u00e1rcel de El Helicoide|date=19 March 2020|website=[[Infobae]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a person self-identified as a member of the [[Tupamaro (Venezuela)|Tupamaro]] [[Colectivo (Venezuela)|''colectivo'']] in the [[23 de Enero|23 de Enero parish]] of Caracas declared to his community with a [[megaphone]] that a case was confirmed, specifically in Block 39, asking his neighbors to stay home and to prevent other blocks from being infected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/gran-caracas/coronavirus-colectivos-del-23-de-enero-aseguran-un-caso-en-bloque-39/|title=Coronavirus Colectivos del 23 de Enero aseguran un caso en el bloque 39|date=20 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=457792|title=[VIDEO] Tupamaros aseguran que el coronavirus ya lleg\u00f3 al 23 de Enero|date=20 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nVenezuelan newspaper ''[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]'', reported a total of 65 cases for 20 March, according to undisclosed sources from the Health Ministry.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.elnacional.com/venezuela/venezuela-registro-19-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-este-viernes/|title=Venezuela registr\u00f3 otros 19 casos de coronavirus este viernes|work=El Nacional|language=es|date=23 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> On that day the ministry did not report any official numbers, the toll was officially updated the next day going from 42 to 70.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/rr-es-plus/401742/cifras-de-coronavirus-presentadas-por-el-gobierno-de-maduro-revelan-incongruencias/|title=Cifras de coronavirus presentadas por el gobierno de Maduro revelan incongruencias|date=20 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, before the official report on 23 March, ''El Nacional'' reported 84 cases according undisclosed source from the Health Ministry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=460967|title=Venezuela registr\u00f3 otros siete casos por coronavirus y la cifra de contagios se elev\u00f3 a 84|date=23 March 2020|website=El Nacional|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJuan Guaid\u00f3 has questioned the veracity of the official number of cases, stating that there are inconsistencies in the estimates given.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/guaido-asegura-que-hay-incongruencias-cifras-del-regimen-covid-19-n4195450|title=Guaid\u00f3 asegura que hay \"incongruencias\" en cifras del r\u00e9gimen sobre COVID-19|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=[[Diario Las Americas]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with [[El Nuevo Herald]] on 22 March, Guaid\u00f3 declared that the number of confirmed cases in Venezuela could be more than two hundred, according to opposition estimates, contrary to the 70 cases that Maduro's administration recognized at the moment. El Nuevo Herald reported that internal sources extraofficially confirmed that estimate, that  according to said sources there were 181 confirmed cases on the morning of 21 March and a total of 298 in observation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Delgado|first=Antonio Mar\u00eda|url=https://www.elnuevoherald.com/noticias/mundo/america-latina/venezuela-es/article241409051.html|title=Exclusiva: Maduro oculta gravedad del coronavirus. Hay m\u00e1s de 200 casos en Venezuela, dice Guaid\u00f3|date=22 March 2020|work=[[El Nuevo Herald]]|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Authorities actions on reporting ==\n{{See also|Censorship in Venezuela|Censorship and media control during the Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\nOn 13 March, [[Delta Amacuro]] indigenous leader and journalist Melquiades \u00c1vila, who has criticized health infrastructure in the country, questioned publicly through Facebook \"will our hospital be ready for coronavirus?\u201d and joked Maduro's claim that 46 hospitals were prepared for COVID-19. The Governor of Delta Amacuro Lizeta Hern\u00e1ndez and member of the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]], sent the state army to detain \u00c1vila. When asked why by ''Reuters'' on the matter, she said that it was to \u201corient\u201d \u00c1vila and ensure he was being \u201cserious and responsible\u201d.<ref name=reuters24march>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-insight/as-coronavirus-hits-venezuela-maduro-further-quashes-dissent-idUSKBN21C1TA|title=As coronavirus hits Venezuela, Maduro further quashes dissent|date=25 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live|author=Angus Berwick|author2= Sarah Kinosian|author3= Maria Ramirez}}</ref>\n\nAn opposition lawmaker, Tony Geara, was arrested on 14 March in a roadblock after declaring that there was no running water in one of the hospitals listed as prepared by the Bolivarian government.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" /> A court charged Geara with illegal possession of explosives and weapons. Geara denies the charges.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nAccording to twelve medical workers interviewed by ''Reuters,'' security forces use roadblocks and checkpoints to shakedown medical staff.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nJulio Molinos, a medical union leader and retired technician, published a video asking the government to be transparent about hospital conditions on 15 March.  Special Action Force (FAES)  arrested Molinos, who was sentenced to house arrest on charges of compiracy and inciting hatred.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nThe National Assembly released a webpage to provide information and health recommendations on COVID-19 but the access to the website was restricted by CANTV, the state internet provider. The censorship was denounced by Guaid\u00f3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/cantv-bloquea-web-informativa-sobre-el-covid-19-denuncia-venezuela-sin-filtro/|title=Cantv bloquea web informativa sobre el COVID-19, denuncia Venezuela Sin Filtro|last=Ferm\u00edn|first=Mar\u00eda Victoria|date=18 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest of Darvinson Rojas ===\nOn the night of 21 March 2020, journalist [[Darvinson Rojas]] was arrested at his home in [[Caracas]] by officials of the [[Venezuelan National Police|Bolivarian National Police]] (PNB) and around fifteen armed personnel from the Special Actions Force (FAES).<ref name=\"EC\">{{cite news|last1=Avenda\u00f1o|first1=Shari|url=https://efectococuyo.com/sucesos/faes-detiene-a-periodista-darvinson-rojas-y-su-familia-denuncia-sntp/|title=Faes detiene a periodista Darvinson Rojas y su familia, denuncia Sntp|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Denuncian-periodista-Darvinson-Rojas-Caracas_0_1008599157.html|title=Denuncian la detenci\u00f3n del periodista venezolano Darvinson Rojas en Caracas|date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[eldiario.es]]|agency=[[EFE]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> According to the National Union of Press Workers (SNTP), the arrest was related to the coverage of Rojas with his recent publications on the COVID-19 situation in Venezuela.<ref name=\"Van\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20200322/4820578104/denuncian-la-detencion-del-periodista-venezolano-darvinson-rojas-en-caracas.html|title=Denuncian la detenci\u00f3n del periodista venezolano Darvinson Rojas en Caracas|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] (CPJ) called for the immediate release of Rojas. Nathalie Southwick, CPJ coordinator, stated that \"Violently detaining a journalist and interrogating him about his sources on a vital public health issue like the COVID-19 outbreak has an undeniable chilling effect that will only discourage other journalists from reporting on the pandemic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2020/03/venezuelan-journalist-arrested-by-special-forces-f.php|title=Venezuelan journalist arrested by special forces following coronavirus coverage|date=22 March 2020|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] demanded Rojas immediate and unconditional release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.amnesty.org/fr/documents/AMR53/2019/2020/fr/|title=Venezuela: Journalist reporting on COVID-19 jailed|date=23 March 2020|work=Amnesty International|access-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe SNTP, on 24 March, denounced that Darvinson was presented in the tribunals \"illegally\" and \"clandestinely\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/sntp-darvinson-rojas-fue-presentado-en-tribunales-de-manera-ilegal-y-clandestina/|title=Sntp: Darvinson Rojas fue presentado en tribunales de manera ilegal y clandestina|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter 12 days incarcerated, Darvinson Rojas was set free on 3 April 2020 under precautionary measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/es/venezuela-libera-a-periodista-detenido-por-publicaciones-en-twitter-sobre-covid-19/a-53001616|title=Venezuela libera a periodista detenido por publicaciones en Twitter sobre COVID-19|date=3 April 2020|website=Deutsche Welle|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n===Daily new cases and active cases===\n{{Graph\n|type=rect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors=#0000aa,#008000, #ff8000,#FF0000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13 March,14 March, 15 March, 16 March, 17 March, 18 March, 19 March, \u22ee , 21 March, 22 March, 23 March, 24 March, 25 March, 26 March, 27 March, 28 March, 29 March, 30 March, 31 March, 1 April, 2 April, 3 April, 4 April, 5 April, 6 April, 7 April, 8 April, 9 April, 10 April, 11 April,12 April,13 April,14 April,15 April,16 April,17 April,18 April,19 April,20 April\n|yAxisTitle=Number of new cases per day\n|y1=2,8,7,16,17,0,6,0,28,7,7,7,15,1,6,6,10,6,8,1,2,7,2,4,6,1,1,4,4,0,6,8,4,4,7,23,0,29,29\n|yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}\n\n{{Graph\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors= #ff8000,#008000,#40E0D0\n|showValues=\n|legend=Legend\n|xAxisTitle=Date (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13 March,14 March, 15 March, 16 March, 17 March, 18 March, 19 March, 20 March , 21 March, 22 March, 23 March, 24 March, 25 March, 26 March, 27 March, 28 March, 29 March, 30 March, 31 March, 1 April, 2 April, 3 April, 4 April, 5 April, 6 April, 7 April, 8 April, 9 April, 10 April, 11 April, 12 April, 13 April,14 April,15 April,16 April,17 April,18 April, 19 April, 20 April\n|yAxisTitle=Number of cases\n|y1=2,10,17,33,36,36,42,42,70,77,84,91,106,107,113,119,129,135,143,144,146,153, 155,159,165, 166,167,171,175,175,181,189,193,197,204,227,227,256,285\n|y2=2,10,17,33,36,36,42,42,{{#expr:70-15}},{{#expr:77-15}},{{#expr:84-15}},{{#expr:91-15}},{{#expr:106-15}},{{#expr:107-31-1}},{{#expr:113-39-2}},{{#expr:119-39-2}},{{#expr:129-39-3}},{{#expr:135-39-3}},{{#expr:143-41-3}},{{#expr:144-43-3}},{{#expr:146-43-5}},{{#expr:153-52-7}},{{#expr:155-52-7}},{{#expr:159-52-7}},{{#expr:165-65-7}},{{#expr:166-65-7}},{{#expr:167-65-9}},{{#expr:171-84-9}},{{#expr:175-84-9}},{{#expr:175-93-9}},{{#expr:181-93-9}},{{#expr:189-110-9}},{{#expr:193-111-9}},{{#expr:197-111-9}},{{#expr:204-111-9}},{{#expr:227-113-9}},{{#expr:227-117-9}},{{#expr:256-117-9}},{{#expr:285-117-10}}\n|y3=,,,,,,,0,15,15,15,15,15,31,39,39,39,39,41,43,43,52, 52,52,65,65,65,84,84,93,93,110,111,111,111,113,117,117,117\n | y1Title=Total (cumulative)\n | y2Title=Active\n | y3Title=Recoveries\n}}\n'''Notes''':\n*There was no official report on 20 March 2020, [[Worldometer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/venezuela/|title=Venezuela Coronavirus: 197 Cases and 9 Deaths - Worldometer|website=Worldometer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] reported 65 cases, numbers coming from an article of ''[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]'' from undisclosed sources from the Venezuelan Ministry of Health.<ref name=\":12\" />\n*The recoveries from 21 March to 25 March indicate people without symptoms for at least 5 days, considered as recovered in the official reports\n\n=== Confirmed deaths ===\n{{Graph\n|type=rect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors= #000000 \n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Week (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13-19 March, 20-26March,27 March-2 April,3-9 April,10-16 April\n|yAxisTitle=New deaths per week\n|y1=0,1,{{#expr:5-1}},{{#expr:9-5}},0\n}}\n\n=== Regional distribution ===\nCases per federal entity as of 20 April 2020<ref name=efectococuyo20a>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/21-guardias-costeros-en-nueva-esparta-entre-los-29-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=21 guardias costeros en Nueva Esparta entre los 29 nuevos casos de coronavirus en Venezuela|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Maria Souquett Gil|language=es|date=20 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=efectococuyo19a>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/venezuela-reporta-29-casos-nuevos-y-decreta-toque-de-queda-en-nueva-esparta-19deabril/|title=Venezuela reporta 29 casos nuevos y decreta toque de queda en Nueva Esparta #19Abr|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Maria Souquett Gil|language=es|date=19 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>  according to the Bolivarian Government:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable col3der\"\n!Federal entity\n!Number of reported cases\n!Number of deaths{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Anzo\u00e1tegui}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Apure}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Aragua}}\n|29\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Barinas}}\n|7\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Bol\u00edvar}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Caracas|name=Capital District}}{{efn|The number of cases per region is inconsistent and may differ from source to source. In other sources, in Aragua, Apure, Capital District, Gu\u00e1rico, Miranda, Vargas and undisclosed locations, the number of cases may have a difference of 1 to 4 cases from the one reported in the here.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/404820/delcy-rodriguez-informa-de-29-casos-nuevos-de-covid-19/|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez informa de 29 casos nuevos de COVID-19|work=Runrunes|date=20 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>|name=runrunesmap}}\n|32\n|2\n|-\n|{{Flag|Cojedes}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Falc\u00f3n}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Dependencias Federales|name=Federal Dependencies}}{{Efn|The only affected federal dependency is [[Los Roques]]}}\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Gu\u00e1rico}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Lara}}\n|5\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|M\u00e9rida}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Miranda}}{{efn|name=runrunesmap}}\n|83\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Monagas}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Nueva Esparta}}\n|72\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Portuguesa}}\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|T\u00e1chira}}\n|8\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Trujillo}}\n|7\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Sucre}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Vargas}}\n|14\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Yaracuy}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Zulia}}\n|4\n|1\n|-\n|Undisclosed location\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|-\n!Total\n!284\n!10\n|}\nVarious Venezuelan newspapers have pointed out that there have been some inconsistencies with the government reports by federal states.<ref name=\"runrunesactu26marzo\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/402336/delcy-rodriguez-confirma-primer-fallecido-por-covid-19/|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez confirma primer fallecido por Covid-19|date=26 March 2020|website=Runrun|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/rr-es-plus/402235/cronologia-de-incongruencias-y-opacidad-en-cifras-oficiales-de-coronavirus-19-en-venezuela/|title=Cronolog\u00eda de incongruencias y opacidad en cifras oficiales de Covid-19 en Venezuela|date=26 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/importados-o-locales-contradicciones-del-chavismo-en-torno-a-los-casos-de-covid-19/|title=\u00bf\"Importados\" o locales?, contradicciones del chavismo en torno a los casos de COVID-19|last=Avenda\u00f1o|first=Shari|date=19 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> For example, 24 March report differs from 23 report, as [[T\u00e1chira]] and [[Portuguesa (state)|Portuguesa]] that reported cases before, were no longer included.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/maduro-informa-que-se-elevan-a-91-contagios-de-covid-19-y-dice-que-hay-casos-comunitarios/|title=Maduro informa que se elevan a 91 contagios de COVID-19 y dice que \"hay casos comunitarios\"|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=25 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, while the official report indicated 107 total cases, the number of cases per dependency amounted to 108.<ref name=\"runrunesactu26marzo\" />\n\nIn April, the Ministry of Public Health of [[Guyana]] confirmed patients with coronavirus in [[Barima-Waini]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/guyana-33-test-positive-for-covid-19/|title=Guyana: 33 test positive for COVID-19|last=Joseph|first=Sharine|date=8 April 2020|website=St. Lucia News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.gy/index.php/component/k2/item/133-14apr|title=Ministry of Public Health - Guyana COVID-19 Dashboard|website=Ministry of Public Health Guyana|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> located in [[Guayana Esequiba]] and a territory disputed with Venezuela. These cases are not included in the statistics provided by the Bolivarian Government of Venezuela.\n\n=== Sex ratio ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Date (2020)\n!Female-Male ratio\n!Ref\n|-\n|17 March\n|6:5\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|18 March\n|1:1\n|<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vtv.gob.ve/vicepresidenta-rodriguez-confirma-3nuevos-casos-covid19-pais1/|title=Vicepresidenta Rodr\u00edguez confirma 3 nuevos casos de Covid-19 en el pa\u00eds|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Venezolana de Televisi\u00f3n]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n|22 March\n|37:40\n|<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/401873/maduro-anuncio-que-cifra-de-contagiados-por-covid-19-aumento-a-77/|title=Maduro anunci\u00f3 que cifra de contagiados por Covid-19 aument\u00f3 a 77|date=23 March 2020|website=Runrun.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|24 March\n|44:47\n|<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/402104/maduro-anuncio-que-hay-7-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-para-este-24mar/|title=Maduro anunci\u00f3 que hay 7 nuevos casos de coronavirus para este #24Mar|date=24 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|27 March\n|57:56\n|<ref name=\"2death\" />\n|-\n|31 March\n|71:72\n|<ref name=\"efectococuyo31m\">{{cite news|author=Ronny Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/hay-ocho-casos-mas-de-covid-19-y-el-pais-tiene-143-contagiados-dice-maduro/|title=Hay ocho casos m\u00e1s de COVID-19 y el pa\u00eds tiene 143 contagiados, dice Maduro|date=31 March 2020|work=Efecto Cocuyo|access-date=31 March 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n|1 April\n|71:73\n|<ref name=\"efectococuyo1a\">{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-un-nuevo-caso-de-covid-19-y-repudia-declaraciones-de-trump/|work=Efecto Cocuyo|date=1 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez confirma un nuevo caso de COVID-19 y repudia declaraciones de Trump|language=es|author=Maria Souquett Gil}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Per origin ===\nAs of 16 March, there were 33 confirmed cases in Venezuela. According to official estimates, among these, 28 came from [[Europe]] and 5 from [[C\u00facuta]], Colombia. Two of the cases consisted of foreign citizens, one of a diplomatic official, while the rest consisted of Venezuelan residents.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBy 22 March, Maduro announced out of all the 77 cases were imported.<ref name=\":5\" /> According to him, 43 had traveled recently, the distribution was as follows:<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable col3der\"\n!Country\n!Number of imported cases\n|-\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Colombia}}\n|10\n|-\n|{{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Peru}}\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|21 \n|-\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|3\n|-\n!Total\n!43\n|}\nOn 24 March, Maduro first mentioned the existence of cases transmitted locally in the country.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2009 flu pandemic in Venezuela]]\n* [[2019 shipping of humanitarian aid to Venezuela]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Venezuela|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101008203535/http://www.mpps.gob.ve/ Ministerio del Poder Popular para la Salud] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://coronavirusvenezuela.info/ Coronavirus - Presidencia Venezuela] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://twitter.com/corona_virusven Coronavirus Venezuela on Twitter] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Crisis in Venezuela|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2020 in Venezuela|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Crisis in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Venezuela]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Venezuela}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Venezuela.svg\n| legend1         = States with confirmed (red) cases (as of 18 April 2020) {{legend|#C9C9C9|No confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#FDD6C4|1-5 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FCA486|6-10 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FB7050|11-30 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#EA372A|31-50 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BA1419|51-100 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#67000D|\u2265101 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Venezuela]]\n| first_case      = [[Miranda (state)|Miranda State]]\n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[China]]<br>[[Spain]]<br>[[United States]]<br>[[Italy]]<br>[[Colombia]]\n| confirmed_cases = 256<ref name=efectococuyo20a/> <small>(as of 20 April 2020)</small>\n| recovery_cases  = 117<ref name=efectococuyo19a/> <small>(as of 19 April 2020)</small> \n| deaths          = 10<ref name=efectococuyo20a/> <small>(as of 20 April 2020)</small>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\n{{Crisis in Bolivarian Venezuela short}}\n\nAs part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing worldwide pandemic]],  the first two patients with [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[Venezuela]] were confirmed on 13 March 2020;<ref name=\"FirstCases\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/regimen-de-maduro-confirma-dos-primeros-casos-de-coronavirus-120128|title=R\u00e9gimen de Maduro confirma dos primeros casos de coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|website=NTN24.com|language=es|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PH\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-confirms-coronavirus-cases-amid-public-health-concerns-idUSKBN2102DR|title=Venezuela confirms coronavirus cases amid public health concerns|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> the first death was reported on 26 March.<ref name=Reutersfirstdeath>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-death-idUSKBN21D3Q3|title=Venezuela confirms first coronavirus death: official|date=26 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the first record of a patient claiming to have symptoms of coronavirus disease dates back to 29 February 2020,<ref name=efectococuyo29m>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/tercer-fallecido-por-coronavirus-en-el-pais-era-un-taxista-de-antimano/|title=Tercer fallecido por coronavirus en el pa\u00eds era un taxista de Ant\u00edmano|work=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|author=Mar\u00eda Victoria Ferm\u00edn|date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> with government officials suspecting that the first person carrying the virus could have entered the country as early as 25 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/de-marzo-a-febrero-versiones-sobre-la-llegada-del-coronavirus-a-venezuela/|title=De marzo a febrero: versiones sobre la llegada del coronavirus a Venezuela|last=Souquett Gil|first=Mariana|date=1 April 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nVenezuela is particularly vulnerable to the wider effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] because of its [[Crisis in Venezuela|ongoing socioeconomic and political crisis]] causing [[Shortages in Venezuela|massive shortages]] of food staples and basic necessities, including medical supplies. The [[Venezuelan refugee crisis|mass emigration]] of Venezuelan doctors has also caused chronic staff shortages in hospitals.<ref name=\"Healthcare\" />\n\nTo prevent the spread of the disease into Venezuela, the governments of [[Brazil]] and [[Colombia]] temporarily closed [[Borders of Venezuela|their borders with Venezuela]].<ref name=\":ET\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"RBR\" />\n\n==Background==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Venezuela medical cases chart}}In January, Venezuela's [[Ministry of Communication and Information (Venezuela)|Ministry of Popular Power for Health]] announced that the Rafael Rangel National Institute of Hygiene ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]: Instituto Nacional de Higiene Rafael Rangel) in [[Caracas]] would act as the observatory for non-influenza respiratory viruses, including coronaviruses in humans. It is the only health institution in the country with the ability to diagnose respiratory viruses and to operate logistically across the [[States of Venezuela|23 states, the Capital District and the Federal Dependencies]] of Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/salud/venezuela-sin-kits-de-diagnostico-ni-condiciones-optimas-para-enfrentar-el-nuevo-coronavirus/|title=Venezuela sin kits de diagn\u00f3stico ni condiciones para enfrentar el nuevo coronavirus|last=Souquett Gil|first=Mariana|date=31 January 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Venezuelan government announced that the country had imposed epidemiological surveillance, restrictions and a plan to detect individuals with COVID-19 at the [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport (Venezuela)|Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport]] in [[Maiquet\u00eda]], Venezuela's main international airport. They said Venezuela would receive diagnostic kits for the virus strain from the [[Pan American Health Organization]] (PAHO).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=51767&SEO=venezuela-imposes-entry-restrictions-over-coronavirus|title=Venezuela imposes entry restrictions over coronavirus|date=3 February 2020|work=[[Prensa Latina]]|access-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== March ===\nVenezuela reported its first official cases of coronavirus disease on 13 March 2020.<ref name=\"PH\" /> However, several days earlier a suspected case became controversial due to the state treatment of a [[whistleblower]].<ref name=\":13\" /> On 7 March, ''[[Fe y Alegr\u00eda]]'' reported that a suspicious medical case was registered in [[Zulia]]: a 31-year-old who was not from Venezuela was examined at the Dr. Pedro Iturbe Hospital and later transferred to the University Hospital of [[Maracaibo]]. The patient had apparent symptoms and was discharged days later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiofeyalegrianoticias.com/detectan-un-caso-sospechoso-de-coronavirus-en-maracaibo/|title=Detectan un caso sospechoso de Coronavirus en Maracaibo|date=7 March 2020|work=[[Fe y Alegr\u00eda]]|access-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> The state governor, {{ill|Omar Prieto|es}}, asked the Public Ministry to investigate a [[University of Zulia]] professor, Freddy Pachano, for bringing attention to the suspected case in the state, and the NGO Espacio P\u00fablico condemned Prieto for ordering such an investigation.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/omar-prieto-pide-investigar-a-profesor-por-denunciar-casos-sospechosos-de-coronavirus/|title=Omar Prieto pide investigar a profesor por denunciar casos sospechosos de coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] declared a ban on protests on 12 March before to prevent cases in Venezuela, as well as a ban on flights from Europe and Colombia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.periodistadigital.com/pd-america/20200312/dictador-nicolas-maduro-prohibe-manifestaciones-evitar-coronavirus-noticia-689404278621/|title=El s\u00e1trapa Nicol\u00e1s Maduro proh\u00edbe las manifestaciones en su contra \"para evitar el coronavirus\"|last=Digital|first=Periodista|date=2020-03-12|website=Periodista Digital|language=es|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nThe first cases, two on 13 March, were registered in the state of [[Miranda (state)|Miranda]].<ref name=\"FirstCases\" /><ref name=\"PH\" /> Colombian president [[Iv\u00e1n Duque M\u00e1rquez|Iv\u00e1n Duque]] closed the border with Venezuela effective from the next day.<ref name=\":ET\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/politica/gobierno/duque-ordena-cerrar-los-pasos-fronterizos-con-venezuela-472746|title=Duque ordena cerrar los pasos fronterizos con Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|work=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)]]|language=ES|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/07a1e78f17fdc39144b14e95292b93a6|title=Venezuela, already in crisis, reports 1st coronavirus cases|last=Smith|first=Scott|date=13 March 2020|website=Associated Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, the official number of cases rose by eight (to ten), and had spread across four states (Miranda, [[Apure]], [[Aragua]] and [[Cojedes (state)|Cojedes]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-ocho-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez confirma ocho nuevos casos de coronavirus en Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|publisher=El Carabore\u00f1o|language=Spanish|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Communication Minister [[Jorge Rodr\u00edguez (politician)|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]] announced that flights from [[Panama]] and the [[Dominican Republic]] to the country would be suspended for 30 days, beginning on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-ocho-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=Suben a 10 los casos por coronavirus en Venezuela|last=Torrealba|first=Diego|date=14 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Stay-at-home order|Stay-at-home orders]] were announced on 15 March, when the country registered another seven cases, and introduced the next day across six states and the [[Caracas]] area.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-orders-collective-quarantive-in-response-to-coronavirus-idUKKBN2121B8|title=Venezuela orders 'collective quarantine' in response to coronavirus|date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020|work=Reuters}}</ref> The orders were dubbed \"collective quarantine\"; there are exceptions for transportation, health, and delivery of food.<ref name=\"reuters\" /> It was on the first day of the quarantine across six states, 16 March, that Argentina's ambassador in Venezuela, Eduardo Porretti, tested positive for the virus,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=454175|title=Embajador de Argentina en Venezuela contrajo coronavirus|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> and [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] announced that sixteen new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 33. Based on this, Maduro extended the quarantine to the entire country.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/401253/maduro-anuncia-que-hay-33-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela-16mar/|title=Maduro confirma 33 casos de coronavirus en Venezuela y ordena \"cuarentena total\" #16Mar|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Runrunes]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Venezuela went into lockdown on 17 March, authorities in Brazil partially [[Brazil\u2013Venezuela border|closed their border]] with Venezuela. Brazilian Health Minister [[Luiz Henrique Mandetta]] had urged closure of the border due to Venezuela's collapsing health system.<ref name=\"RBR\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-brazil-venezuela-idUSKBN2143ZS|title=Brazil partially closing Venezuela border, allowing trucks|date=18 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Venezuelan Vice-President [[Delcy Rodr\u00edguez]] announced three more cases the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2143QY|title=Quarantine threatens to deepen Venezuelan crisis as roadblocks snarl food supplies|date=17 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the afternoon, a patient that would later test positive for coronavirus fled from a hospital in Propatria, in west Caracas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/paciente-portador-de-covid-19-huyo-de-cdi-en-propatria-donde-permanecia-aislado/|title=Paciente portador de COVID-19 huy\u00f3 de CDI en Propatria donde permanec\u00eda aislado|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Carabobe\u00f1o]]|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/paciente-coronavirus-huye-del-hospital-caracas-n4195206|title=Paciente con coronavirus huye del hospital en Caracas|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=[[Diario Las Am\u00e9ricas]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Delcy Rodr\u00edguez reported that the numbers of cases had not changed since the previous day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=456588|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez: No se confirmaron nuevos casos de coronavirus en las \u00faltimas 24 horas|date=18 March 2020|website=El Nacional|language=es|url-status=live|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> By 21 March, the government reported 70 confirmed cases in the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-aislados-idLTAKBN21810Y-OUSLT|title=Venezuela usar\u00e1 cuartos de hotel para aislar casos suaves de coronavirus: ministro - Reuters|date=21 March 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> two of which were in critical condition, and with 15 labeled as recovered (showing no symptoms after five days).<ref name=\"mpps-latest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vtv.gob.ve/venezuela-70-casos-confirmados-covid-19-15-recuperados/|title=Venezuela registra 70 casos confirmados de Covid-19 y 15 de ellos se han recuperado satisfactoriamente|work=Venezolana de Televisi\u00f3n|language=es|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Rodr\u00edguez{{Who|date=April 2020}} said the two critical cases were hospitalized in private clinics in Miranda state and that their treatment was being provided for free through the Ministry of Health.<ref name=\"mpps-latest\" />\n\nEconomic measures to deal with the consequences of the pandemic were announced on 22 March, along with seven more cases.<ref name=\"reuters22march\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN21A02V|title=Venezuela prohibits company layoffs and suspends credit collections over coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the plans, rent and credit payments will be suspended for six months, accompanied by compensation in [[Currency of Venezuela|local currency]] for property owners and medium-sized businesses.<ref name=\"reuters22march\" /> The measures also extende a 2015 policy that prevents companies from firing employees through December 2020.<ref name=\"reuters22march\" />\n\nThe first confirmed death from the disease was announced on 26 March.<ref name=\"Reutersfirstdeath\" /> Another death was reported the next day.<ref name=\"2death\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/segunda-muerte-por-covid-19-y-suben-a-113-los-contagiados/|title=Segunda muerte por COVID-19 y suben a 113 los contagiados\n|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=27 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"27MarchReuters\">{{cite news|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-idLTAKBN21E3KX-OUSLT|title=Venezuela reporta segunda muerte por COVID-19, casos ascienden a 113 en el pa\u00eds|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=Reuters|language=es}}</ref> Also on 27 March, Delcy Rodr\u00edguez met with [[Prime Minister of Trinidad and Tobago]] [[Keith Rowley]], with the meeting focused on the strategy being deployed in both countries to combat the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gov.tt/content/prime-minister-meets-venezuelan-vice-president#.XoJKjogzaUn|title=Prime Minister Meets with Venezuelan Vice President|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=gov.tt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> There was also controversy on this day, when NGO [[PROVEA|Provea]] revealed that around ninety people coming from [[C\u00facuta]], [[Colombia]], were forcefully isolated on 25 March by the [[Venezuelan National Guard|National Guard]] in [[Barquisimeto|Barqusimeto]], [[Lara (state)|Lara]], without food or proper sanitary conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cronica.uno/en-lara-la-gnb-somete-a-cuarentena-forzosa-a-mas-de-60-personas-que-regresaron-de-cucuta/|title=En Lara la GNB somete a cuarentena forzosa a m\u00e1s de 60 personas que regresaron de C\u00facuta|last=Sarmiento|first=Mabel|date=27 March 2020|website=Cr\u00f3nica Uno|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/provea-aislan-a-90-personas-de-manera-forzosa-en-barquisimeto/|title=Provea: Aislan a 90 personas de manera forzosa en Barquisimeto|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=[[El Carabobe\u00f1o]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/ong-denuncia-confinamiento-forzado-90-venezolanos-covid-19-n4195775|title=ONG denuncia \"confinamiento forzado\" de 90 venezolanos por COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Diario las Am\u00e9ricas]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>  \n\n===April===\n[[Ministry of Communication and Information (Venezuela)|Information Minister]] [[Jorge Rodr\u00edguez (politician)|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]] first reported that there were more recoveries than new infections in Venezuela on 11 April.<ref name=\"EP11A\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/jorge-rodriguez-asegura-que-venezuela-no-reporta-nuevos-casos-de-covid-19-este-11abril/|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez: Venezuela no reporta nuevos casos de COVID-19 este #11abril|last=Leonett|first=Vanessa|date=11 April 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\"efectococuyo11a\">{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/rodriguez-asegura-que-en-venezuela-se-hacen-25-000-pruebas-diarias-para-covid-19/|title=Rodr\u00edguez asegura que en Venezuela se hacen \"25.000 pruebas diarias\" para COVID-19|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Ibis Le\u00f3n|language=es|date=11 April 2020|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> Delcy Rodr\u00edguez and Nicol\u00e1s Maduro announced an extension of the national quarantine and state of alarm for 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-alarma-idLTAKCN21U02U-OUSLT|title=Venezuela extiende 30 d\u00edas m\u00e1s el estado de alarma y cuarentena por coronavirus - Reuters|date=12 April 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter a sudden rise of the number of cases in [[Margarita Island]], Nicol\u00e1s Maduro announced a [[curfew]] the entire state of [[Nueva Esparta]] on 19 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/salud-coronavirus-venezuela-casos-idLTAKBN222031-OUSLT|title=Venezuela impone nuevo toque de queda en una isla por salto de casos de coronavirus - Reuters|date=19 April 2020|website=Reuters|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> 41 of the cases at the time, were related to ''Roberto Vahlis Baseball Academy''. Some of its member had just arrived from [[Dominican Republic]] by plane.<ref name=efectococuyo19a/>\n\n== Measures ==\n\n=== Executive response ===\nOn 12 March, [[President of Venezuela|President]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] declared a public health emergency in the country and suspended all inbound flights from [[Europe]] and [[Colombia]] for 30 days. He also announced that public gatherings were to be suspended and that the government would be evaluating whether or not to suspend flights from other regions in the coming weeks. According to Maduro, there had been 30 suspected cases in Venezuela, but these had all tested negative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-pol/venezuelas-maduro-suspends-all-flights-from-europe-and-colombia-for-a-month-over-coronavirus-concerns-idUSKBN20Z2W9|title=Venezuela's Maduro suspends flights from Europe, Colombia over coronavirus concerns|date=12 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=13 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter the first cases in the country were confirmed, Vice-President Delcy Rodr\u00edguez instructed all the passengers of the 5 and 8 March [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] 6673 flight{{Clarify|reason=Is it 5 or 8 March; the rest of the sentence indicates only one flight, which can't have been on two days|date=April 2020}} to immediately enter into a mandatory preventive quarantine, since the two cases were from this flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/gran-caracas/gobierno-convoca-a-viajeros-del-vuelo-6673-presentarse-para-cumplir-la-cuarentena/|title=Gobierno convoca a viajeros del vuelo 6673 presentarse para cumplir la cuarentena|date=13 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRodr\u00edguez announced that all classes would be suspended at public and private schools from Monday 16 March until further notice,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caraotadigital.net/nacionales/delcy-rodriguez-anuncio-suspension-de-clases-tras-llegada-del-coronavirus-a-venezuela|title=Anuncian suspensi\u00f3n de clases tras llegada del Coronavirus a Venezuela|date=13 March 2020|website=Noticias de Venezuela y el Mundo - Caraota Digital|language=es|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> while [[N\u00e9stor Reverol]] announced that the government would provide border control authorities with face masks, gloves and thermometers, without mentioning supplies for citizens and hospitals.<ref name=\"PH\" /> Reverol also announced that the operational control of all the police forces would be transferred to the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|Armed Forces]] in order to coordinate the action and contingency plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.panorama.com.ve/ciudad/Reverol-No-puede-entrar-ninguna-persona-al-territorio-nacional-sin-tapabocas-20200313-0044.html|title=Reverol: \"No puede entrar ninguna persona al territorio nacional sin tapabocas\"|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=Panorama|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, authorities arrested two people for spreading false information about the virus, recording a video about fake cases in [[Los Teques]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/sucesos/64379/dos-detenidos-por-difundir-informacion-falsa-sobre-el-covid-19|title=Dos detenidos por difundir informaci\u00f3n falsa sobre el Covid 19|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> SUDEBAN, the government's department related to banks and financial institutions, announced the suspension of banking activities, effective from 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eltiempo.com.ve/2020/03/15/sudeban-informo-que-actividades-bancarias-estaran-suspendidas-desde-el-lunes-comunicado/|title=Sudeban inform\u00f3 que actividades bancarias estar\u00e1n suspendidas desde el lunes (+Comunicado)|date=15 March 2020|website=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDefense Minister [[Vladimir Padrino L\u00f3pez]] announced that, effective from 16 March, the Armed Forces would control access to the six states and the [[Capital District (Venezuela)|Capital District]] declared by Nicol\u00e1s Maduro to be in quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/padrino-lopez-a-partir-del-16mar-la-fan-controlara-el-acceso-a-los-estados-en-cuarentena/|title=Padrino L\u00f3pez: Fuerza Armada controlar\u00e1 acceso a los estados en cuarentena|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Maduro reversed the country's official position against the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF), asking the institution for US$5&nbsp;billion to combat the pandemic,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/economia/Maduro-FMI-millones-dolares-COVID-19_0_1006850528.html|title=Maduro le pide al FMI 5 mil millones de d\u00f3lares para actuar contra el COVID-19|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[EFE]]|publisher=eldiario.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a first during Maduro's presidency; he has been a critic of the institution.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berwick|first=Angus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2143QY|title=Quarantine threatens to deepen Venezuelan crisis as roadblocks snarl food supplies|date=17 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/420afb1fa856dedcc4cb3eddcd8ac0a2|title=Venezuela seeks emergency $5 billion IMF loan to fight virus|date=17 March 2020|website=AP NEWS|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The IMF also has had conflicts with the Venezuelan government in the past, as Maduro's predecessor [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] had pledged to cut ties with the fund in 2007, and the IMF suspended US$400&nbsp;million in [[special drawing rights]] during the [[Venezuelan presidential crisis]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-17/venezuela-requests-5-billion-from-imf-to-fight-coronavirus|title=Venezuela Requests $5 Billion from IMF to Fight Coronavirus|date=17 March 2020|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=17 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> The IMF rejected the deal as it was not clear, among its member states, on who it recognizes as Venezuela's president, Nicol\u00e1s Maduro or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/420afb1fa856dedcc4cb3eddcd8ac0a2|title=IMF rejects Maduro's bid for emergency loan to fight virus|date=17 March 2020|website=AP NEWS|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> According to a report by [[Bloomberg News|''Bloomberg'']], the Maduro administration also tried to request aid of $1 billion from the IMF after the first request was denied.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Vasquez|first=Alex|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-21/rejected-venezuela-returns-to-the-imf-seeking-1-billion-in-aid|title=Rejected Venezuela Returns to IMF Seeking $1 Billion in Aid|date=21 March 2020|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Rodr\u00edguez announced that 4,000 diagnosis kits were delivered from [[China]] to test for coronavirus disease. The government said that the Chinese diagnosis kits would benefit 300,000 Venezuelans and thanked the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] and its [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] for its generosity. In a separate measure, Venezuela's INEA maritime authority has prohibited crews aboard ships docking in the country's ports from disembarking.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela/venezuela-lifts-coronavirus-cases-to-42-thanks-china-for-aid-idUSKBN2163I9|title=Venezuela lifts coronavirus cases to 42, thanks China for aid|date=19 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Maduro announced that he had received a letter from the [[United Nations]] (UN) Resident Coordinator and [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) Resident Representative Peter Grohmann, confirming that the organization \"is ready to support the Venezuelan government in its fight against COVID-19.\" Maduro stressed that the UN has taken concrete actions, particularly in the areas of health and water, sanitation and hygiene, and \"will support the Ministry of Health in the care and containment of the coronavirus.\" Likewise, they will offer support in the disclosure of reliable and updated information.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://actualidad.rt.com/actualidad/346828-maduro-confirma-venezuela-recibira-ayuda|title=Maduro confirma que Venezuela recibir\u00e1 ayuda de la ONU para combatir el coronavirus|date=19 March 2020|work=[[RT en Espa\u00f1ol]]|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Maduro said that [[Russia]] was considering \"a significant donation of special humanitarian aid\" to the country, such as medical equipment and kits for the diagnosis of COVID-19, which was expected to arrive by the following week.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferm\u00edn Kancev|first=Mar\u00eda Victoria|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/maduro-rusia-enviara-ayuda-humanitaria-a-venezuela-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Maduro: Rusia enviar\u00e1 ayuda humanitaria a Venezuela por el coronavirus|date=20 March 2020|work=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|access-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> On 23 March, Foreign Minister [[Jorge Arreaza]] and Russian ambassador Sergei Melik-Bagdasarov announced that 10,000 diagnosis kits had been delivered from Russia, with more to be supplied in future shipments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ariza|first=Joselyn|url=http://mppre.gob.ve/2020/03/23/rusia-envia-insumos-medicos-venezuela-detectar-covid19/|title=Rusia env\u00eda insumos m\u00e9dicos a Venezuela para detectar Covid-19|date=23 March 2020|publisher=Venezuelan Ministry of Foreign Affairs|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> In a [[Twitter|tweet]], President Maduro thanked the [[Government of Russia|Russian government]] and President [[Vladimir Putin]] for their generosity and for standing in solidarity with the Venezuelan people.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NicolasMaduro |number=1242281781740670980|title=Llegaron a Venezuela 10 mil kits de pruebas diagn\u00f0sticas procedentes de la Federaci\u00f0n de Rusia para el despistaje del COVID-19. En nombre de nuestro pueblo, agradezco la solidaridad y la cooperaci\u00f0n del hermano Presidente Vlad\u00edmir Putin y del pueblo ruso. \u00a1Un Abrazo! |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMaduro announced several economic measures on 23 March to deal with unemployment, the assumption of wage payment by the state, the suspension of rent and credit interests payments, the assignment of new bonds, the flexibility of new loans and credit, the prohibition of the telecommunication services and the guarantee of CLAP ([[Local Committees for Supply and Production]]) supplies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/economia/medidas-economicas-populistas-anunciadas-por-maduro-podrian-enterrar-al-sector-privado/|title=Medidas econ\u00f3micas populistas anunciadas por Maduro podr\u00edan enterrar al sector privado|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Erika|date=23 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== National Assembly response ===\nDisputed [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] leader and disputed [[Venezuelan presidential crisis|acting president]] [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] said that the country is experiencing one of the most serious health crises in its history, caused by the inaction of the Maduro government, and announced a series of measures in order to take \"responsible measures against the pandemic.\"<ref name=\"infobae\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/03/13/guaido-anuncio-una-redefinicion-de-la-agenda-de-protestas-por-el-coronavirus-es-momento-de-que-el-regimen-deje-entrar-la-ayuda-humanitaria/|title=Guaid\u00f3 anunci\u00f3 una redefinici\u00f3n de la agenda de protestas por el coronavirus: \"Es momento de que el r\u00e9gimen deje entrar la ayuda humanitaria\"|date=13 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"guaidocorona\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/guaido-anuncia-redefinicion-de-las-convocatorias-de-calle-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Guaid\u00f3 anuncia redefinici\u00f3n de las convocatorias de calle por el coronavirus|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=13 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> These include the postponement of opposition protests and the creation of the Special Health Commission.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"infobae\" /> In addition, Guaid\u00f3 also called for the entry of humanitarian aid from the [[United Nations]], while explaining that health services are not impacted by [[International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis|international sanctions]].<ref name=\"guaidocorona\" />\n\nThe Committee of Electoral Candidacies, in charge of appointing a new [[National Electoral Council (Venezuela)|National Electoral Council]] (CNE), announced that it would suspend its meetings because of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/politica/64502/comite-para-designar-nuevo-cne-suspendera-reuniones|title=Comit\u00e9 para designar nuevo CNE suspender\u00e1 reuniones|last=Murillo|first=Yuskerli|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Universal (Caracas)]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Julio Castro M\u00e9ndez|Julio Castro]], head of the Special Health Commission appointed by Juan Guaid\u00f3, reported on 16 March that face masks are a prevention measure useful only for one day,  and that once used the mask loses its effectiveness and can become a source of infection; he also declared that Venezuelans have to take additional measures to deal with the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elimpulso.com/2020/03/16/julio-castro-la-mascarilla-solo-sirve-para-un-dia-puede-ser-un-foco-de-infeccion-si-se-usa-varias-veces-16mar/|title=Julio Castro: La mascarilla solo sirve para un d\u00eda, puede ser un foco de infecci\u00f3n si se usa varias veces #16Mar|last=Escalona|first=Jos\u00e9|date=16 March 2020|website=[[El Impulso]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] deputy Jes\u00fas Y\u00e1nez announced that the government of [[Taiwan]] donated 1,000 surgical masks as a measure to prevent the coronavirus pandemic. The masks were distributed in five stations of the [[Caracas Metro]] ([[Plaza Sucre station|Plaza Sucre]], [[P\u00e9rez Bonalde station|P\u00e9rez Bonalde]], [[Plaza Venezuela station|Plaza Venezuela]], [[Chacao station|Chacao]] and [[Petare station|Petare]]). Y\u00e1nez highlighted that the metro is a means of transportation used by a large part of the population and is a breeding ground for the pandemic due to the crowding of people in closed spaces, should any one of them be carrying the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/13/mil-venezolanos-recibieron-donacion-de-taiwan-para-prevenir-el-coronavirus/|title=Mil venezolanos recibieron donaci\u00f3n de Taiw\u00e1n para prevenir el coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nGuaid\u00f3's Special Health Commission collected 3,500 protection kits for caregivers at five hospitals on 16 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Berwick|first=Angus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN2132FD|title=Venezuela expands quarantine as number of coronavirus cases climbs to 33|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Guaid\u00f3 announced that he delivered medical kits to protect the health sector from the coronavirus pandemic. On his official [[Twitter]] account, he shared a video expressing that \"We are protecting a sector that today is giving everything: the health sector, our doctors and nurses. To support them is to support us all. We must bring this help to hundreds who need it\", and concluded \"We can contain this emergency. Venezuela is in our hands.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/21/en-video-guaido-entrega-kits-para-proteger-al-sector-salud-del-brote-de-coronavirus/|title=EN VIDEO: Guaid\u00f3 entrega kits para proteger al sector salud del brote de coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=jguaido|number=1241389880137125892|date=21 March 2020|title=Estamos protegiendo a un sector que hoy est\u00e1 d\u00e1ndolo todo: el sector salud, nuestros m\u00e9dicos y enfermeras. Apoyarlos es apoyarnos todos. Esta ayuda debemos llevarla a cientos que la necesitan. Podemos contener esta emergencia. Venezuela est\u00e1 en nuestras manos. #AuxilioParaVzla|author=Juan Guaid\u00f3}}</ref> Guaid\u00f3 also announced the creation of the Human Rights Observatory as a response to the increase of human rights violations in the country during the social isolation orders.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.europapress.es/internacional/noticia-guaido-denuncia-aumento-violaciones-ddhh-venezuela-estallido-pandemia-20200323130355.html|title=Guaid\u00f3 denuncia un aumento de las violaciones de los DDHH en Venezuela desde el estallido de la pandemia|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=[[Europa Press]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGuaid\u00f3 called for the creation of a \"national emergency government\", not lead by Maduro, on 28 March. According to Guaid\u00f3, a loan of US$1.2 billion was ready to be given in support of a power-sharing coalition between pro-Maduro officials, the military and the opposition in order to fight the pandemic in Venezuela. If accepted, the money would go to assist families affected by the disease and its economic consequences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/645b00c744ded5db872e02b933609deb|title=Guaido urges unity government backed by loans to fight virus|last=Goodman|first=Joshua|date=29 March 2020|website=Associated Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Other responses ===\n[[Baltazar Enrique Porras Cardozo|Baltazar Porras]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caracas|Apostolic Administrator of Caracas]], announced the suspension of ecclesiastic activities on 15 March, while assuring that temples would remain open, asking Venezuelans to avoid crowded places and to remain calm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vpitv.com/ultimas_noticias_sobre_venezuela/actividades-eclesiasticas/|title=Suspendieron actividades eclesi\u00e1sticas en Venezuela tras brote de coronavirus|last=|first=|date=15 March 2020|website=[[VPItv]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Health Ministry certified the microbiology laboratory of the [[University of the Andes (Venezuela)|University of the Andes]], in [[M\u00e9rida (state)|M\u00e9rida state]], to start carrying out tests to detect the presence of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]], the coronavirus responsible for the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] disease, on 18 March. Once the necessary supplies are received, the laboratory will be able to perform up to 20 tests per day and would be the second laboratory in the country to perform detection tests after the National Hygiene Institute in Caracas; it would be expected to carry out tests for the states of M\u00e9rida, [[T\u00e1chira]], [[Trujillo (state)|Trujillo]] and [[Barinas (state)|Barinas]], and possibly other states in the west, as it is closer than the Hygiene Institute in Caracas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/los-andes/laboratorio-de-microbiologia-de-la-ula-hara-pruebas-para-detectar-coronavirus/|title=Laboratorio de microbiolog\u00eda de la ULA har\u00e1 pruebas para detectar coronavirus|last=Fern Rodr\u00edguez|first=Mar\u00eda|date=18 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThree men that were playing [[dominoes]] during the quarantine were murdered on 21 March in the [[23 de Enero|23 de Enero parish]], in Caracas, and two more were injured.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/sucesos/colectivos-imponen-toque-de-queda-en-el-23-de-enero-por-el-coronavirus/|title=Colectivos imponen toque de queda en el 23 de Enero por el coronavirus|last=Galaviz|first=Daisy|date=23 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> According to neighbors and relatives, a dozen members of the ''[[Colectivo (Venezuela)|colectivo]]'' Tres Ra\u00edces arrived while they were playing and were responsible for their deaths; the witnesses accused the ''colectivo'' members of being linked with [[Iris Varela]], Minister of Popular Power for the Prison Service, being linked to a [[Cuerpo de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas, Penales y Criminal\u00edsticas|CICPC]] officer, and of wearing FAES and [[Venezuelan National Police|National Police]] uniforms, announcing that they would protest as a response to the killings, in defiance of the quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/sucesos/familiares-senalan-a-colectivos-por-asesinato-de-tres-vecinos-del-23-de-enero/|title=Familiares se\u00f1alan colectivos por asesinato tres vecinos del 23 de Enero|date=22 March 2020|website=[[El Pitazo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ''colectivo'' denied the accusations of being related to the government or police, saying that the murders were instead motivated by revenge.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn late March, the ''[[Colectivo (Venezuela)|colectivos]]'' Tres Ra\u00edces and [[La Piedrita]] started imposing a paramilitary-enforced [[curfew]] in the 23 de Enero parish, increasing repression and imposing closure times to businesses.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\n\n=== Government reactions ===\nMaduro asked people to not politicize the pandemic,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.entornointeligente.com/maduro-pide-no-politizar-el-tema-del-coronavirus-mientras-apunta-el-dedo-a-los-eeuu-y-la-oposicin-videos/|title=Maduro pide no politizar el tema del coronavirus mientras apunta el dedo a los EEUU y la oposici\u00f3n (VIDEOS)|date=13 March 2020|work=Entorno Inteligente|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> while also expressing concern as to how the country could control the pandemic with the [[International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis|United States-imposed sanctions]].<ref name=\"FirstCases\" /> Maduro called on [[US President]] [[Donald Trump]] to lift the sanctions so the country could acquire necessary medical supplies.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Laya|first=Patricia|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/venezuela-doctors-fear-pandemic-will-overwhelm-wrecked-hospitals|title=Venezuela Conducts 'Tens' of Virus Tests and Bans Europe Flights|date=12 March 2020|work=Bloomberg|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJuan Guaid\u00f3 denounced that since the start of the pandemic, human rights violations by Maduro's administration had increased, citing the murders in the 23 de Enero parish, the arrest of [[Darvinson Rojas]], and human rights abuses against political prisoners, who are held in prisons with a high infection risk. Guaid\u00f3 announced the creation of a Human Rights Observatory as a response.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n=== Other reactions ===\nThe Venezuelan Medical Federation expressed condemnation at how a medic in Zulia was forced to leave for Colombia after denouncing the inability of Venezuela to cope if the disease arrived;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/fmv-denuncio-amedrentamiento-a-medicos-tras-estado-de-alarma-por-coronavirus/|title=FMV denunci\u00f3 amedrentamiento a m\u00e9dicos tras estado de alarma por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> it also asked for the release of the political prisoners in the country, who are vulnerable to the virus, specifically [[Roberto Marrero]], [[Juan Requesens]], and other lawmakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/presidente-de-la-fmv-exhorta-a-que-se-liberen-a-presos-politicos-por-coronavirus/|title=Presidente de la FMV exhorta a que se liberen a presos pol\u00edticos por coronavirus|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Anzo\u00e1tegui|Anzo\u00e1tegui state]], nurses denounced the lack of face masks, gloves and disposable gowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/oriente/enfermeras-denuncian-falta-de-mascarillas-guantes-y-bata-desechable-en-anzoategui/|title=Enfermeras denuncian falta de mascarillas, guantes y bata desechable en Anzo\u00e1tegui|last=Pellicani|first=Giovanna|date=16 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the Chinese Embassy in [[Caracas]] rejected the accusations made by [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] deputies against China in calling the pandemic the \"China or Wuhan virus.\" In a statement, the embassy said it \"strongly rejects the attacks and unfounded and arbitrary accusations of some Venezuelan deputies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.eluniversal.com/politica/64829/embajada-china-rechaza-acusaciones-de-parlamentarios-venezolanos|title=Embajada china rechaza acusaciones de parlamentarios venezolanos|date=19 March 2020|work=[[[[El Universal (Caracas)]] (Venezuela)]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nTransparencia Venezuela asked for transparency and access to public information regarding the handling of the emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/403571/transparencia-venezuela-exige-informacion-veraz/|title=Transparencia Venezuela exige informaci\u00f3n veraz|last=|first=|date=2020-04-07|website=Runrun.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nMedia outlets, such as [[El Nacional (Venezuela)|''El Nacional'']], denounced the price increase of face masks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/economia/coronavirus-en-venezuela-denuncian-encarecimiento-de-las-mascarillas/|title=Coronavirus en Venezuela: encarecimiento de las mascarillas|last=Villarreal|first=Karina|date=13 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/venezuela/como-es-la-situacion-en-venezuela-frente-al-coronavirus-472324|title=Coronavirus en Venezuela: $ 140 mil por caja de tapabocas|date=13 March 2020|website=El Tiempo|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://versionfinal.com.ve/ciudad/tapabocas-desechables-se-elevan-de-7-000-a-80-000-bolivares-tras-confirmacion-de-coronavirus/|title=Tapabocas desechables se elevan de 7.000 a 80.000 bol\u00edvares tras confirmaci\u00f3n de coronavirus|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=Diario Versi\u00f3n Final|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Outlets have also reported on the violation of the quarantine for reasons such as buying food, medicines, and both cleaning and hygiene products, as well as the public services crisis, including the lack of drinking water, electric power, cooking gas, telephone signal and [[waste collection]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/venezuela/la-necesidad-obliga-el-pueblo-en-la-calle-a-pesar-de-la-cuarentena/|title=La necesidad obliga: el pueblo en la calle a pesar de la cuarentena|last=Brito|first=Estefani|date=26 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== International sanctions ====\n{{see also|International sanctions during the Venezuelan crisis}}\nThe [[Embassy of the United States, Caracas|United States Embassy in Venezuela]] rejected claims from [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] and [[Jorge Arreaza]] that sanctions are preventing the government from purchasing medical supplies, saying that \u201cmedicines, medical supplies, spare parts and components for medical devices in Venezuela, or to people from third countries who buy specifically for resale from Venezuela are excluded from the sanctions.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2020/03/14/embajada-virtual-de-eeuu-en-venezuela-se-las-canto-clarito-a-maduro-tras-llorantina-por-sanciones/|title=Embajada virtual de EEUU en Venezuela se las cant\u00f3 clarito a Maduro tras llorantina por sanciones|date=14 March 2020|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=usembassyve|number=1238476780731850757|date=13 March 2020|title=Medicinas, insumos m\u00e9dicos, piezas de repuesto y componentes para productos sanitarios en Venezuela, o a personas de terceros pa\u00edses que compran espec\u00edficamente para reventa a Venezuela quedan excluidos de las sanciones estadounidenses. Para que sepan @NicolasMaduro @jaarreaza|author=Embajada Virtual de los EE.UU., Venezuela}}</ref> Days later, Foreign Minister [[Jorge Arreaza]] called the statements \"the height of impudence and falsehood.\" He declared that Venezuelan government assets worth more than US$5&nbsp;billion were blocked overseas, in addition to \"Venezuela's ban on access to the international [[Bank|banking system]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.2001.com.ve/en-la-agenda/224732/jorge-arreaza--bloqueo-economico-contra-venezuela-afecta-adquisicion-de-insumos.html|title=Jorge Arreaza: bloqueo econ\u00f3mico contra Venezuela afecta adquisici\u00f3n de insumos|date=21 March 2020|work=[[Diario 2001]]|access-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agencia Venezolana de Noticias]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nFormer Attorney General [[Luisa Ortega D\u00edaz]] declared that Maduro \"lied\" when saying that there were no medicines in the country because of the sanctions, saying that the reasons were incompetence and [[Corruption in Venezuela|corruption]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/ortega-diaz-maduro-miente-al-decir-que-no-hay-medicinas-por-las-sanciones/|title=Ortega D\u00edaz: Maduro miente al decir que no hay medicinas por las sanciones|last=Pitazo|first=Redacci\u00f3n El|date=16 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs|US Acting Assistant Secretary for Western Hemisphere Affairs]] [[Michael Kozak]] also accused Maduro of lying, saying that [[United States sanctions|U.S. sanctions]] never block food or medicine purchases. He emphasized that [[shortages in Venezuela]] resulted from \"the regime\u2019s theft of the nation\u2019s wealth.\"<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WHAAsstSecty|number=1240784224988381184|date=19 March 2020|title=More lies from #Maduro, author of the #MaduroCrisis, about #Venezuela\u2019s tragedy. U.S. sanctions NEVER block food or medicine. Shortages in Venezuela result from the regime\u2019s theft of the nation\u2019s wealth. #EstamosUnidosVE|author=Michael G. Kozak}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://albertonews.com/coronavirus/kozak-reitero-que-las-sanciones-de-eeuu-al-regimen-de-maduro-no-bloquean-comida-o-medicinas/|title=Kozak reiter\u00f3 que las sanciones de EEUU al r\u00e9gimen de Maduro 'no bloquean comida o medicinas'|date=20 March 2020|website=AlbertoNews|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nEconomist [[Francisco Rodr\u00edguez (economist)|Francisco Rodr\u00edguez]] declared that the sanctions \"severely harm the capacity of affected countries\" to respond to the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://cepr.net/press-release/us-government-should-immediately-lift-economic-sanctions-to-avoid-causing-more-deaths-from-pandemic-economists-say/|title=US Government Should Immediately Lift Economic Sanctions to Avoid Causing More Deaths From Pandemic, Economists Say|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=Center for Economic and Policy Research|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|sure=y|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 24 March, [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|UN High Commissioner for Human Rights]] [[Michelle Bachelet]] called for any sanctions imposed on Venezuela and other countries facing the pandemic such as [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cuba|Cuba]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe|Zimbabwe]] to be \"urgently reevaluated\" in order to avoid pushing strained medical systems into collapse. In a statement, Bachelet said: \"At this crucial time, both for global public health reasons, and to support the rights and lives of millions of people in these countries, sectoral sanctions should be eased or suspended.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1060092|title=Ease sanctions against countries fighting COVID-19: UN human rights chief|date=24 March 2020|website=UN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/world/bachelet-calls-easing-sanctions-enable-medical-systems-fight-covid-19-and-limit-global|title=Bachelet calls for easing of sanctions to enable medical systems to fight COVID-19 and limit global contagion|date=24 March 2020|work=[[ReliefWeb]]|access-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]]}}</ref> Bachelet also accentuated the need to protect health workers in these countries as authorities should not punish professionals that point out the deficiencies in the state response to the crisis.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n===International concern===\n{{See also|Health care in Venezuela|Shortages in Venezuela}}\nInternational concern was raised before the first cases were reported, as Venezuela's [[Health care in Venezuela|health care system]] has completely collapsed due to the [[Crisis in Venezuela|ongoing crisis]], meaning its already suffering population is especially vulnerable to the spread of a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"Healthcare\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/venezuela-doctors-fear-pandemic-will-overwhelm-wrecked-hospitals|title=Venezuela Conducts 'Tens' of Virus Tests and Bans Europe Flights|date=12 March 2020|work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|access-date=13 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPer the ''[[Global Health Security Index]]'', Venezuela's health system is ranked among the worst in the world in its ability to detect, quickly respond, and mitigate a pandemic.<ref name=\"ghsindex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ghsindex.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/2019-Global-Health-Security-Index.pdf|title=2019 Global Health Security Index|date=22 October 2019|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> Hospitals are plagued by chronic shortages of supplies, including eye protectors, gloves, masks, and soap.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-idUSKBN20X2F1|title=Buckets for toilets, recycled gloves: Venezuelan hospitals await coronavirus unprepared|date=10 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=11 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> Due to [[Shortages in Venezuela|ongoing shortages of resources]], hospitals must also constantly deal with chronic lack of staff, thus making the response to treating a large number of infected patients significantly more challenging.<ref name=\":0\" /> Patients are also often turned away at hospitals due to overcrowding, or asked to bring in their own gauze, IV solution, or syringes, while there are often no hygiene facilities like toilets, and power outages are a regular occurrence.<ref name=\"Healthcare\" />\n\nThe [[Pan American Health Organization]] (PAHO) said that it would be prioritizing Venezuela alongside Haiti and other Central and South American countries because of \u201cchallenges to their health systems.\u201d<ref name=\"PH\" />\n\n''[[Associated Press]]'' reported that experts are worried that the [[Venezuelan refugee crisis]] could worsen the spread of the virus.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Prison system ====\n''[[Reuters]]'' reported that Venezuela's notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary prisons could spread the coronavirus \"like a fast-moving fire.\" Venezuelan prisons frequently lack bathrooms, people sleep on floors, and many inmates spend their days without shirts or shoes on, in part to combat the infernal heat of windowless facilities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellsworth|first=Brian|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-prisons/overcrowded-and-unsanitary-venezuelas-prisons-brace-for-coronavirus-idUSKBN215323|title=Overcrowded and unsanitary, Venezuela's prisons brace for coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sequera|first2=Vivian}}</ref> This has caused [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]] [[Mike Pompeo]] to demand the Maduro government release six [[Citgo]] executives, held in prison since 2017, on humanitarian grounds.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SecPompeo|number=1240617609441280002|date=19 March 2020|title=It is past time for the Maduro regime to release the #Citgo6 who are currently languishing in the notorious Helicoide prison in #Venezuela. 2+ years in prison with no evidence brought against them; 18 hearings cancelled. Unacceptable.|author=Secretary Pompeo}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Pompeo said that all six men have weakened [[immune system]]s and \"face a grave health risk if they become infected\" with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200319-us-demands-venezuela-free-citgo-executives-as-virus-hits|title=US demands Venezuela free Citgo executives as virus hits|date=19 March 2020|work=[[France 24]]|access-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 84 out of 518 inmates escaped from a prison in San Carlos, [[Zulia]], after restrictions against the pandemic were announced, including jail visits. Mayor Bladimir Labrador declared that ten prisoners were killed during the prison break and that two policemen were detained for complicity. According to Carlos Nieto Palma from the NGO Ventana a la Libertad, the suspension of visits directly affects the prisoner's nutrition, given that there was no state-sponsored program to feed them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2020/03/19/5e72c06f21efa09a6a8b462a.html|title=Las restricciones por el coronavirus provocan una fuga de presos que deja 10 muertos en Venezuela|date=19 March 2020|website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|publisher=AFP|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The NGO Provea denounced \"grave human rights violations\" after a military spokesperson announced the \"neutralization\" of 35 escapees.  State authorities later declared that the there were eight deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talcualdigital.com/provea-denuncia-asesinato-de-35-presos-fugados-de-reten-en-zulia/|title=Provea denuncia asesinato de 35 presos fugados de ret\u00e9n en Zulia|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=[[Tal Cual]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n\nAs a result of the pandemic's economic impact some business have sought to supplement lost business with deliveries, though exact figures remain obscure and the services are prohibitively costly for average Venezuelans. Some have started to make deliveries to support their families using bicycles instead of motorcycles due to [[gasoline]] shortages.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-transpor/for-struggling-venezuelans-in-quarantine-an-opportunity-in-delivery-services-idUSKCN21Y1VN |title=For struggling Venezuelans in quarantine, an opportunity in delivery services |date=April 16, 2020 |work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Non-government estimates ==\nOn 18 March, four cases were extraofficially reported in [[El Helicoide]], three women and a male officer of the motorized brigade of the [[Venezuelan National Police|National Police]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=456613|title=Detectaron cuatro casos de coronavirus en El Helicoide|date=18 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/03/19/los-presos-politicos-de-venezuela-estan-riesgo-por-el-coronavirus-se-detectaron-cuatro-casos-de-funcionarios-contagiados-en-la-carcel-de-el-helicoide/|title=Los presos pol\u00edticos de Venezuela est\u00e1n en riesgo por el coronavirus: se detectaron cuatro casos en la c\u00e1rcel de El Helicoide|date=19 March 2020|website=[[Infobae]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a person self-identified as a member of the [[Tupamaro (Venezuela)|Tupamaro]] [[Colectivo (Venezuela)|''colectivo'']] in the [[23 de Enero|23 de Enero parish]] of Caracas declared to his community with a [[megaphone]] that a case was confirmed, specifically in Block 39, asking his neighbors to stay home and to prevent other blocks from being infected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/gran-caracas/coronavirus-colectivos-del-23-de-enero-aseguran-un-caso-en-bloque-39/|title=Coronavirus Colectivos del 23 de Enero aseguran un caso en el bloque 39|date=20 March 2020|website=El Pitazo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=457792|title=[VIDEO] Tupamaros aseguran que el coronavirus ya lleg\u00f3 al 23 de Enero|date=20 March 2020|website=[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nVenezuelan newspaper ''[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]'', reported a total of 65 cases for 20 March, according to undisclosed sources from the Health Ministry.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.elnacional.com/venezuela/venezuela-registro-19-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-este-viernes/|title=Venezuela registr\u00f3 otros 19 casos de coronavirus este viernes|work=El Nacional|language=es|date=23 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> On that day the ministry did not report any official numbers, the toll was officially updated the next day going from 42 to 70.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/rr-es-plus/401742/cifras-de-coronavirus-presentadas-por-el-gobierno-de-maduro-revelan-incongruencias/|title=Cifras de coronavirus presentadas por el gobierno de Maduro revelan incongruencias|date=20 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, before the official report on 23 March, ''El Nacional'' reported 84 cases according undisclosed source from the Health Ministry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com/?p=460967|title=Venezuela registr\u00f3 otros siete casos por coronavirus y la cifra de contagios se elev\u00f3 a 84|date=23 March 2020|website=El Nacional|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJuan Guaid\u00f3 has questioned the veracity of the official number of cases, stating that there are inconsistencies in the estimates given.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diariolasamericas.com/america-latina/guaido-asegura-que-hay-incongruencias-cifras-del-regimen-covid-19-n4195450|title=Guaid\u00f3 asegura que hay \"incongruencias\" en cifras del r\u00e9gimen sobre COVID-19|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=[[Diario Las Americas]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with [[El Nuevo Herald]] on 22 March, Guaid\u00f3 declared that the number of confirmed cases in Venezuela could be more than two hundred, according to opposition estimates, contrary to the 70 cases that Maduro's administration recognized at the moment. El Nuevo Herald reported that internal sources extraofficially confirmed that estimate, that  according to said sources there were 181 confirmed cases on the morning of 21 March and a total of 298 in observation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Delgado|first=Antonio Mar\u00eda|url=https://www.elnuevoherald.com/noticias/mundo/america-latina/venezuela-es/article241409051.html|title=Exclusiva: Maduro oculta gravedad del coronavirus. Hay m\u00e1s de 200 casos en Venezuela, dice Guaid\u00f3|date=22 March 2020|work=[[El Nuevo Herald]]|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Authorities actions on reporting ==\n{{See also|Censorship in Venezuela|Censorship and media control during the Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\nOn 13 March, [[Delta Amacuro]] indigenous leader and journalist Melquiades \u00c1vila, who has criticized health infrastructure in the country, questioned publicly through Facebook \"will our hospital be ready for coronavirus?\u201d and joked Maduro's claim that 46 hospitals were prepared for COVID-19. The Governor of Delta Amacuro Lizeta Hern\u00e1ndez and member of the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]], sent the state army to detain \u00c1vila. When asked why by ''Reuters'' on the matter, she said that it was to \u201corient\u201d \u00c1vila and ensure he was being \u201cserious and responsible\u201d.<ref name=reuters24march>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-venezuela-insight/as-coronavirus-hits-venezuela-maduro-further-quashes-dissent-idUSKBN21C1TA|title=As coronavirus hits Venezuela, Maduro further quashes dissent|date=25 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live|author=Angus Berwick|author2= Sarah Kinosian|author3= Maria Ramirez}}</ref>\n\nAn opposition lawmaker, Tony Geara, was arrested on 14 March in a roadblock after declaring that there was no running water in one of the hospitals listed as prepared by the Bolivarian government.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" /> A court charged Geara with illegal possession of explosives and weapons. Geara denies the charges.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nAccording to twelve medical workers interviewed by ''Reuters,'' security forces use roadblocks and checkpoints to shakedown medical staff.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nJulio Molinos, a medical union leader and retired technician, published a video asking the government to be transparent about hospital conditions on 15 March.  Special Action Force (FAES)  arrested Molinos, who was sentenced to house arrest on charges of compiracy and inciting hatred.<ref name=\"reuters24march\" />\n\nThe National Assembly released a webpage to provide information and health recommendations on COVID-19 but the access to the website was restricted by CANTV, the state internet provider. The censorship was denounced by Guaid\u00f3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/cantv-bloquea-web-informativa-sobre-el-covid-19-denuncia-venezuela-sin-filtro/|title=Cantv bloquea web informativa sobre el COVID-19, denuncia Venezuela Sin Filtro|last=Ferm\u00edn|first=Mar\u00eda Victoria|date=18 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest of Darvinson Rojas ===\nOn the night of 21 March 2020, journalist [[Darvinson Rojas]] was arrested at his home in [[Caracas]] by officials of the [[Venezuelan National Police|Bolivarian National Police]] (PNB) and around fifteen armed personnel from the Special Actions Force (FAES).<ref name=\"EC\">{{cite news|last1=Avenda\u00f1o|first1=Shari|url=https://efectococuyo.com/sucesos/faes-detiene-a-periodista-darvinson-rojas-y-su-familia-denuncia-sntp/|title=Faes detiene a periodista Darvinson Rojas y su familia, denuncia Sntp|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Denuncian-periodista-Darvinson-Rojas-Caracas_0_1008599157.html|title=Denuncian la detenci\u00f3n del periodista venezolano Darvinson Rojas en Caracas|date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[eldiario.es]]|agency=[[EFE]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> According to the National Union of Press Workers (SNTP), the arrest was related to the coverage of Rojas with his recent publications on the COVID-19 situation in Venezuela.<ref name=\"Van\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20200322/4820578104/denuncian-la-detencion-del-periodista-venezolano-darvinson-rojas-en-caracas.html|title=Denuncian la detenci\u00f3n del periodista venezolano Darvinson Rojas en Caracas|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|publisher=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] (CPJ) called for the immediate release of Rojas. Nathalie Southwick, CPJ coordinator, stated that \"Violently detaining a journalist and interrogating him about his sources on a vital public health issue like the COVID-19 outbreak has an undeniable chilling effect that will only discourage other journalists from reporting on the pandemic.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2020/03/venezuelan-journalist-arrested-by-special-forces-f.php|title=Venezuelan journalist arrested by special forces following coronavirus coverage|date=22 March 2020|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] demanded Rojas immediate and unconditional release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.amnesty.org/fr/documents/AMR53/2019/2020/fr/|title=Venezuela: Journalist reporting on COVID-19 jailed|date=23 March 2020|work=Amnesty International|access-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe SNTP, on 24 March, denounced that Darvinson was presented in the tribunals \"illegally\" and \"clandestinely\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/sntp-darvinson-rojas-fue-presentado-en-tribunales-de-manera-ilegal-y-clandestina/|title=Sntp: Darvinson Rojas fue presentado en tribunales de manera ilegal y clandestina|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter 12 days incarcerated, Darvinson Rojas was set free on 3 April 2020 under precautionary measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/es/venezuela-libera-a-periodista-detenido-por-publicaciones-en-twitter-sobre-covid-19/a-53001616|title=Venezuela libera a periodista detenido por publicaciones en Twitter sobre COVID-19|date=3 April 2020|website=Deutsche Welle|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n===Daily new cases and active cases===\n{{Graph\n|type=rect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors=#0000aa,#008000, #ff8000,#FF0000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13 March,14 March, 15 March, 16 March, 17 March, 18 March, 19 March, \u22ee , 21 March, 22 March, 23 March, 24 March, 25 March, 26 March, 27 March, 28 March, 29 March, 30 March, 31 March, 1 April, 2 April, 3 April, 4 April, 5 April, 6 April, 7 April, 8 April, 9 April, 10 April, 11 April,12 April,13 April,14 April,15 April,16 April,17 April,18 April,19 April,20 April\n|yAxisTitle=Number of new cases per day\n|y1=2,8,7,16,17,0,6,0,28,7,7,7,15,1,6,6,10,6,8,1,2,7,2,4,6,1,1,4,4,0,6,8,4,4,7,23,0,29,29\n|yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}\n\n{{Graph\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors= #ff8000,#008000,#40E0D0\n|showValues=\n|legend=Legend\n|xAxisTitle=Date (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13 March,14 March, 15 March, 16 March, 17 March, 18 March, 19 March, 20 March , 21 March, 22 March, 23 March, 24 March, 25 March, 26 March, 27 March, 28 March, 29 March, 30 March, 31 March, 1 April, 2 April, 3 April, 4 April, 5 April, 6 April, 7 April, 8 April, 9 April, 10 April, 11 April, 12 April, 13 April,14 April,15 April,16 April,17 April,18 April, 19 April, 20 April\n|yAxisTitle=Number of cases\n|y1=2,10,17,33,36,36,42,42,70,77,84,91,106,107,113,119,129,135,143,144,146,153, 155,159,165, 166,167,171,175,175,181,189,193,197,204,227,227,256,285\n|y2=2,10,17,33,36,36,42,42,{{#expr:70-15}},{{#expr:77-15}},{{#expr:84-15}},{{#expr:91-15}},{{#expr:106-15}},{{#expr:107-31-1}},{{#expr:113-39-2}},{{#expr:119-39-2}},{{#expr:129-39-3}},{{#expr:135-39-3}},{{#expr:143-41-3}},{{#expr:144-43-3}},{{#expr:146-43-5}},{{#expr:153-52-7}},{{#expr:155-52-7}},{{#expr:159-52-7}},{{#expr:165-65-7}},{{#expr:166-65-7}},{{#expr:167-65-9}},{{#expr:171-84-9}},{{#expr:175-84-9}},{{#expr:175-93-9}},{{#expr:181-93-9}},{{#expr:189-110-9}},{{#expr:193-111-9}},{{#expr:197-111-9}},{{#expr:204-111-9}},{{#expr:227-113-9}},{{#expr:227-117-9}},{{#expr:256-117-9}},{{#expr:285-117-10}}\n|y3=,,,,,,,0,15,15,15,15,15,31,39,39,39,39,41,43,43,52, 52,52,65,65,65,84,84,93,93,110,111,111,111,113,117,117,117\n | y1Title=Total (cumulative)\n | y2Title=Active\n | y3Title=Recoveries\n}}\n'''Notes''':\n*There was no official report on 20 March 2020, [[Worldometer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/venezuela/|title=Venezuela Coronavirus: 197 Cases and 9 Deaths - Worldometer|website=Worldometer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] reported 65 cases, numbers coming from an article of ''[[El Nacional (Venezuela)|El Nacional]]'' from undisclosed sources from the Venezuelan Ministry of Health.<ref name=\":12\" />\n*The recoveries from 21 March to 25 March indicate people without symptoms for at least 5 days, considered as recovered in the official reports\n\n=== Confirmed deaths ===\n{{Graph\n|type=rect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=300\n|colors= #000000 \n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Week (2020)\n|xAxisAngle=-90\n|x=13-19 March, 20-26March,27 March-2 April,3-9 April,10-16 April\n|yAxisTitle=New deaths per week\n|y1=0,1,{{#expr:5-1}},{{#expr:9-5}},0\n}}\n\n=== Regional distribution ===\nCases per federal entity as of 20 April 2020<ref name=efectococuyo20a>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/21-guardias-costeros-en-nueva-esparta-entre-los-29-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-venezuela/|title=21 guardias costeros en Nueva Esparta entre los 29 nuevos casos de coronavirus en Venezuela|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Maria Souquett Gil|language=es|date=20 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=efectococuyo19a>{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/venezuela-reporta-29-casos-nuevos-y-decreta-toque-de-queda-en-nueva-esparta-19deabril/|title=Venezuela reporta 29 casos nuevos y decreta toque de queda en Nueva Esparta #19Abr|work=Efecto Cocuyo|author=Maria Souquett Gil|language=es|date=19 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>  according to the Bolivarian Government:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable col3der\"\n!Federal entity\n!Number of reported cases\n!Number of deaths{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Anzo\u00e1tegui}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Apure}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Aragua}}\n|29\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Barinas}}\n|7\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Bol\u00edvar}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Caracas|name=Capital District}}{{efn|The number of cases per region is inconsistent and may differ from source to source. In other sources, in Aragua, Apure, Capital District, Gu\u00e1rico, Miranda, Vargas and undisclosed locations, the number of cases may have a difference of 1 to 4 cases from the one reported in the here.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/404820/delcy-rodriguez-informa-de-29-casos-nuevos-de-covid-19/|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez informa de 29 casos nuevos de COVID-19|work=Runrunes|date=20 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>|name=runrunesmap}}\n|32\n|2\n|-\n|{{Flag|Cojedes}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Falc\u00f3n}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Dependencias Federales|name=Federal Dependencies}}{{Efn|The only affected federal dependency is [[Los Roques]]}}\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Gu\u00e1rico}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Lara}}\n|5\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|M\u00e9rida}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Miranda}}{{efn|name=runrunesmap}}\n|83\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Monagas}}\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Nueva Esparta}}\n|72\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Portuguesa}}\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|T\u00e1chira}}\n|8\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Trujillo}}\n|7\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Sucre}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Vargas}}\n|14\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Yaracuy}}\n|2\n|0\n|-\n|{{flag|Zulia}}\n|4\n|1\n|-\n|Undisclosed location\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|-\n!Total\n!284\n!10\n|}\nVarious Venezuelan newspapers have pointed out that there have been some inconsistencies with the government reports by federal states.<ref name=\"runrunesactu26marzo\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/402336/delcy-rodriguez-confirma-primer-fallecido-por-covid-19/|title=Delcy Rodr\u00edguez confirma primer fallecido por Covid-19|date=26 March 2020|website=Runrun|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/rr-es-plus/402235/cronologia-de-incongruencias-y-opacidad-en-cifras-oficiales-de-coronavirus-19-en-venezuela/|title=Cronolog\u00eda de incongruencias y opacidad en cifras oficiales de Covid-19 en Venezuela|date=26 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/importados-o-locales-contradicciones-del-chavismo-en-torno-a-los-casos-de-covid-19/|title=\u00bf\"Importados\" o locales?, contradicciones del chavismo en torno a los casos de COVID-19|last=Avenda\u00f1o|first=Shari|date=19 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> For example, 24 March report differs from 23 report, as [[T\u00e1chira]] and [[Portuguesa (state)|Portuguesa]] that reported cases before, were no longer included.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/maduro-informa-que-se-elevan-a-91-contagios-de-covid-19-y-dice-que-hay-casos-comunitarios/|title=Maduro informa que se elevan a 91 contagios de COVID-19 y dice que \"hay casos comunitarios\"|last=Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|first=Ronny|date=25 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, while the official report indicated 107 total cases, the number of cases per dependency amounted to 108.<ref name=\"runrunesactu26marzo\" />\n\nIn April, the Ministry of Public Health of [[Guyana]] confirmed patients with coronavirus in [[Barima-Waini]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/guyana-33-test-positive-for-covid-19/|title=Guyana: 33 test positive for COVID-19|last=Joseph|first=Sharine|date=8 April 2020|website=St. Lucia News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.gy/index.php/component/k2/item/133-14apr|title=Ministry of Public Health - Guyana COVID-19 Dashboard|website=Ministry of Public Health Guyana|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> located in [[Guayana Esequiba]] and a territory disputed with Venezuela. These cases are not included in the statistics provided by the Bolivarian Government of Venezuela.\n\n=== Sex ratio ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Date (2020)\n!Female-Male ratio\n!Ref\n|-\n|17 March\n|6:5\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|18 March\n|1:1\n|<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vtv.gob.ve/vicepresidenta-rodriguez-confirma-3nuevos-casos-covid19-pais1/|title=Vicepresidenta Rodr\u00edguez confirma 3 nuevos casos de Covid-19 en el pa\u00eds|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Venezolana de Televisi\u00f3n]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n|22 March\n|37:40\n|<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/401873/maduro-anuncio-que-cifra-de-contagiados-por-covid-19-aumento-a-77/|title=Maduro anunci\u00f3 que cifra de contagiados por Covid-19 aument\u00f3 a 77|date=23 March 2020|website=Runrun.es|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|24 March\n|44:47\n|<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://runrun.es/noticias/402104/maduro-anuncio-que-hay-7-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-para-este-24mar/|title=Maduro anunci\u00f3 que hay 7 nuevos casos de coronavirus para este #24Mar|date=24 March 2020|website=Runrunes|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|27 March\n|57:56\n|<ref name=\"2death\" />\n|-\n|31 March\n|71:72\n|<ref name=\"efectococuyo31m\">{{cite news|author=Ronny Rodr\u00edguez Rosas|url=https://efectococuyo.com/politica/hay-ocho-casos-mas-de-covid-19-y-el-pais-tiene-143-contagiados-dice-maduro/|title=Hay ocho casos m\u00e1s de COVID-19 y el pa\u00eds tiene 143 contagiados, dice Maduro|date=31 March 2020|work=Efecto Cocuyo|access-date=31 March 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n|1 April\n|71:73\n|<ref name=\"efectococuyo1a\">{{cite news|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/jorge-rodriguez-confirma-un-nuevo-caso-de-covid-19-y-repudia-declaraciones-de-trump/|work=Efecto Cocuyo|date=1 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020|title=Jorge Rodr\u00edguez confirma un nuevo caso de COVID-19 y repudia declaraciones de Trump|language=es|author=Maria Souquett Gil}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Per origin ===\nAs of 16 March, there were 33 confirmed cases in Venezuela. According to official estimates, among these, 28 came from [[Europe]] and 5 from [[C\u00facuta]], Colombia. Two of the cases consisted of foreign citizens, one of a diplomatic official, while the rest consisted of Venezuelan residents.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBy 22 March, Maduro announced out of all the 77 cases were imported.<ref name=\":5\" /> According to him, 43 had traveled recently, the distribution was as follows:<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable col3der\"\n!Country\n!Number of imported cases\n|-\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Colombia}}\n|10\n|-\n|{{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Peru}}\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|21 \n|-\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|3\n|-\n!Total\n!43\n|}\nOn 24 March, Maduro first mentioned the existence of cases transmitted locally in the country.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2009 flu pandemic in Venezuela]]\n* [[2019 shipping of humanitarian aid to Venezuela]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Venezuela|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101008203535/http://www.mpps.gob.ve/ Ministerio del Poder Popular para la Salud] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://coronavirusvenezuela.info/ Coronavirus - Presidencia Venezuela] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://twitter.com/corona_virusven Coronavirus Venezuela on Twitter] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Crisis in Venezuela|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2020 in Venezuela|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Crisis in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Venezuela]]\n", "name_user": "ReyHahn", "label": "safe", "comment": "285", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Venezuela"}
{"title_page": "Taylor rule", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Taylor Law|Taylor's law|Taylor's theorem}}\nThe Taylor rule is one kind of targeting monetary policy rule of a central bank. The Taylor rule was proposed by the American economist [[John B. Taylor]] in 1992, who is currently the George P.Shultz Senior Fellow In Economics at and the director of Standford\u2019s Introductory Economics Centre.<ref>\"Hoover Institution Senior Fellow: Biography\". Hoover Institution. Retrieved 27 October 2011.</ref> John B. Taylor was an economic adviser in the presidential administrations of Geral Ford and George H.W. Bush, and undersecretary in the U.S. Treasury.<ref>Interview with John B. Taylor, Federal Reserve Bank of MINNEAPOLIS, interview by Douglas Clement, June1, 2006</ref> \n\nThe idea of John B. Taylor to propose a central bank the technic to stabilize the economic activity by setting an interest rate.<ref>Judd, John P. and Bharat Trehan, Has the Fed Gotten Tougher on Inflation? (1995) FRBSF Weekly Letter, Number 95-13, March 31</ref>The rule defines the good monetary policy based on the free main indicator: the federal funds rate, the price level and the changes in real income.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905</ref>\n\nThe monetary policy of the Federal Reserve has been changing throughout the 20th century. The period between 1960s - 1970s is defined by Taylor as a period of a poor monetary policy. The inflation rate was growing while the interest rate was sat at the low level not allowing to restrain the rise of prices.<ref>B. Taylor, John (January 2014). \"Causes of the Financial Crisis and the Slow Recovery: A Ten-Year Perspective\", ''Hoover Institution Economics Working Paper''.</ref>\n\nThe Taylor rule prescribes to regulate the economic activity by setting up the federal rate (overnight bank rate) based on the inflation gap between desired (targeted) inflation rate and actual inflation rate; and the output gap between the actual and natural level. The practical implication of the rule defines that a central bank implements a stabilizing monetary policy when it rises the nominal interest rate by more than an increase in inflation.<ref>Frederic S. Mishkin, Monetary Policy Strategy Lessons from the Crisis National Bureau of Economic Research Cambridge MA 02138 February 2011</ref> Other words, the rule prescribes a relatively high-interest rate in the situation when actual inflation is higher than a targeted one. The main advantage of a general targeting rule is that a central bank gains the discretion to apply all means to achieve the set target. The economic model based on backwards- and forward-looking assumptions is justified.<ref>Lars E. O. Svensson, What Is Wrong with Taylor Rules? Using Judgment in Monetary Policy through Targeting Rules (June 2003), Journal of Economic Literature</ref>\n\n==As an equation==\nAccording to Taylor's original version of the rule, the nominal interest rate should respond to\ndivergences of actual inflation rates  from ''target'' inflation rates and of actual [[Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) from ''potential'' GDP:\n\n:<math>i_t = \\pi_t + r_t^* + a_\\pi  ( \\pi_t - \\pi_t^* )  + a_y ( y_t - \\bar y_t ).</math>\n\nIn this equation, <math>\\,i_t\\,</math> is the target short-term [[nominal interest rate]] (e.g. the [[Federal funds rate|federal funds rate]] in the US, the [[Official bank rate|Bank of England base rate]] in the UK), <math>\\,\\pi_t\\,</math> is the rate of [[inflation]] as measured by the [[GDP deflator]], <math>\\pi^*_t</math> is the desired rate of inflation, <math>r_t^*</math> is the assumed equilibrium real interest rate, <math>\\,y_t\\,</math> is the logarithm of real [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]], and <math>\\bar y_t</math> is the logarithm of [[potential output]], as determined by a linear trend.\n\nIn this equation, both <math>a_{\\pi}</math> and <math>a_y</math> should be positive (as a rough rule of thumb, Taylor's 1993 paper proposed setting <math>a_{\\pi}=a_y=0.5</math>).<ref>Athanasios Orphanides (2008). \"Taylor rules,\" ''[[The New Palgrave Dictionary of Economics]]'', 2nd Edition. v. 8, pp. 2000-2004, equation (7).[http://www.dictionaryofeconomics.com/article?id=pde2008_T000215&q=taylor%20rules&topicid=&result_number=1 Abstract.]</ref>  That is, the rule \"recommends\" a relatively high interest rate (a \"tight\" monetary policy) when inflation is above its target or when output is above its [[full employment|full-employment]] level, in order to reduce inflationary pressure.  It recommends a relatively low interest rate (\"easy\" monetary policy) in the opposite situation, to stimulate output.  Sometimes monetary policy goals may conflict, as in the case of [[stagflation]], when inflation is above its target while output is below full employment. In such a situation, a Taylor rule specifies the relative weights given to reducing inflation versus increasing output.\n\n==The Taylor principle==\nBy specifying <math>a_{\\pi}>0</math>, the Taylor rule says that an increase in inflation by one percentage point should prompt the [[central bank]] to raise the [[nominal interest rate]] by more than one percentage point (specifically, by <math>1+a_{\\pi}</math>, the sum of the two coefficients on <math>\\pi_t</math> in the equation above). Since the [[real interest rate]] is (approximately) the nominal interest rate minus inflation, stipulating <math>a_{\\pi}>0</math> implies that when inflation rises, the [[real interest rate]] should be increased.  The idea that the nominal interest rate should be raised \"more than one-for-one\" to cool the economy when inflation increases (that is increasing the real interest rate) has sometimes been called the Taylor principle.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Generalizing the Taylor Principle |first=Troy |last=Davig |first2=Eric M. |last2=Leeper |journal=[[American Economic Review]] |volume=97 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=607\u2013635 |jstor=30035014 |doi=10.1257/aer.97.3.607|url=https://caepr.indiana.edu/RePEc/inu/caeprp/CAEPR2006-001.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== The historical perspective ==\nThe policy rule emerged in the era of the broad debate on the policy rules versus discretion. The discourse among economists and policymakers started at the beginning of the 19th century. The first forum for debate was launched in the 1920s by the House Committee on Banking and Currency. In the hearing on the Strong bill in 1923, the conflict in the views on the monetary policy clearly appeared. Congressman Governor Strong, supported by John R. Commons and Irving Fisher, was highly concerned about the practices uses by the FED to control the price stability. In his opinion, [[the FED]] policy regarding the price level was unstable and could not guarantee long-term stability. After the death of the congressman, a political debate on changing the FED\u2019s policy was suspended. The FED was highly influenced by the New York Bank.\n\nOnly after the Great Depression hit the country, the FED policies started to be debated again. Irving Fisher compressed that \u201cthis depression was almost wholly preventable and that it would have been prevented if Governor Strong had lived, who was conducting open-market operations with a view of bringing about stability\u201d.<ref>Robert L. Hetzel, The Rules versus discretion debate over monetary policy in the 1920</ref> Later on, such monetarists as Friedman and Schwartz, confirmed that the economic dichotomy and the high inflation could be bypassed if the FED followed more precise the constant-money-rule.<ref>Frederic S. Mishkin, Monetary Policy Strategy Lessons from the Crisis National Bureau of Economic Research Cambridge MA 02138 February 2011</ref>\n\nThe recession in the US in the 1960s was accompanied by relatively high-interest rate. After Bretton Woods collapse the policy-makers were focused on keeping a low-interest rate, which had a negative impact on inventory process and resulted in the Great Inflation of 1970.\n\nSince the mid-1970s monetary targets have been used in many countries to state targets for inflation. Many advanced economies, such as the US and the UK, their policy rates were broadly consistent with the Taylor rule in the period of the \u201cGreat Moderation\u201d between the mid-1980s and early 2000s. The Great moderation period was characterized by the limited inflation and stability of prices. In light of the Taylor rule, many central banks started to adjust their policies. The first mover was New Zeeland, where the inflation target was introduced in 1984. The Reserve Bank of New Zeeland was reformed to prioritize the price stability, besides, it gained more independence. After that, the Bank of Canada in 1991 and by 1994 the banks of Sweden, Finland, Australia, Spain, Israel and Chile were given the mandate to target inflation.<ref>Pier Francesco Asso, George A. Kahn, and Robert Leeson, The Taylor Rule and the Practice of Central Banking (February 2010), The Federal Reserve Bank of Kansas City</ref>\n\nHowever, since the 2000s the actual interest rate in advanced economies, especially in the US, was below the suggested by the Taylor rule. The deviation can be explained by the fact that the central banks were supposed to mitigate the outcomes of financial busts but should intervene only when there are inflation expectations. The economics shocks were accompanied by the fall of the interest rate.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref>\n\n==Alternative versions of the rule==\n[[File:Taylor Rule Prescriptions for Fed Funds Rate 2016.png|thumb|350px|right|Effective federal funds rate and prescriptions from alternate versions of the Taylor Rule]]\nWhile the Taylor principle has proved very influential, there is more debate about the other terms that should enter into the rule. According to some simple [[New Keynesian economics|New Keynesian]] macroeconomic models, insofar as the central bank keeps inflation stable, the degree of fluctuation in output will be optimized (Blanchard and Gali call this property the '[[divine coincidence]]'). In this case, the central bank does not need to take fluctuations in the output gap into account when setting interest rates (that is, it may optimally set <math>a_y=0</math>.) On the other hand, other economists have proposed including additional terms in the Taylor rule to take into account financial conditions: for example, the interest rate might be raised when stock prices, housing prices, or interest rate spreads increase.\n\n* Taylor Rule 1993 - the original definition by John Taylor with <math>a_{\\pi} = a_y = 0.5</math>\n* Taylor Rule 1999 - adapted and updated by John Taylor in a new research paper: <math>a_{\\pi} = 0.5, a_y \\ge 0</math>\n\n== Alternative theories ==\n'''''Solvency rule''''': the alternative theory to the Taylor equitation. The new perspective on the rule was presented by Emiliano Brancaccio after the financial crises of 2008. The Taylor rule can bee is seen in the light of solvency and capital controls.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio, Giuseppe Fontana, The Global Economic Crisis. (2011), Routledge, Oxon OX14 4RN</ref> The inflation target and output gap are neglected, while the interest rate is put under the conditionality to the solvency of workers and firms that represent financial stability. Opposite to stricter Taylor rule the solvency rule represents more a benchmark than a mechanistic formula.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio and Giuseppe Fontana, \u2018Solvency rule\u2019 versus \u2018Taylor rule\u2019: an alternative interpretation of the relation between monetary policy and the economic crisis (August 2012 ), Cambridge Journal of Economics</ref>\n\n'''''[[McCallum rule]]''''': The rule created by economist Bennett T. McCallum at the end of the 20th-century targets the nominal gross domestic products. In the idea of McCallum the FED should stabilize the nominal GDP to achieve economic stability. Although the same monetary policy objectives can be reached by McCallum rule as by Taylor rule, the McCallum rule uses the precise financial data.<ref>Michael F. Gallmeyer Burton Hollifield Stanley E. Zin, Taylor Rules, McCallum Rules and the term structure of interest rates (April 2005), National Bureau Of Economic Research 1050 Massachusetts Avenue Cambridge, MA 02138</ref> Thus, the McCallum rule can overcome the problem of the unobservable variables. \n\n==Empirical relevance==\nAlthough the [[Federal Reserve]] does not explicitly follow the Taylor rule, many analysts have argued that the rule provides a fairly accurate summary of US monetary policy under [[Paul Volcker]] and [[Alan Greenspan]].<ref name=\"Clarida 2000\">{{cite journal |last=Clarida |first=Richard |first2=Jordi |last2=Gal\u00ed |first3=Mark |last3=Gertler |year=2000 |title=Monetary Policy Rules and Macroeconomic Stability: Theory and Some Evidence |journal=[[Quarterly Journal of Economics]] |volume=115 |issue=1 |pages=147\u2013180 |doi=10.1162/003355300554692 |jstor=2586937 |citeseerx=10.1.1.111.7984 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowenstein |first=Roger |title=The Education of Ben Bernanke | newspaper=The New York Times |date=2008-01-20 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/20/magazine/20Ben-Bernanke-t.html}}</ref>Similar observations have been made about central banks in other developed economies, both in countries like Canada and New Zealand that have officially adopted inflation targeting rules, and in others like [[Germany]] where the [[Bundesbank]]'s policy did not officially target the inflation rate.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bernanke |first=Ben |first2=Ilian |last2=Mihov |year=1997 |title=What Does the Bundesbank Target? |journal=[[European Economic Review]] |volume=41 |issue=6 |pages=1025\u20131053 |doi=10.1016/S0014-2921(96)00056-6 |url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w5764.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Clarida |first=Richard |first2=Mark |last2=Gertler |first3=Jordi |last3=Gal\u00ed |year=1998 |title=Monetary Policy Rules in Practice: Some International Evidence |journal=European Economic Review |volume=42 |issue=6 |pages=1033\u20131067 |doi=10.1016/S0014-2921(98)00016-6 |url=http://papers.nber.org/papers/w6254.pdf }}</ref> This observation has been cited by [[Richard Clarida|Clarida]], [[Jordi Gal\u00ed|Gal\u00ed]], and [[Mark Gertler (economist)|Gertler]] as a reason why inflation had remained under control and the economy had been relatively stable (the so-called '[[Great Moderation]]') in most developed countries from the 1980s through the 2000s.<ref name=\"Clarida 2000\" /> However, according to Taylor, the rule was not followed in part of the 2000s, possibly leading to the housing bubble.<ref>{{cite paper |url=http://www.stanford.edu/~johntayl/FCPR.pdf |title=The Financial Crisis and the Policy Responses: An Empirical Analysis of What Went Wrong |first=John B. |last=Taylor |year=2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Taylor |first=John B. |year=2009 |title=Getting Off Track: How Government Actions and Interventions Caused, Prolonged, and Worsened the Financial Crisis |location= |publisher=Hoover Institution Press |isbn=978-0-8179-4971-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/gettingofftrackh00tayl }}</ref> Certain research has determined that some households form their expectations about the future path of interest rates, inflation, and unemployment in a way that is consistent with Taylor-type rules.<ref>{{cite paper |work=Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco Working Paper 2012-01 |title=Do People Understand Monetary Policy? |first=Carlos |last=Carvalho |first2=Fernanda |last2=Nechio |year=2013 |ssrn=1984321 }}</ref>\n\n== Limitation of the Taylor rule ==\nThe Taylor rule is highly debated in the discourse of the rules vs. discretion. There are a few main limitations of the Taylor rule.\n\n1) ''Technical reasons.'' For the economic models, the period of 4 months was widely used, however, the period is not accurate to track the real changes in price, and this period is too long for setting the fixed interest rate.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905)</ref> Besides, the formulate incorporates the unobservable parameters can be easily misevaluated.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref> For example, the output-gap could not be precisely estimated by any bank.\n\n2) ''The inaccuracy of predictable variables'', such as the inflation and output gap that depend on the different scenarios of economic development. 3) ''Difficulty to assess the state of the economy in real-time'' 4) ''The discretionary optimization'' that leads to stabilization bias and a lack of history dependence.<ref>Lars E. O. Svensson, What Is Wrong with Taylor Rules? Using Judgment in Monetary Policy through Targeting Rules (June 2003), Journal of Economic Literature</ref>\n\n5) ''The limited number of factors in the model.'' The model does not outlook the financial parameters. Thus, in the period of the financial boost the Taylor rule might tend to underestimate the interest rate, and opposite, during the financial busts overestimate.\n\n6) ''Does not reflect the usability of other monetary policy instruments'' such as reserve funds adjustment, balance sheet policies.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref>\n\n7) ''The relationship between the interest rate and aggregate demand is questioning'' by Kriesler and Lanoie, 2007.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio and Giuseppe Fontana, \u2018Solvency rule\u2019 versus \u2018Taylor rule\u2019: an alternative interpretation of the relation between monetary policy and the economic crisis (August 2012 ), Cambridge Journal of Economics</ref>\n\nHowever, Taylor in his economic work highlighted that the rule should not be implicated mechanically: \u201c\u2026There will be episodes where monetary policy will need to be adjusted to deal with special factors.\u201d On another hand, the Taylor rule is opposed to the discretion approach since it aimed to overcome the limitation of the purely discretionary approach.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905</ref> Hence, although the Taylor rule gives the room for manoeuvre, it is encouraged to treat the Taylor rule as a policy rule that required the strict implementation of the policy based on the incoming economic parameters.\n\n==Criticisms==\n[[Athanasios Orphanides]] (2003) claims that the Taylor rule can misguide policy makers since they face [[real-time data]]. He shows that the Taylor rule matches the US funds rate less perfectly when accounting for these informational limitations and that an activist policy following the Taylor rule would have resulted in an inferior macroeconomic performance during the Great Inflation of the seventies.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Orphanides |first=A. |year=2003 |title=The Quest for Prosperity without Inflation |journal=[[Journal of Monetary Economics]] |volume=50 |issue=3 |pages=633\u2013663 |doi=10.1016/S0304-3932(03)00028-X |citeseerx=10.1.1.196.7048 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, financial manager [[Bill H. Gross|Bill Gross]] said the Taylor rule \"must now be discarded into the trash bin of history\", in light of tepid GDP growth in the years after 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/07/30/gross-low-rates-are-the-problem-not-the-solution.html |title=Gross: Low rates are the problem, not the solution |work=CNBC |author=Bill Gross |date=July 30, 2015 |accessdate=July 30, 2015|author-link=Bill H. Gross }}</ref> Gross believed low interest rates were not the cure for decreased growth, but the source of the problem.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Monetary policy]]\n*[[McCallum rule]]\n*[[Monetary policy reaction function]]\n*[[Inflation targeting]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stanford.edu/~johntayl/PolRulLink.htm Resources from John Taylor's web site.]\n*[http://www.federalreserve.gov/Pubs/FEDS/2007/200718/200718pap.pdf Federal Reserve paper on the Taylor Rule.]\n\n{{Federal Reserve System}}\n{{Central banks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor Rule}}\n[[Category:Federal Reserve System]]\n[[Category:Monetary policy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Taylor Law|Taylor's law|Taylor's theorem}}\nThe Taylor rule is one kind of targeting monetary policy rule of a central bank. The Taylor rule was proposed by the American economist [[John B. Taylor]] in 1992, who is currently the George P.Shultz Senior Fellow In Economics at and the director of Standford\u2019s Introductory Economics Centre.<ref>\"Hoover Institution Senior Fellow: Biography\". Hoover Institution. Retrieved 27 October 2011.</ref> John B. Taylor was an economic adviser in the presidential administrations of Geral Ford and George H.W. Bush, and undersecretary in the U.S. Treasury.<ref>Interview with John B. Taylor, Federal Reserve Bank of MINNEAPOLIS, interview by Douglas Clement, June1, 2006</ref> \n\nThe idea of John B. Taylor to propose a central bank the technic to stabilize the economic activity by setting an interest rate.<ref>Judd, John P. and Bharat Trehan, Has the Fed Gotten Tougher on Inflation? (1995) FRBSF Weekly Letter, Number 95-13, March 31</ref>The rule defines the good monetary policy based on the free main indicator: the federal funds rate, the price level and the changes in real income.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905</ref>\n\nThe monetary policy of the Federal Reserve has been changing throughout the 20th century. The period between 1960s - 1970s is defined by Taylor as a period of a poor monetary policy. The inflation rate was growing while the interest rate was sat at the low level not allowing to restrain the rise of prices.<ref>B. Taylor, John (January 2014). \"Causes of the Financial Crisis and the Slow Recovery: A Ten-Year Perspective\", ''Hoover Institution Economics Working Paper''.</ref>\n\nThe Taylor rule prescribes to regulate the economic activity by setting up the federal rate (overnight bank rate) based on the inflation gap between desired (targeted) inflation rate and actual inflation rate; and the output gap between the actual and natural level. The practical implication of the rule defines that a central bank implements a stabilizing monetary policy when it rises the nominal interest rate by more than an increase in inflation.<ref>Frederic S. Mishkin, Monetary Policy Strategy Lessons from the Crisis National Bureau of Economic Research Cambridge MA 02138 February 2011</ref> Other words, the rule prescribes a relatively high-interest rate in the situation when actual inflation is higher than a targeted one. The main advantage of a general targeting rule is that a central bank gains the discretion to apply all means to achieve the set target. The economic model based on backwards- and forward-looking assumptions is justified.<ref>Lars E. O. Svensson, What Is Wrong with Taylor Rules? Using Judgment in Monetary Policy through Targeting Rules (June 2003), Journal of Economic Literature</ref>\n\n==As an equation==\nAccording to Taylor's original version of the rule, the nominal interest rate should respond to\ndivergences of actual inflation rates  from ''target'' inflation rates and of actual [[Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) from ''potential'' GDP:\n\n:<math>i_t = \\pi_t + r_t^* + a_\\pi  ( \\pi_t - \\pi_t^* )  + a_y ( y_t - \\bar y_t ).</math>\n\nIn this equation, <math>\\,i_t\\,</math> is the target short-term [[nominal interest rate]] (e.g. the [[Federal funds rate|federal funds rate]] in the US, the [[Official bank rate|Bank of England base rate]] in the UK), <math>\\,\\pi_t\\,</math> is the rate of [[inflation]] as measured by the [[GDP deflator]], <math>\\pi^*_t</math> is the desired rate of inflation, <math>r_t^*</math> is the assumed equilibrium real interest rate, <math>\\,y_t\\,</math> is the logarithm of real [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]], and <math>\\bar y_t</math> is the logarithm of [[potential output]], as determined by a linear trend.\n\nIn this equation, both <math>a_{\\pi}</math> and <math>a_y</math> should be positive (as a rough rule of thumb, Taylor's 1993 paper proposed setting <math>a_{\\pi}=a_y=0.5</math>).<ref>Athanasios Orphanides (2008). \"Taylor rules,\" ''[[The New Palgrave Dictionary of Economics]]'', 2nd Edition. v. 8, pp. 2000-2004, equation (7).[http://www.dictionaryofeconomics.com/article?id=pde2008_T000215&q=taylor%20rules&topicid=&result_number=1 Abstract.]</ref>  That is, the rule \"recommends\" a relatively high interest rate (a \"tight\" monetary policy) when inflation is above its target or when output is above its [[full employment|full-employment]] level, in order to reduce inflationary pressure.  It recommends a relatively low interest rate (\"easy\" monetary policy) in the opposite situation, to stimulate output.  Sometimes monetary policy goals may conflict, as in the case of [[stagflation]], when inflation is above its target while output is below full employment. In such a situation, a Taylor rule specifies the relative weights given to reducing inflation versus increasing output.\n\n==The Taylor principle==\nBy specifying <math>a_{\\pi}>0</math>, the Taylor rule says that an increase in inflation by one percentage point should prompt the [[central bank]] to raise the [[nominal interest rate]] by more than one percentage point (specifically, by <math>1+a_{\\pi}</math>, the sum of the two coefficients on <math>\\pi_t</math> in the equation above). Since the [[real interest rate]] is (approximately) the nominal interest rate minus inflation, stipulating <math>a_{\\pi}>0</math> implies that when inflation rises, the [[real interest rate]] should be increased.  The idea that the nominal interest rate should be raised \"more than one-for-one\" to cool the economy when inflation increases (that is increasing the real interest rate) has sometimes been called the Taylor principle.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Generalizing the Taylor Principle |first=Troy |last=Davig |first2=Eric M. |last2=Leeper |journal=[[American Economic Review]] |volume=97 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=607\u2013635 |jstor=30035014 |doi=10.1257/aer.97.3.607|url=https://caepr.indiana.edu/RePEc/inu/caeprp/CAEPR2006-001.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== The historical perspective ==\nThe policy rule emerged in the era of the broad debate on the policy rules versus discretion. The discourse among economists and policymakers started at the beginning of the 19th century. The first forum for debate was launched in the 1920s by the House Committee on Banking and Currency. In the hearing on the Strong bill in 1923, the conflict in the views on the monetary policy clearly appeared. Congressman Governor Strong, supported by John R. Commons and Irving Fisher, was highly concerned about the practices uses by the FED to control the price stability. In his opinion, [[the FED]] policy regarding the price level was unstable and could not guarantee long-term stability. After the death of the congressman, a political debate on changing the FED\u2019s policy was suspended. The FED was highly influenced by the New York Bank.\n\nOnly after the Great Depression hit the country, the FED policies started to be debated again. Irving Fisher compressed that \u201cthis depression was almost wholly preventable and that it would have been prevented if Governor Strong had lived, who was conducting open-market operations with a view of bringing about stability\u201d.<ref>Robert L. Hetzel, The Rules versus discretion debate over monetary policy in the 1920</ref> Later on, such monetarists as Friedman and Schwartz, confirmed that the economic dichotomy and the high inflation could be bypassed if the FED followed more precise the constant-money-rule.<ref>Frederic S. Mishkin, Monetary Policy Strategy Lessons from the Crisis National Bureau of Economic Research Cambridge MA 02138 February 2011</ref>\n\nThe recession in the US in the 1960s was accompanied by relatively high-interest rate. After Bretton Woods collapse the policy-makers were focused on keeping a low-interest rate, which had a negative impact on inventory process and resulted in the Great Inflation of 1970.\n\nSince the mid-1970s monetary targets have been used in many countries to state targets for inflation. Many advanced economies, such as the US and the UK, their policy rates were broadly consistent with the Taylor rule in the period of the \u201cGreat Moderation\u201d between the mid-1980s and early 2000s. The Great moderation period was characterized by the limited inflation and stability of prices. In light of the Taylor rule, many central banks started to adjust their policies. The first mover was New Zeeland, where the inflation target was introduced in 1984. The Reserve Bank of New Zeeland was reformed to prioritize the price stability, besides, it gained more independence. After that, the Bank of Canada in 1991 and by 1994 the banks of Sweden, Finland, Australia, Spain, Israel and Chile were given the mandate to target inflation.<ref>Pier Francesco Asso, George A. Kahn, and Robert Leeson, The Taylor Rule and the Practice of Central Banking (February 2010), The Federal Reserve Bank of Kansas City</ref>\n\nHowever, since the 2000s the actual interest rate in advanced economies, especially in the US, was below the suggested by the Taylor rule. The deviation can be explained by the fact that the central banks were supposed to mitigate the outcomes of financial busts but should intervene only when there are inflation expectations. The economics shocks were accompanied by the fall of the interest rate.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref>\n\n==Alternative versions of the rule==\n[[File:Taylor Rule Prescriptions for Fed Funds Rate 2016.png|thumb|350px|right|Effective federal funds rate and prescriptions from alternate versions of the Taylor Rule]]\nWhile the Taylor principle has proved very influential, there is more debate about the other terms that should enter into the rule. According to some simple [[New Keynesian economics|New Keynesian]] macroeconomic models, insofar as the central bank keeps inflation stable, the degree of fluctuation in output will be optimized (Blanchard and Gali call this property the '[[divine coincidence]]'). In this case, the central bank does not need to take fluctuations in the output gap into account when setting interest rates (that is, it may optimally set <math>a_y=0</math>.) On the other hand, other economists have proposed including additional terms in the Taylor rule to take into account financial conditions: for example, the interest rate might be raised when stock prices, housing prices, or interest rate spreads increase.\n\n* Taylor Rule 1993 - the original definition by John Taylor with <math>a_{\\pi} = a_y = 0.5</math>\n* Taylor Rule 1999 - adapted and updated by John Taylor in a new research paper: <math>a_{\\pi} = 0.5, a_y \\ge 0</math>\n\n== Alternative theories ==\n'''''Solvency rule''''': the alternative theory to the Taylor equitation. The new perspective on the rule was presented by Emiliano Brancaccio after the financial crises of 2008. The Taylor rule can bee is seen in the light of solvency and capital controls.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio, Giuseppe Fontana, The Global Economic Crisis. (2011), Routledge, Oxon OX14 4RN</ref> The inflation target and output gap are neglected, while the interest rate is put under the conditionality to the solvency of workers and firms that represent financial stability. Opposite to stricter Taylor rule the solvency rule represents more a benchmark than a mechanistic formula.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio and Giuseppe Fontana, \u2018Solvency rule\u2019 versus \u2018Taylor rule\u2019: an alternative interpretation of the relation between monetary policy and the economic crisis (August 2012 ), Cambridge Journal of Economics</ref>\n\n'''''[[McCallum rule]]''''': The rule created by economist Bennett T. McCallum at the end of the 20th-century targets the nominal gross domestic products. In the idea of McCallum the FED should stabilize the nominal GDP to achieve economic stability. Although the same monetary policy objectives can be reached by McCallum rule as by Taylor rule, the McCallum rule uses the precise financial data.<ref>Michael F. Gallmeyer Burton Hollifield Stanley E. Zin, Taylor Rules, McCallum Rules and the term structure of interest rates (April 2005), National Bureau Of Economic Research 1050 Massachusetts Avenue Cambridge, MA 02138</ref> Thus, the McCallum rule can overcome the problem of the unobservable variables. Alexander Jung , Does McCallum\u2019s rule outperform Taylor\u2019s rule during the financial crisis? The ECB\n\n==Empirical relevance==\nAlthough the [[Federal Reserve]] does not explicitly follow the Taylor rule, many analysts have argued that the rule provides a fairly accurate summary of US monetary policy under [[Paul Volcker]] and [[Alan Greenspan]].<ref name=\"Clarida 2000\">{{cite journal |last=Clarida |first=Richard |first2=Jordi |last2=Gal\u00ed |first3=Mark |last3=Gertler |year=2000 |title=Monetary Policy Rules and Macroeconomic Stability: Theory and Some Evidence |journal=[[Quarterly Journal of Economics]] |volume=115 |issue=1 |pages=147\u2013180 |doi=10.1162/003355300554692 |jstor=2586937 |citeseerx=10.1.1.111.7984 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowenstein |first=Roger |title=The Education of Ben Bernanke | newspaper=The New York Times |date=2008-01-20 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/20/magazine/20Ben-Bernanke-t.html}}</ref>Similar observations have been made about central banks in other developed economies, both in countries like Canada and New Zealand that have officially adopted inflation targeting rules, and in others like [[Germany]] where the [[Bundesbank]]'s policy did not officially target the inflation rate.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bernanke |first=Ben |first2=Ilian |last2=Mihov |year=1997 |title=What Does the Bundesbank Target? |journal=[[European Economic Review]] |volume=41 |issue=6 |pages=1025\u20131053 |doi=10.1016/S0014-2921(96)00056-6 |url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w5764.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Clarida |first=Richard |first2=Mark |last2=Gertler |first3=Jordi |last3=Gal\u00ed |year=1998 |title=Monetary Policy Rules in Practice: Some International Evidence |journal=European Economic Review |volume=42 |issue=6 |pages=1033\u20131067 |doi=10.1016/S0014-2921(98)00016-6 |url=http://papers.nber.org/papers/w6254.pdf }}</ref> This observation has been cited by [[Richard Clarida|Clarida]], [[Jordi Gal\u00ed|Gal\u00ed]], and [[Mark Gertler (economist)|Gertler]] as a reason why inflation had remained under control and the economy had been relatively stable (the so-called '[[Great Moderation]]') in most developed countries from the 1980s through the 2000s.<ref name=\"Clarida 2000\" /> However, according to Taylor, the rule was not followed in part of the 2000s, possibly leading to the housing bubble.<ref>{{cite paper |url=http://www.stanford.edu/~johntayl/FCPR.pdf |title=The Financial Crisis and the Policy Responses: An Empirical Analysis of What Went Wrong |first=John B. |last=Taylor |year=2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Taylor |first=John B. |year=2009 |title=Getting Off Track: How Government Actions and Interventions Caused, Prolonged, and Worsened the Financial Crisis |location= |publisher=Hoover Institution Press |isbn=978-0-8179-4971-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/gettingofftrackh00tayl }}</ref> Certain research has determined that some households form their expectations about the future path of interest rates, inflation, and unemployment in a way that is consistent with Taylor-type rules.<ref>{{cite paper |work=Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco Working Paper 2012-01 |title=Do People Understand Monetary Policy? |first=Carlos |last=Carvalho |first2=Fernanda |last2=Nechio |year=2013 |ssrn=1984321 }}</ref>\n\n== Limitation of the Taylor rule ==\nThe Taylor rule is highly debated in the discourse of the rules vs. discretion. There are a few main limitations of the Taylor rule.\n\n1) ''Technical reasons.'' For the economic models, the period of 4 months was widely used, however, the period is not accurate to track the real changes in price, and this period is too long for setting the fixed interest rate.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905)</ref> Besides, the formulate incorporates the unobservable parameters can be easily misevaluated.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref> For example, the output-gap could not be precisely estimated by any bank.\n\n2) ''The inaccuracy of predictable variables'', such as the inflation and output gap that depend on the different scenarios of economic development. 3) ''Difficulty to assess the state of the economy in real-time'' 4) ''The discretionary optimization'' that leads to stabilization bias and a lack of history dependence.<ref>Lars E. O. Svensson, What Is Wrong with Taylor Rules? Using Judgment in Monetary Policy through Targeting Rules (June 2003), Journal of Economic Literature</ref>\n\n5) ''The limited number of factors in the model.'' The model does not outlook the financial parameters. Thus, in the period of the financial boost the Taylor rule might tend to underestimate the interest rate, and opposite, during the financial busts overestimate.\n\n6) ''Does not reflect the usability of other monetary policy instruments'' such as reserve funds adjustment, balance sheet policies.<ref>Boris Hofmann, Taylor rules and monetary policy: a global \u201cGreat Deviation\u201d? (September 2012)</ref>\n\n7) ''The relationship between the interest rate and aggregate demand is questioning'' by Kriesler and Lanoie, 2007.<ref>Emiliano Brancaccio and Giuseppe Fontana, \u2018Solvency rule\u2019 versus \u2018Taylor rule\u2019: an alternative interpretation of the relation between monetary policy and the economic crisis (August 2012 ), Cambridge Journal of Economics</ref>\n\nHowever, Taylor in his economic work highlighted that the rule should not be implicated mechanically: \u201c\u2026There will be episodes where monetary policy will need to be adjusted to deal with special factors.\u201d On another hand, the Taylor rule is opposed to the discretion approach since it aimed to overcome the limitation of the purely discretionary approach.<ref>John B. Taylor, Discretion versus policy rules in practice (1993), Standford University, y, Stanford, CA 94905</ref> Hence, although the Taylor rule gives the room for manoeuvre, it is encouraged to treat the Taylor rule as a policy rule that required the strict implementation of the policy based on the incoming economic parameters.\n\n==Criticisms==\n[[Athanasios Orphanides]] (2003) claims that the Taylor rule can misguide policy makers since they face [[real-time data]]. He shows that the Taylor rule matches the US funds rate less perfectly when accounting for these informational limitations and that an activist policy following the Taylor rule would have resulted in an inferior macroeconomic performance during the Great Inflation of the seventies.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Orphanides |first=A. |year=2003 |title=The Quest for Prosperity without Inflation |journal=[[Journal of Monetary Economics]] |volume=50 |issue=3 |pages=633\u2013663 |doi=10.1016/S0304-3932(03)00028-X |citeseerx=10.1.1.196.7048 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, financial manager [[Bill H. Gross|Bill Gross]] said the Taylor rule \"must now be discarded into the trash bin of history\", in light of tepid GDP growth in the years after 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/07/30/gross-low-rates-are-the-problem-not-the-solution.html |title=Gross: Low rates are the problem, not the solution |work=CNBC |author=Bill Gross |date=July 30, 2015 |accessdate=July 30, 2015|author-link=Bill H. Gross }}</ref> Gross believed low interest rates were not the cure for decreased growth, but the source of the problem.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Monetary policy]]\n*[[McCallum rule]]\n*[[Monetary policy reaction function]]\n*[[Inflation targeting]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stanford.edu/~johntayl/PolRulLink.htm Resources from John Taylor's web site.]\n*[http://www.federalreserve.gov/Pubs/FEDS/2007/200718/200718pap.pdf Federal Reserve paper on the Taylor Rule.]\n\n{{Federal Reserve System}}\n{{Central banks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor Rule}}\n[[Category:Federal Reserve System]]\n[[Category:Monetary policy]]\n", "name_user": "Elizaveta Lebedeva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlternative theories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_rule"}
{"title_page": "Carceri Nuove (Rome)", "text_new": "{{short description|Jail built by Pope Innocent X}}\n\n[[File:Regola - Carceri nuove 00458-9.JPG|thumb|The fassade of the ''Carceri Nuove'' along Via Giulia]]\nThe '''Carceri Nuove''' ({{lang-en|New Jails}}) is a building in Rome important for historical and architectural reasons. \n\nBuilt in the mid-17th century by decision of [[Pope Innocent X]] - moved by ideals of humanity and clemency - to replace the various prisons scattered throughout the city, the jail remained in operation until the construction of the judicial prison of ''[[Regina Coeli (prison)|Regina Coeli]]'' in [[Trastevere]] at the turn of the 20th century. The building currently houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo''. \n\n==Location==\nThe building is located in Rome, in the [[Regola]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|Rione]]'', about halfway down [[Via Giulia]] (at n. 52), in an area devastated by the demolitions started in 1938 for the construction of a road between ''[[ponte Mazzini]]'' bridge and ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele'', never built because of the war.  To the south it borders with ''vicolo delle prigioni'', to the north with ''vicolo della scimia''.<ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PopeInnocentX.jpg|thumb|Pope Innocent X Pamphilj, driven by ideals of humanity, was the creator of the ''Carceri Nuove'']]\nThe ''Carceri Nuove'' were built between 1652 and 1655 at the will of [[Pope Innocent X]] [[Pamphili family|Pamphilj]] (r. 1644-1655) by [[Antonio Del Grande]].<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> The pope in fact, while he was ''[[Auditor (ecclesiastical)|Uditore]]'' of the [[Sacra Rota]] tribunal, had been able to see personally the inhuman conditions in which the prisoners of [[Tor di Nona]] jail lived.<ref name=bar248>Baronio, p. 248</ref> Once he arrived at [[Papal throne]], he decided to alleviate their condition by building a new prison.<ref name=bar248/> \n\nThe occasion for the construction was given a complaint by the English College, which protested the pontifical intention to confiscate houses of the College to enlarge the prisons of Corte Savella.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> Virgilio Spada, \"deputato sopra la Congregazione delle Carceri di casa Giulia\" and brother of Cardinal [[Bernardino Spada|Bernardino]], had the [[Construction surveying|survey]] of Corte Savella carried out and commissioned Del Grande to draw up a restructuring project, but Innocent X decided to build a new prison between Via Giulia, the Tiber and Piazza Padella.<ref name=delGrandeDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/antonio-del-grande_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Antonio Del Grande|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Manfredo|last=Tafuri|volume=36|year=1988|language=it}}</ref>\nThis jail replaced those that had existed until then in the city: ''Tor di Nona'' in [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], ''Corte Savella'' in Regola, and [[Palazzo del Governatore di Borgo|the jail]] in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]].<ref name=pie7913/> The ''Carceri Nuove'' were the first example in Rome of modern [[penitentiary]], where the humanity of the inmates was placed at the centre of the penitentiary system. <ref name=pie7913/> The philosophy that animated this house of punishment is also underlined by the [[inscription]] placed on the front door:<ref name=pie7913/> \n\n{{quote|'''IVSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE / SECVRIORI AC MITIORI REORVM CVSTODIAE / NOVVM CARCEREM / INNOCENTIVS X PONT. MAX / POSVIT / ANNO DOMINI / MDCLV'''}}\n\n{{quote|Innocent X [[Pontifex_maximus#Catholic_Church_use_of_the_title|Pontifex Maximus]] erected [[in the year of the Lord]] 1655 the new prison for justice, for clemency and for a safer and more humane custody of the guilty}}\n\nWhen the pope died in January 1655 the building was not yet completed; his successor [[Alexander VII]] (r. 1655-1667) completed its construction, but  before its inauguration the edifice was used during the [[Naples Plague|1656 plague]] epidemic as ''stufa'' (from the German word ''stube'', it was something between a Roman bath and a modern sauna, very popular in Rome at that time) where those who were in [[quarantine]] in [[San Pancrazio]] and [[Sant'Eusebio]] were washed.\n\nThe inmates were continuously assisted by members of the [[Archconfraternities]] of [[Church of San Giovanni della Pigna|San Giovanni della Pigna]], the ''[[Assumption of Mary|Assunta]]'' at [[Church of the Ges\u00f9|the Ges\u00f9]] and [[San Girolamo della Carit\u00e0]]. <ref name=bar248/> The ''Carceri Nuove'' remained operative until the inauguration of the ''Regina Coeli'' Prison at Via della Lungara, being used for preventive custody. \nAfter that, only minors were kept there.<ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> In 1931 the edifice became the seat of the ''Centro per Studi Penitenziari'' and the ''Museo di Criminologia''.<ref name=pie7914/> Later the building became the seat of the ''United Nations Research Institute for Social Defence''. <ref name=pie7914/> Now (2020) it houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Anti-Mafia and Counter-Terrorism Directorate\").\n\n==Architecture and Organization==\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Portal.jpg|thumb|The severe portal of the Carceri Nuove on Via Giulia]]\nThe building, considered until the 18th century a model humanitarian prison, was designed by Del Grande following a detailed program of Virgilio Spada and keeping in mind the prisons of Tordinona.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> It was organized in two blocks: the one of the representations and the parlors, on Via Giulia, and the one of the dungeons towards the Tiber; the two bodies are connected by a gallery open on the side courtyards.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> It is possible that the planimetric shape - similar to a sword coming out of a [[hilt]] - is the allegory either of the justice of Pope Innocent or of Virgilio Spada (\"Sword\" in English), superintendent of the construction.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/>\n\nThe building is built in bricks with [[overhang]] in rustic [[travertine]] or [[stucco]].<ref name=pie7913/> It has 4 floors with 6 windows each on the main facade along Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7914/> On the ground floor the windows are rectangular and equipped with [[grille]]s. <ref name=pie7913/> At the center of the ground floor there is a strongly [[taper ratio|tapered]]  [[portal (architecture)|portal]] with at the center of the [[lintel]] a large [[Rustication (architecture)|bugna]] surmounted by the [[inscription]] cited  above.<ref name=pie7914/> The imposing building is concluded by a large groove [[cornice]].<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> \n\nInside the building there are two courtyards and a large staircase, but the floors are five.<ref name=pie7914/> \nOn the ground floor lay the rooms where men and women were interrogated, the lodgings of the caretakers, the chancellery, the services, a courtyard for the walk, two ''larghe'' (large rooms) for those accused of serious crimes, two punishment chambers, a juvenile prison and a chapel.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\nOn the first floor there were: two ''larghe'' for those accused of minor crimes; rooms for civilians accused of petty crimes; a room for [[Roman Jews|Jews]]; the archive and a second chapel.<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nOn the second floor lay a room reserved for the so-called ''visita graziosa'' (\"gracious visit\") of the commission for the welfare of inmates set up in 1435 under [[Pope Eugene IV]] (r. 1431-1447):<ref name=pie7914/> then there was the [[chaplain]]'s room, the ''conforteria'' (the place where those condemned to death received the comforts of religion), a chapel for those condemned to the death penalty and an isolation room for those sick of [[mange]].<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nThe third and fourth floors were occupied by seventeen [[dungeon]]s, each one bearing the name of a [[Saint (Catholic)|saint]].<ref name=pie7914/> They were accessed through very low doors, and each one was illuminated by a narrow window at the top protected by a double grille.<ref name=pie7914/>. \n\nIn the women's sector there were three ''larghe'' on the first floor and three dungeons on the second floor, the chapel, the infirmary and the apartment of the ''[[Prior|Priora]]''.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\nUntil the [[pontificate]] of [[Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) the prisons had also chambers for the clergymen; afterwards, these were imprisoned in special rooms in [[Castel Sant'Angelo]].<ref name=pie7914/> In 1824 a large kitchen was built on the ground floor, while the women's prison was extended to the second floor.<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nIn 1842 the ''Carceri Nuove'' housed 680 inmates, 600 men and 80 women.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Baronio, Cesare\n | title=Descrizione di Roma moderna\n | publisher=M.A. and P.A. De Rossi, Roma\n | language=Italian\n | year=1697\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Coord|41|53|50.18|N|12|28|1.38|E|display=title}}\n[[Category:Rome R. VII Regola]]\n[[Category:1655 establishments in the Papal States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Rome]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Jail built by Pope Innocent X}}\n\n[[File:Regola - Carceri nuove 00458-9.JPG|thumb|The fassade of the ''Carceri Nuove'' along Via Giulia]]\nThe '''Carceri Nuove''' ({{lang-en|New Jails}}) is a building in Rome important for historical and architectural reasons. \n\nBuilt in the mid-17th century by [[Pope Innocent X]] - moved by ideals of humanity and clemency - to replace the various prisons scattered throughout the city, the jail remained in operation until the construction of the judicial prison of ''[[Regina Coeli (prison)|Regina Coeli]]'' in [[Trastevere]] at the turn of the 20th century. The building currently houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo''. \n\n==Location==\nThe building is located in Rome, in the [[Regola]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|Rione]]'', about halfway down [[Via Giulia]] (at n. 52), in an area devastated by the demolitions started in 1938 for the construction of a road between ''[[ponte Mazzini]]'' bridge and ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele'', never built because of the war.  To the south it borders with ''vicolo delle prigioni'', to the north with ''vicolo della scimia''.<ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PopeInnocentX.jpg|thumb|Pope Innocent X Pamphilj, driven by ideals of humanity, was the creator of the ''Carceri Nuove'']]\nThe ''Carceri Nuove'' were built between 1652 and 1655 at the will of [[Pope Innocent X]] [[Pamphili family|Pamphilj]] (r. 1644-1655) by [[Antonio Del Grande]].<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> The pope in fact, while he was ''[[Auditor (ecclesiastical)|Uditore]]'' of the [[Sacra Rota]] tribunal, had been able to see personally the inhuman conditions in which the prisoners of [[Tor di Nona]] jail lived.<ref name=bar248>Baronio, p. 248</ref> Once he arrived at [[Papal throne]], he decided to alleviate their condition by building a new prison.<ref name=bar248/> \n\nThe occasion for the construction was given a complaint by the English College, which protested the pontifical intention to confiscate houses of the College to enlarge the prisons of Corte Savella.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> Virgilio Spada, \"deputato sopra la Congregazione delle Carceri di casa Giulia\" and brother of Cardinal [[Bernardino Spada|Bernardino]], had the [[Construction surveying|survey]] of Corte Savella carried out and commissioned Del Grande to draw up a restructuring project, but Innocent X decided to build a new prison between Via Giulia, the Tiber and Piazza Padella.<ref name=delGrandeDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/antonio-del-grande_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Antonio Del Grande|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Manfredo|last=Tafuri|volume=36|year=1988|language=it}}</ref>\nThis jail replaced those that had existed until then in the city: ''Tor di Nona'' in [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], ''Corte Savella'' in Regola, and [[Palazzo del Governatore di Borgo|the jail]] in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]].<ref name=pie7913/> The ''Carceri Nuove'' were the first example in Rome of modern [[penitentiary]], where the humanity of the inmates was placed at the centre of the penitentiary system. <ref name=pie7913/> The philosophy that animated this house of punishment is also underlined by the [[inscription]] placed on the front door:<ref name=pie7913/> \n\n{{quote|'''IVSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE / SECVRIORI AC MITIORI REORVM CVSTODIAE / NOVVM CARCEREM / INNOCENTIVS X PONT. MAX / POSVIT / ANNO DOMINI / MDCLV'''}}\n\n{{quote|Innocent X [[Pontifex_maximus#Catholic_Church_use_of_the_title|Pontifex Maximus]] erected [[in the year of the Lord]] 1655 the new prison for justice, for clemency and for a safer and more humane custody of the guilty}}\n\nWhen the pope died in January 1655 the building was not yet completed; his successor [[Alexander VII]] (r. 1655-1667) completed its construction, but  before its inauguration the edifice was used during the [[Naples Plague|1656 plague]] epidemic as ''stufa'' (from the German word ''stube'', it was something between a Roman bath and a modern sauna, very popular in Rome at that time) where those who were in [[quarantine]] in [[San Pancrazio]] and [[Sant'Eusebio]] were washed.\n\nThe inmates were continuously assisted by members of the [[Archconfraternities]] of [[Church of San Giovanni della Pigna|San Giovanni della Pigna]], the ''[[Assumption of Mary|Assunta]]'' at [[Church of the Ges\u00f9|the Ges\u00f9]] and [[San Girolamo della Carit\u00e0]]. <ref name=bar248/> The ''Carceri Nuove'' remained operative until the inauguration of the ''Regina Coeli'' Prison at Via della Lungara, being used for preventive custody. \nAfter that, only minors were kept there.<ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> In 1931 the edifice became the seat of the ''Centro per Studi Penitenziari'' and the ''Museo di Criminologia''.<ref name=pie7914/> Later the building became the seat of the ''United Nations Research Institute for Social Defence''. <ref name=pie7914/> Now (2020) it houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Anti-Mafia and Counter-Terrorism Directorate\").\n\n==Architecture and Organization==\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Portal.jpg|thumb|The severe portal of the Carceri Nuove on Via Giulia]]\nThe building, considered until the 18th century a model humanitarian prison, was designed by Del Grande following a detailed program of Virgilio Spada and keeping in mind the prisons of Tordinona.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> It was organized in two blocks: the one of the representations and the parlors, on Via Giulia, and the one of the dungeons towards the Tiber; the two bodies are connected by a gallery open on the side courtyards.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> It is possible that the planimetric shape - similar to a sword coming out of a [[hilt]] - is the allegory either of the justice of Pope Innocent or of Virgilio Spada (\"Sword\" in English), superintendent of the construction.<ref name=delGrandeDbi/>\n\nThe building is built in bricks with [[overhang]] in rustic [[travertine]] or [[stucco]].<ref name=pie7913/> It has 4 floors with 6 windows each on the main facade along Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7914/> On the ground floor the windows are rectangular and equipped with [[grille]]s. <ref name=pie7913/> At the center of the ground floor there is a strongly [[taper ratio|tapered]]  [[portal (architecture)|portal]] with at the center of the [[lintel]] a large [[Rustication (architecture)|bugna]] surmounted by the [[inscription]] cited  above.<ref name=pie7914/> The imposing building is concluded by a large groove [[cornice]].<ref name=delGrandeDbi/> \n\nInside the building there are two courtyards and a large staircase, but the floors are five.<ref name=pie7914/> \nOn the ground floor lay the rooms where men and women were interrogated, the lodgings of the caretakers, the chancellery, the services, a courtyard for the walk, two ''larghe'' (large rooms) for those accused of serious crimes, two punishment chambers, a juvenile prison and a chapel.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\nOn the first floor there were: two ''larghe'' for those accused of minor crimes; rooms for civilians accused of petty crimes; a room for [[Roman Jews|Jews]]; the archive and a second chapel.<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nOn the second floor lay a room reserved for the so-called ''visita graziosa'' (\"gracious visit\") of the commission for the welfare of inmates set up in 1435 under [[Pope Eugene IV]] (r. 1431-1447):<ref name=pie7914/> then there was the [[chaplain]]'s room, the ''conforteria'' (the place where those condemned to death received the comforts of religion), a chapel for those condemned to the death penalty and an isolation room for those sick of [[mange]].<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nThe third and fourth floors were occupied by seventeen [[dungeon]]s, each one bearing the name of a [[Saint (Catholic)|saint]].<ref name=pie7914/> They were accessed through very low doors, and each one was illuminated by a narrow window at the top protected by a double grille.<ref name=pie7914/>. \n\nIn the women's sector there were three ''larghe'' on the first floor and three dungeons on the second floor, the chapel, the infirmary and the apartment of the ''[[Prior|Priora]]''.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\nUntil the [[pontificate]] of [[Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) the prisons had also chambers for the clergymen; afterwards, these were imprisoned in special rooms in [[Castel Sant'Angelo]].<ref name=pie7914/> In 1824 a large kitchen was built on the ground floor, while the women's prison was extended to the second floor.<ref name=pie7914/> \n\nIn 1842 the ''Carceri Nuove'' housed 680 inmates, 600 men and 80 women.<ref name=pie7914/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Baronio, Cesare\n | title=Descrizione di Roma moderna\n | publisher=M.A. and P.A. De Rossi, Roma\n | language=Italian\n | year=1697\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Coord|41|53|50.18|N|12|28|1.38|E|display=title}}\n[[Category:Rome R. VII Regola]]\n[[Category:1655 establishments in the Papal States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Rome]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Alessandro57", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carceri_Nuove_(Rome)"}
{"title_page": "Mary Hawton", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian tennis player}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                  = Mary Hawton\n|fullname              = \n|image                 = \n|caption               = \n|country               = {{flagu|Australia}}\n|residence             = \n|birth_date            = {{birth date|df=yes|1924|9|4}}\n|birth_place            = [[Sydney]], Australia\n|death_date            = {{death date and age|df=yes|1981|1|18|1924|9|4}}\n|death_place            = [[Sydney]], Australia\n|height                = \n|college               = \n|turnedpro             = \n|retired               = \n|plays                 = Right-handed\n|careerprizemoney        = \n|tennishofyear           = \n|tennishofid            = \n|website                = \n|singlesrecord           = \n|singlestitles           = \n|highestsinglesranking       = \n|currentsinglesranking       = \n|AustralianOpenresult       = SF (1948, 1952, 1953, 1954, 1956, 1959)\n|FrenchOpenresult         = 4R (1960, 1962)\n|Wimbledonresult          = 4R (1958)\n|USOpenresult           = QF (1957)\n|doublesrecord           = \n|doublestitles           = \n|highestdoublesranking       = \n|currentdoublesranking       = \n|grandslamsdoublesresults     =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult    = '''W''' (1946, 1954, 1955, 1956, 1958)\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult      = F (1958)\n|WimbledonDoublesresult        = F (1957)\n|USOpenDoublesresult        = SF (1957, 1958, 1960)\n|OthertournamentsDoubles      = \n|MastersCupDoublesresult      = \n|WTAChampionshipsDoublesresult   = \n|OlympicsDoublesresult       = \n|Mixed               = \n|mixedrecord            = \n|mixedtitles            = \n|AustralianOpenMixedresult     = '''W''' (1958)\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult       = QF (1960, 1962)\n|WimbledonMixedresult       = 3R (1957, 1960)\n|USOpenMixedresult         = 2R (1957)\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles   = \n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult     = \n}}\n'''Mary Renetta Hawton''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Bevis'''; 4 September 1924 \u2013 18 January 1981) was a tennis player from Australia. Her career spanned the end of the 1940s and the 1950s.\n\nHawton won the women's doubles title at the [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] five times.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Open players archive \u2013 Mary Beavis|url=http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/players/1104.html|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Open players archive \u2013 Mary Hawton|url=http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/players/10254.html|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref> In 1958 she also won the mixed doubles title together with compatriot [[Robert Howe (tennis)|Robert Howe]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Open Winners|url=http://www.tennisnow.com/Tournaments/Grand-Slam-Winners/Australian-Open.aspx|publisher=TennisNow.com|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, she married Keith Ernest Hawton.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17982165 |title=Tennis Champions Engaged. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=14 May 1946  |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141345203 |title=Gossip From Joan. |newspaper=[[Wellington Times]] |location=NSW |date=25 October 1948 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShe was captain of the Australian [[Fed Cup]] team in 1979 and 1980 and director of the NSW Tennis Association.\n\nIn 1979 Hawton published a book titles ''How to Play Winning Tennis''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=How to play winning tennis|publisher=Worldcat|year=1979|oclc=630558374}}</ref> She died on 18 January 1981 in Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article125648026 |title=In Brief Death of Tennis Pioneer. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=20 January 1981 |page=18 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Mary Hawton Trophy, the prize for the winner of the Australian teams championships for girls, was named after her,<ref>{{cite web|title=December Showdown|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Fact-Sheet-Optus-12s-14s-Teams-Championships-2012.pdf|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref> as is Hawton Place, in the Canberra suburb of [[Chisholm, Australian Capital Territory|Chisholm]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/page/25600601|title=Commonwealth of Australia Gazette. Periodic (National : 1977 - 2011) - 15 May 1987 - p3|website=Trove|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMary Hawton found much success in Australia at the [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]]. She made it to the semifinals in singles six times in [[1948 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1948]], [[1952 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1952]], [[1953 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1953]], [[1954 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1954]], [[1956 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1956]] and [[1959 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1959]]. Hawton reached 12 finals in Australia, eight of these being consecutive. She also reached the doubles finals at the Wimbledon and French Championships in [[1957 Wimbledon Championships|1957]] and [[1958 French Championships (tennis)|1958]] with Australian [[Thelma Coyne Long]]. Mary Bevis Hawton ended her career with six Grand Slam titles: five in women's doubles and one in mixed doubles.\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n===Doubles: 14 (5\u20139)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:190px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:190px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:140px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win || 1946 || Australian Championships || Grass || {{